{"year": 1975, "entry_id": "T1", "patch": {"authors_raw": "McNaughton, C.", "abstract": "Efficacy Granule cell response to perforant path stimulation was found to fluctuate with an apparent circadian rhythm. Since both spike and EPSP components of the evoked potential covaried in time, the effect is probably a synaptic phenomenon. Circadian synapses in the CNS could account for diurnal shifts in behavioral probability patterns."}}
{"year": 1975, "entry_id": "T20", "patch": {"title": "A Case of Meridional Aniseikonia", "authors_raw": "Mitchell, D."}}
{"year": 1975, "entry_id": "T4", "patch": {"title": "Kinetics of the Topographic Regulation in the Neural Re-connections Between the whole Retina and a Half-Tectum in Goldfish", "authors_raw": "Yoon, M.G.", "abstract": "If the caudal half of the tectum is excised in adult goldfish, visual projections from the ·1l1oleretina later becomes orderly compressed onto the remaining rostral half-tectum. It takes at least 33 days for the half-tectum to complete the topographic regulation into a ~hole."}}
{"year": 1975, "entry_id": "T43", "patch": {"title": "Chlordiazepoxide-Induced Teversal of an Amphetamine-Established Aversion: Non-Associative Effects", "authors_raw": "Riley, A. L.", "abstract": "Cappell and LeBlanc (1973) reported the reversal of an amphetamine- established aversion by chlordiazepoxide (CuZP). These results t•!ere explained in terms of the anti-puni sr,ment effect of CDZP on amphetamine-established behavior. The present report, however, suggests that this reversal is a function of the interaction betHeen increased thirst induced by CDZPand the insensitivity of a one-bottle test in measuring conditioned taste aversions."}}
{"year": 1975, "entry_id": "T6", "patch": {"authors_raw": "LoLordo, Vincent M. and Jacobs,  W. J. and Foree, Donald D."}}
{"year": 1976, "entry_id": "35", "patch": {"title": "The Amnesic Effect of ECS Reduced by Hydrocortisone", "abstract": "Injection of hydrocortisone into the~ prior to a passive avoidance training reduces the amnesic effect cf ECS given shortly after the training. It is probable that ECS produces ai-rmesia by preventing corti- costeroids from entering into the hippocampus to modify the neural activity :i.n the limbic sys ten."}}
{"year": 1977, "entry_id": "36", "patch": {"title": "Some Personal, Social, and Institutional Aspects of Rape", "authors_raw": "Renner, E. and Jusczyk, A.", "abstract": "A woman who has heen raped is often doubly victimized: first, by the act; and second, by the legal process, the medical examinatio~, tl1e social embarrassment, and the emotional stress which follows. We will describe an empirical approacl for deterJ11ining the level of social aware- ness, for t,nderstanding the personal stress of the victim, and for identifying the sources of disillusionment with the social and institutional response to rape. The focus of the research was designed to contribute to the public education, the personal counselling, and the social action functions of Halifax Rape Relief."}}
{"year": 1977, "entry_id": "6", "patch": {"title": "Differences Between Normal and \"Compressed\" Tecta Seen by Golgi Methods", "abstract": "Observations of \"compressed\" tecta after impregnations hy the Golgi-Ccx technique suggest an expansion cf the :.iendritic arbor of some tcctal elements. Studies in progress using the Rapid Golgi technique to identify the elements in.vol ved, and quantitative aspects of the presumed dend-.ri tic spread are disc:uss ed. Also, the implications of such an expan- sion are considered."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "3", "patch": {"title": "Growth of the Goldfish Optic Tectum", "abstract": "Goldfish grow throughout their lives; their brains grow also. It is apparent that this growth occurs through addition of new cells and by increases in size of existing cells. I will describe the post- natal growth of the tectal stratum periventriculare and show that most of the growth in this region occurs through enlargement of existing cells. In light of growth by cell addition in the retina, this form of tectal growth is difficult to understand. The occurrence of continu- ously shifting synaptic connections, and the implications of this phenomenon in an active, functioning animal, will be discussed."}}

