{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"title": "Changing-site Channels for Different Object Sizes.", "authors_raw": "Regan, K. Beverley D.", "abstract": "We previously reported psychophysical evidence for the exis- tence of a neural mechanism specifically sensitive to changin_£ object size. We now report that f~r narrow adapting stimuli, the changing- size specific threshold elevation is significant, providing the widths of the test and adapting stimuli do not differ by more than 0.5°. However, no significant elevation occurs for adapting stimuli wider than 1.5°. Further evidence that the changing-size channel is sensitive only to objects smaller than 1.5° is that aftereffects to changing size are explicable in terms of Waterfall effects at the moving edges when adapting stimuli are wider than 1.5°."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8", "patch": {"abstract": "Depending on the requirements of the situation, it is\nbelieved that an organism, such as a pigeon, can either remember a\nstimulus or a future behaviour required by the present stimulus. Honig\nhas shown that in situations in which a pigeon is only required to\nremember whether to peck or not, remembering occurs over longer inter-\nvals than are normally found with procedures which require the recall\nof a stimulus. The present research uses a procedure which also requires\nonly that the pigeon remember whether to respond or not, It is simpler\nthan those that have been used previously. Since this seems to produce\nas much recall in pigeons as Honig's procedure, this hypothesis is\nVO\"r2_<._ 9. B. Tansley & M. Regan - Estimation of the Sensitivity of FM Channels\n~ ..1 in the Human Auditory System.\nBecause of the high sensitivity of auditory mechanisms to\namplitude changes associated with frequency variations of an acoustic\nstimulus, the estimation of frequency-modulation sensitivity via a\n~,~ threshold method is often contaminated with input from channels selec-\n~'· / tively sensitive to changing amplitude. We propose a method whereby it\n~ v .-,1 appears possible to estimate the sensitivity of FM channels by\n_•;.,---trr \"titrating off'' the activity of AMchannels due to differential\nponses within the auditory system to equal amplitude frequency varia-\nre-\ntions. With this method, the sensitivity of the FM channel under test\n~-I 1_/:r-~l appears to be lower than previously reported.\nll--~J\nR. Douglas - Heterosynaptic Inhibition of Synaptic £1a~!icity.\nThere are two major inputs to the dentate area of the hippo-\ncampus. The perforant path fibers make excitatory synapses onto the\ngranule cells, and long-lasting increases in the effectiveness of these\nsynapses can be produced by high-frequency activation. The commissural ~\ninput has a predominately inhibitory effect on the granule cells, and\ndoes not appear to be modifiable. However, high-frequency activity\nalong it can completely prevent the enhancement of the perforant path\nsynapses. The commissural effect on synaptic plasticity can be disso-\nciated from its effects on cell discharge."}}
{"year": 1979, "entry_id": "18", "patch": {"title": "The Interaction of Retinal and Tectal Cells of Goldfish in Tissue Culture", "abstract": "In culture retinal ganglion growth can be seen to enter\npieces of tectal tissue but it is unclear what happens when this occurs\nwithout doing elaborate histological procedures. The difficulty in\ntissue culture arises in dissociating tectal cells, and then determining\nwhen a cell is living. Having made some progress in this, I wish to show\nsome results from early experiments combining retinal tissue and single\ntectal cells in vitro."}}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "11", "patch": {"abstract": "Are hospitalized children under stress? Does the existence of a\nplayschool in the hospital reduce this stress? In this initial study, the\nplay behaviour of hospitalized children was compared with that of children in\na daycare center. Differences in levels of play, social behaviour and\n\"emotional\" displays wi 11 be discussed.\n\nA. D. Moore. Scanning Electron Microscope Study of the Eye Disc in the Larval Fly.\nLarval diptera show no external indication of their adult features.\nHowever, early in development, cells within the body are sequestered away to\nform imaginal discs, which transform into such adult structures as genitalia,\nlegs, wings, eyes and antennae. A scanning electron microscope study was\nconducted on one of these discs, the eye disc, in the 3rd instar larva of\nthe housefly, Musca domestica."}}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "21", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Hollway, G. J. and Ozier, M."}}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "6", "patch": {"abstract": "Rats were depleted of hippocampal nor adrenaline by systemic\ninjection of reserpine or by 6-0H-dopamine destruction of the dorsal nor-\nadrenergic bundle. Verification was by radioenzymatic liquid scintillation\ncount. Brief high frequency electrical stimulation of perforant path fibers\nwas used to cause short-term and long-term potentiation of the synapses onto\ngranule cells as measured by the field potential response to test shocks in the\nperforant path. Short term potentiation of the field excitatory post-synaptic\npotential (EPSP) was unaffected by noradrenaline depletion whereas long-term\npotentiation of the EPSP was reduced by more than 50%."}}
{"year": 1983, "entry_id": "12", "patch": {"title": "Semantic Priming", "abstract": "The time-course of accessing information from semantic memory was investigated by preceding a target stimulus for a lexical decision (word-nonword) with a prfme word over a range (-40 to +640 msec) of temporal intervals. With respect to target words, the prime word was either semantically related, unrelated or neutral. Three sets of\nmaterials were used to vary the type of semantic relation (i.e.,\ncategorical, associative, or indirect) between the prime and target.\nGenerally, a related prime facilitated decision times to words, and an\nunrelated prime inhibited decision times, relative to the neutral\ncondition. The magnitude and time-course of these effects were different\nfor three sets of materials. We take all of these effects to have\nimplications for the nature of the retrieval mechanisms and structure of\nsemantic memory."}}
{"year": 1983, "entry_id": "28", "patch": {"title": "Context Effects in Approach-Withdrawal Behavior in the Pigeon: Part II"}}
{"year": 1984, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"abstract": "This research investigates hemispheric asymmetries in the perception and\nidentification of both positive and negative emotion. The main purpose\nwas to identify conditions under which an overall left visual field\nadvantage obtains for all emotion and those in which a dissociation is\nfound for positive and negative emotion. Pairs of faces were presented\nsuch that one face was presented to each visual field. The pairs\nconsisted of either happy and neutral or sad and neutral faces. Righ-\nhanded subjects were required to respond to the faces that 1) were more\nemotional, and 2) made them feel either better or worse. The dependent\nmeasures were the latency and accuracy of respones. The main finding was\nthat visual field asymmetries depended on the task requirements. When\nasked to respond to the more emotional face visual field differences\nvaried primarily as a function of the sex of the subject. However, both\nsexes showed an overall left visual field advantage for better and worse\njudgements. Support was not provided for the idea of differential\nhemipsheric specialization for positive and negative emotion. Results\nare discussed in light of previous findings suggesting that males and\nfemales tend to use different strategies in such tasks.\nK. Berridge\nTrigeminal Control Of Ingestive and Grooming Sequences.\nWe're currently examining sensorimotor interactions in the production of\ntaste-elicited fixed action patterns and grooming sequences in rats.\nWe're employing a trigeminal deafferentation procedure that eliminates\ntactile input from the face and mouth while preserving intact all motor\nefferent and gustatory afferent neurons. This study addresses two issues: 1) the role of non-taste afferent information in the assessment of food palatability, and 2) the role of tactile sensory feedback in the production of ingestive and grooming movements and sequences."}}
{"year": 1985, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"title": "Is the Concept of a Maternal Pheromone useful to explain the Attractiveness of Maternal Odours?", "abstract": "Studies of odour preferences were examined in an effort to·answer some\nquestions regarding the interpretation of such preferences as evidence\nfor a \"maternal pheromone\". Some odorous substances, in particular,\nfeces and ventral scent gland sebum, both of which are copiously produced\nby lactation females, are preferentially approached by preweanling pups.\nThe attractiveness of an odour to pups may, in part, be a function of the\nodour's saliency, its familiarity, or its similarity to other, already\nfamiliar odours. Unfamiliar odours can be made attractive by exposure,\nand familiarity with an odour seems to be both necessary and sufficient\nto increase the attractiveness of that odour, whether it is produced by a\nconspecific or not. Simple exposure has been shown to be effective in\nestablishing an odour as attractive but this attraction may be increased\nif conditioning contingencies are also present. Since the attractiveness\nof maternal odours can be explained simply by assessing the role of\nfamiliarity, the concept of a \"maternal pheromone\" is not necessary and\nis not parsimonious with the data. Furthermore, it is not successful in\nexplaining the modifiability of odour preferences through experience.\nR. Mistlberger & B. Rusak\nEffects of Paraventricular Nuclei Lesions on Entrainment of Circadian\nActivity Rhythms to Restricted Feeding in the Rat\nPeriodic food availability cycles (2h food - 22h fast) can entrain a\nvariety of circadian rhythms in rats. The phase angle of entrainment is\nsuch that these rhythms anticipate the daily mealtime; for example, the\nrat becomes active 2-3h before mealtime. The neural mechanisms mediating\nanticipatory, food entrainable rhythms are functionally and antomically\ndistinct from those controlling free running, light entrainable rhythms\nsince suprachiasmatic nuclei lesions abolish or severely disrupt free\nrunning but not food anticipatory rhythms, Previous attempts to localize\ncritical components of the food entrainment mechanism indicate that the\npineal and adrenal glands, the hypophysis and the ventromedial\nhypothalamus are non-essential. The present study investigates whether\nthe paraventricular nuclei (PVN) might be involved, in view of their\npurported role in the regulation of food intake and the preminence of\nfood intake over light in the phase control of certain PVN receptor\nrhythms. Circadian locomotor rhythms were monitored in 9 rats on\nrestricted food schedules (2h diurnal mealtime) for 2 weeks prior to and\n3 weeks after bilateral PVN ablation. Six rats displayed signs of\nobesity typically associated with PVN lesions. Anticipatory activity was\nmarkedly attenuated in 3 of these rats and largely unaffected in the\nremaining 6. The animals will be tested again after several months to\nassess the stability of this effect."}}
{"year": 1986, "entry_id": "15", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Nakajima, S."}}
{"year": 1986, "entry_id": "26", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Baker, F. A. and Yoon, M. G. and Benowitz, L. I."}}
{"year": 1987, "entry_id": "11", "patch": {"title": "Does Life Imitate Art?", "authors_raw": "", "abstract": "The development of perspective in children's drawings will be examined with an eye on the development of perspective in the history of Western art. Several experiments that examine one aspect of perspective in children's drawings -- how to draw occluded objects -- will be reported.\n  author = {Enns, J."}}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "32", "patch": {"title": "Context effects on discrimination of complex tones"}}
{"year": 1990, "entry_id": "11", "patch": {"title": "Is it sane to think of pain on the plane? Answers from the WHO", "abstract": "Pain transmission theories such as the gate control theory have been useful in enhancing our understanding of pain and have legitimized the role of psychological factors in pain. They have not however, provided any guidance to clinicians or researchers in how to assess pain. Because of the lack of an appropriate theoretical model pain assessment has not progressed as much as one of pain assessment that may provide a strategy for advancing pain assessment."}}
{"year": 1990, "entry_id": "22", "patch": {"title": "NoPain NoGain: Lookin~ back at Pain.", "abstract": "How ~ood were the ~ains? Treatment strategies for pain abound. Toe efficacy of these strategies is well documented: major review papers tell us this! Unfortunately, most of the reviews are flawed. In ten minutes, I will (1) review problems with the way researchers synthesize knowledge, (2) revive the adage, \"garbage in, garbage out\"-as it applies to methods of data collapsing, and (3) present a proposal to implement what I have facetiously called, \" A Best Evidence Critical Appraisal Meta-Analytic Synthesis\"**"}}
{"year": 1990, "entry_id": "35", "patch": {"title": "Orientatingof Visual Attention", "abstract": "Percpetion of a visual scene can be spatially selective in two senses. First,~ adjustments of gaze direction can be made to control which regions of the visual field are processed by the sensitive fovea and its associated neural machinery. Second,~ adjustments can be made in which specific objects or regions are selected ( in the absence of gaze changes) for preferential treatment. Overt and covert visual orienting can be controlled exon~nously by features of the visual scene as well as endo&enously by the observer's expectations and intentions. Imagine the 2x2 matrix implied by this classification. In this talk I will concentrate on the cells representing endogenous and exogenous control are quite different. This might be interpreted to imply that two different attentional systems are involved. Alternatively, a single attentional system might bring different resources or strategies to bear depending on the nature of the control signal."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "1", "patch": {"title": "The evolution of avian imitation", "authors_raw": "Moore, Bruce", "abstract": "1. The ability to imitate movements, previously demonstrated clearly only among \"higher\" mammals (certain primates and cetaceans), is shown in a psittacine bird. The animal, a Grey Parrot (Psittacus erithacus) uses its feet, wings, head, beak and tongue in unambiguous imitation of human movements 2. Several lines of evidence suggest that the bird's imitation is not homologous to that in mammals. The process therefore seems to have evolved at least twice. 3. A \"new\" form of imitative learning, non-vocal mimicry, in which bodily movements are used to create mimetic sounds, is tentatively identified in passerine and psittacine birm. 4. Hierarchical and phylogenetic relationships suggest that the evolutionary path of avian imitation has been: Song/call learning --vocal mimicry -- non-vocal mimicry -movement imitation."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "15", "patch": {"title": "Things that go jump in the dark", "abstract": "Compared vernier and step displacement acuities in human foveal vision. When test and reference stimuli were of the same contrast, vernier thresholds were lower than step thresholds. For opposite-contrast stimuli, vernier thresholds increased four-five fold but step thresholds by very little. Further evidence was found demonstrating the difference between spatial and temporal visual mechanisms. Preliminary data obtained in a cat subject are also shown."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "19", "patch": {"title": "Interaction between 01 and 02 dopaminergic receptors in self- stimulation of the lateral hypothalamus in the rat", "authors_raw": "Lau, Chin and Nakajima, S."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "23", "patch": {"title": "Temporal auditory processing deficits in developmental dysphasia", "abstract": "The most comprehensive, if somewhat controversial, account of developmental dysphasia is Tallal's. Briefly, she argues that the speech reception deficit is due to an auditory temporal processing disorder: the disordered mechanism is thought to be cortical in locus, and to affect the perception of both linguistic and nonlinguistic sounds. The most compelling demonstration of the impairment lies in the inability of these children to discriminate the order of two brief (75 ms) tone pulses if the duration of the silent period between them is less than 100 to 300 ms, a task which normals perform with near-perfect accuracy for inter-stimulus intervals as small as O ms. The intended connotation of the term \"temporal processing\" is, however, far from clear in Tallal's published work. By the same token, nothing is known about the generality of any deficit across auditory perceptual dimensions that have their origins in different forms of time-related or time- dependent sound processing. In this talk, I will present sketches of two of a long series of experiments, based on modem auditory neuroscience, that we have planned to address these lacunae."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "26", "patch": {"title": "Children's reasoning for prediction of human actions: Developmental studies", "abstract": "We study young (2-5 years old) children's cognitive development with respect to their abilities to make appropriate predictions of a protagonist's actions and to explain their own judgements. Four brief movies are designed to test (1) \"Simple Desire Reasoning\", (2) \"Belief/Desire Reasoning\", (3) \"Descepant Belief Reasoning\", and (4) \"False Belief Reasoning\" (Wellman & Woolley, 1990; Pemer, 1990) as follows: [a] Let a child (the subject) assume an active role of 'explainer' who tells his/her addressee (the experimenter) what is going on in a test story enacted in the movie that the child has been watching (instead of being passive observer of the test situation presented by the experimenter). Then the experimenter asks the child to predict what the protagonists in the movie will do. [b] Video-recording of all utterances and communicative gestures produced by the chidren and the experimenter during the entire discursive organizations as well as for their lexico-syntactic structures and semantic cohesion. These analyses will reveal not only the cognitive abilities of the children for different types of reasoning but also their pragmatic competence in communicating their thoughts and emotions at various stages of their develoment [c] Longitudinal studies with individual children (2 to 5 years old) to denote the individual patterns of developmental changes through consecutive tests."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28", "patch": {"title": "Attention and express saccades"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "3", "patch": {"title": "Pigeons discriminate uniform from mixed arrays of visual elements", "abstract": "One property of an array of visual elements is the degree of uniformity -- the extent to which the elements are all the same, or mixed. Pigeons were trained to respond to uniform arrays of two kinds of elements, and not to respond to mixed arrays of the same elements. We obtained orderly gradients that reflected the degree of uniformity (or mixture). This discrimination is sensitive to the discriminability of the elements. It can be transferred between different sets of elements following appropriate training procedures."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "30", "patch": {"title": "Neuropsychological assessment of subcortical dementia in Huntington's Disease"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "32", "patch": {"title": "Pigeon umwelt: Is a picture worth a thousand words?"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34", "patch": {"title": "Symmetry and orientation normalization in the recognition of naturalistic stimuli"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "38", "patch": {"title": "Integration of kinematic information in emotional judgments", "abstract": "Adults rated the happiness/sadness of 36 short film excerpts of a person whose facial and body movements varied from excerpt to excerpt. There were three different facial expression (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by mouth position and eye focus) and three different body movement patterns (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by position and rate of limb movement) combined factorially. The influence of both sources of information on ratings was highly significant and in the manner predicted. Thus, emotional meaning can be communicated by multidimensional kinematic information. Results are compared with those from preschool children."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "41", "patch": {"title": "Neurological and psychosocial predictors of mental health in patients with Multiple Sclerosis", "abstract": "In the initial study of an ongoing project investigating quality of life and psychosocial functioning in MS patients, 89 subjects from the Dalhousie MS Research Clinic were assessed. Scores on the Mental Health Inventory were used as the dependent measure in a multiple regression analysis that included measures of social support, fatigue, responsiveness to stress, physical handicap, neurological disability, duration of disease and disease activity. Results indicate that social support and fatigue are important issues for MS patients. These two factors alone accounted for 44.8% of variance in Mental Health scores of the total sample. Furthermore, standard status meaures of neurological disability and physical handicap were not significant predictors of Mental Health status in MS patients."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42", "patch": {"title": "Localization of cholinergic and nerve growth factor-receptor neurons projecting to the suprachiasmatic nucleus of the rat"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "44", "patch": {"title": "Imagination and social understanding", "abstract": "It has been claimed that social understanding is achieved not so much through the development and application of a \"theory of mind\" but through the ability to pretend or imagine self in situations appropriate to another time or person. In this paper, I discuss recent work of ours on social reasoning tasks, in which children's judgements have to be made either from a third-person perspective or from an imagined first-person perspective. Initial results seem to support the idea that imagined or pretend contexts facilitate social reasoning."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "47", "patch": {"title": "Cholinergic and aminergic inputs from the mesopontine area to the basal forebrain and thalamus: A hypothesis for brainstem involvement in cortical arousal", "abstract": "Researchers of behavioral states have investigated the role of specific direct and indirect cholinergic inputs of the basal forebrain and mesopontine tegmental cholinergic areas in the regulation of waking and sleep. This study examines the contribution of tegmental cholinergic, serotonergic and dopaminergic cell groups in modulating the activity of both thalamic and basal forebrain neurons in cortical arousal. Following multiple injections of both FITC beads into the basal forebrain, and Fluorogold into the thalamus, alternate sections from the forebrain and brainstem were processed for immunohistochemistry with antibodies to visualire cholinergic and aminergic neurons. Injection sites were plotted and alternate brainstem sections were surveyed for the presence of triple labeled neurons."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "51", "patch": {"title": "Studies of ambiguous pitch: Direction and reaction time measures", "abstract": "In line with our interest in the representation of sequential patterns, listeners judged the pitch direction of pairs of randomly selected Shepard tones (synthesized from 10 consecutive octave components with amplitude envelope peaking over central components) from the set of 12 semitones in the octave. Direction judgments were consistent for short absolute distances between tones and were bivalent for distances of 5- 6 semitones. Reaction time data and the pattern of directions preceding ambiguous intervals reveals whether ambiguous pitch is disambiguated by preceding redundant directional patterns."}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "52", "patch": {"abstract": "The marvels of mouse movements provide the inspiration for this projecL The small but sophisticated brains of these little beasts enable them to articulate beautifully coordinated actions. These, as other animal (and human) actions, challenge us to think carefully about how mammalian brains achieve their essential balance between isolable operations and the rules of combination in space and time among these operations. We shall treat the troops with our first attempts to employ benign developmental analyses of neurological mutant strains to examine fundamental problems of pattern formation in behavioral organization. The data are preliminary, but you'll love our mice!"}}
{"year": 1992, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"title": "EXPRESSION OF C-FOS IN THE ACCESSORY OLFACTORY SYSTEM OF JUVENILE FEMALE MICE AFTER EXPOSURE TO MALE-SOILED BEDDING", "authors_raw": "Schellinck, Heather and Smyth, Cathy and Brown, Richard and Wilkinson, Michael", "abstract": "Exposure to the urine or soiled bedding odours of novel adult males is known to\naccelerate puberty in juvenile female mice. To determine what part of the olfactory\nsystem is activated by these odours, the expression of cf os in the main olfactory\nbulb (MOB) and the accessory olfactory bulb (AOB) of juvenile female mice was\nexamined after their exposure to male-soiled bedding, peppermint extract or their\nown bedding. Well defined immunoreactivity was found throughout the AOB of the\njuvenile female mice exposed to the bedding odours of adult males for 3 and 12\nhours. In contrast, dense fos staining was found in the granular cell layer of the\nMOB of mice exposed to peppermint odours for 3 or 12 hours. Of the mice\nexposed to their own bedding for 3 or 12 hours, none showed immunostaining for\nfos in the AOB; slight or no staining was observed in the MOB. These data indicate\nthat social odours activate fos in the AOB while non-social odours activate the\nMOB."}}
{"year": 1993, "entry_id": "P10", "patch": {"title": "GENDER DIFFERENCES IN THE CONSTRUCT VALIDITY OF TWO HOSTILITY MEASURES", "abstract": "Objective: To detennine the construct validity of the Ho subscale of the MMPI and the structured interview method (SI) of hostility measurement while examining gender differences. Design: Correlational Setting: University Participants: From an introductory psychology class. Mean age of nineteen. 54 male and 87 female volunteers were used. Interventions: Subjects were given a standard structured interview and asked to fill out the Ho scale and the PANAS negative affect (NA) scale. Measures: Two tailed t-tests were used to compare means of males with females. Simple correlations and intercorrelations between Ho and SI measures were used. Results: For females 9% of the variance (r=.30) in scores on the Ho scale were accounted for by variability of scores on the NA scale. No significant variability in PH scores was accounted for by NA scores in females. In males, 11% of the variance (r=.34) in scores on the Ho scale were accounted for by variability in NA scores. Scores of PH accounted for an additional 33% of variability in Ho scores in males. Conclusions: It appears that Ho and SI methods of hostility assessment are not measuring the same construct for females, but have high construct validity for males. Rater-reliability and other possible confounding factors for the female hostility data will be presented. There are significant gender differences in expression of hostility."}}
{"year": 1993, "entry_id": "P2", "patch": {"title": "RESPONSE COMPETITION CONTRIBUTES TO THE EFFECTS OF ORIENTATION WHEN LOCATING THE TOP OR BOTTOM OF ROTATED OBJECTS", "abstract": "The time to determine if a dot is located near the top or bottom pole of rotated objects increases linearly for rotations up to 120 deg. This effect has been linked to a similar effect of orientation found for rotated object naming. However, different causes for these effects may be inferred if it was shown that they were panly due to response compatibility in the top-bottom discrimination task. Results from this task showed that responses to dots at the top were faster than those to dots at the bottom of the screen. This effect was additive with the effects of object orientation. However, compatibility between location of the dot on the screen and response was confounded with object orientation. Objects near upright orientations were confounded with compatible responses and objects at more extreme orientations were confounded with incompatible responses. To determine if response compatibility accounted for some of the effects of orientation during top-bottom discriminations, \"top\" and \"bottom\" keys were positioned horizontally or vertically. Vertical key placement, which was thought to improve response mapping, resulted in a greater effect of orientation than horizontal placement The effects of orientation during top-bottom discriminations may partially reflect response competition, suggesting these orientation effects are not reflective of those found during rotated object naming."}}
{"year": 1993, "entry_id": "T19", "patch": {"abstract": "The \"touch screen\" provides a sensitive method for assessing the discrimination of complex arrays of elements. Pigeons were trained to peck at one side of a randomized array when there were more blue than red elements, and at the other side with the opposite proportions. This yielded orderly maintained discriminations of response location based on relative numerosity. Corresponding results were obtained when pigeons had to respond to the left side when uniform arrays were presented, and to the right side when other, mixed proportions were shown. This general method has the advantage that the different elements are equally associated with reinforcement during training."}}
{"year": 1993, "entry_id": "T7", "patch": {"title": "THE PSYCHOSOCIAL AND PHYSICAL PREDICTORS OF ADOLESCENTS' RECOVERY FROM ORAL SURGERY", "abstract": "This study expanded medical models of prediction and outcome related to surgery in adolescents. Fifty two adolescents undergoing 3rd molar surgery participated. Adolescents' negative affectivity, expectancies, coping styles and illness behavior encouragement were assessed before surgery. Extent of surgery was assessed by the oral surgeon. Outcome measures included resumption of initial mouth opening, disability and pain. After controlling for extent of surgery, the psychosocial parameters accounted for 16% of the variance in mouth opening and 24% of the variance in disability. Extent of surgery did not predict recovery. Expectancies had an independent and significant association with recovery. Gender effects masked associations between some predictors and recovery. Adding pain as a predictor more than doubled the variance explained in disability. Expectancies about recovery should be included in models of adolescents' recovery from surgery. Interventions which modify pessimistic expectancies and improve pain treatment may enhance recovery."}}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "P9", "patch": {"title": "STRESS AND ALCOHOL PREFERENCE", "abstract": "Volpicelli, Ulm, and Hopson (1990) found that rats given a choice between 5% ethanol and water in the home cage showed enhanced ethanol preference following four daily 1-hr sessions of inescapable shock in another environment, relative to a no-treatment control. We attempted to replicate this effect including a shocked group, a no-treatment control, and a group taken to the distinctive environment each day but not shocked. Our baseline ethanol preferences were much higher than theirs, 0.55 versus 0.35. Additionally, whereas their ethanol preferences increased from baseline to shock to post-shock phases, our ethanol preferences decreased over phases, especially in the no-treatment group. In the second replication, the pattern of results was the same, although baseline preferences were like those of Volpicelli et al. Thus we did not replicate the stress effect on alcohol consumption observed by Volpicelli et al. Additional research aimed at resolving this discrepancy is in progress."}}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T11", "patch": {"title": "--  OLFACTORY AND TASTE ABILITIES IN PRE- AND POSTPARTUM WOMEN"}}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T2", "patch": {"title": "LINE BISECTION AND VISUAL ORIENTATION ERRORS ALONG HORIZONTAL AND VERTICAL PLANES IN PERIPERSONAL AND EXTRAPERSONAL SPACE IN PATIENTS WITH VISUOSPATIAL NEGLECT: A PROPOSAL", "abstract": "In recent years, line bisection and visual orientation studies of visuospatial\nneglect have been prolific, but the evidence provided has been fixed by\nphysical limitations and methodological moderations. Line bisections are\nperformed manually and are confined to peripersonal space. Thus,\nknowledge of visuospatial deficits outside of arm's reach (e.g., extra-\npersonal space) is missing. Similarly, the visual orientation task is carried\nout by comparing responses along a left-right continuum. Thus,\ninvestigation of visuospatial neglect along multiple planes is absent. The\npurpose of the present study will be twofold. First, it proposes to\ninvestigate line bisection and visual orientation errors along horizontal and\nvertical planes in peripersonal and extrapersonal space. Second, a model\nexplicating line bisection errors is missing. It is suggested that the\ntheoretical framework of the visual orientation task may provide an\nopportunity to funher elucidate on mechanisms of line bisection errors.\nThus, the present study intends to illuminate mechanisms underlying\nbisection errors by comparing displacement errors on line bisection to errors\non a visual orientation task. A proposal outlining the background and\nresearch plan will be presented."}}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T4", "patch": {"title": "HOW CAN WE DETERMINE IF ATTENTION IS THE GENERATOR RESPONSIBLE FOR ILLUSORY LINE DRAWING?", "abstract": "Two circles, separated by 4° are displayed on a screen. One briefly brightens and then a line connecting the two circles is added to the display. Although the line appears instantaneously, the subject's subjective experience is that the line is \"drawn\" from the flashed circle toward the unchanged one. The flashed circle does attract the observer's attention, and Shimojo, who discovered this line drawing illusion, attributes it to the locus of attention. Alternatively, the illusion might depend on purely visual mechanisms activated by the stimulus, such as those associated with apparent motion. We plan to compare the strength of the illusion under conditions of exogenous (externally generated, e.g. following abrupt peripheral luminance increment) and endogenous (internally generated, e.g. following verbal instruction) control over attention. Our first step was to determine if the line drawing illusion could be cancelled by presenting a line that WAS drawn over time in the direction opposite to the illusory motion."}}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "P4", "patch": {"abstract": "Women frequently report changes in odor and taste perception during pregnancy. Despite the potential such changes have in modifying food intake--thereby affecting nutritional health--there are a scarcity of comprehensive, well-designed studies examining the specific nature and direction of smell and taste alterations associated with pregnancy. In this prospective, controlled, longitudinal study, 64 women (32 pregnant subjects, 32 control subjects) will be assessed four times over a nine month period: (1) 6-10 weeks postconception (middle of first trimester); (2) 14-18 weeks postconception (middle of second trimester); (3) 28-32 weeks postconception (early to middle of third trimester); and (4) 4-8 weeks postpartum. Non-pregnant women will be tested at approximately equivalent intervals from the time of their first assessment and at consistent times during the early part of their menstrual cycle. Alterations in smell and taste will be assessed using a battery of objective psychophysical tests, questionnaires, rating scales, and diet records designed to measure the following: (a) odor and taste thresholds; (b) odor and taste identification; (c) qualitative ratings of odor and taste preference, familiarity, intensity, arousal, and palatability; (d) odor-evoked memories; (e) the development of food cravings and aversions; and (f) the preferences of the smells and tastes of non-food items. For the pregnant women, test battery results will be correlated with their serum honnone levels of estradiol, progesterone, human chorionic gonadotropin, oxytocin, and prolactin in an effort to reveal hormonal influences on the smell and taste senses. Additionally, the degree of pregnancy sickness during the first trimester will be assessed and will be correlated with performance on the perceptual tests. We hypothesize that changes in smell and taste perception during pregnancy may be the sensory mechanism underlying food cravings and aversions. We also hypothesize that during early pregnancy superior smell and taste performance should be positively correlated with the degree of severity of pregnancy sickness. These hypotheses are based on the theory that pregnancy sickness is a maternal evolutionary adaptation designed to avoid the ingestion of naturally occurring toxins, thus protecting the embryo from exposure to potentially harmful substances. A potential application of this research will be to help provide a rational basis for updating the nutritional guidelines available to pregnant women."}}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T26", "patch": {"abstract": "In recent decades, attentional biases along three-dimensional spatial coordinates have been a topic of increased interest. However, physical boundaries, as well as methodological restraints have precluded a thorough and systematic investigations of human performances along these planes. The currentstudy proposed to address some of these limitations by investigating line bisection and visual orientation performances along horizontal and vertical planes in peripersonal (within hand's reach) and extrapersonal (outside of hand's reach) space. Subjects bisected a total of 72 computer-generated horizontal and vertical lines projected in each spatial location. Furthermore, on any given trial, horizontal lines appeared at the top, centre or bottom of the screen, while vertical lines appeared at the left, centre or right of the screen. As well, a bisecting cursor appeared at either end of each line. In the visual orientation task, subjects reponded to 229 validly or invalidly cued targets in each spatial location. On any given trial, targets appeared at the top left, top right, bottom left or bottom right of the screen. Overall, horizontal and vertical lines were bisected to the left and above the midpoint, respectively. Moreover, analyses of variance revealed that bisecting biases varied significantly in peripersonal and extrapersonal space contingent upon bisector and line position on the screen. Overall, subjects responded more quickly to validly than invalidly cued targets. Analyses of variance revealed that response time also varied significantly and differently along horizontal and vertical planes in peripersonal and extrapersonal space. These findings are discussed in light of current models of visual attention. ~ O.C.E.A.N. - ology 1-u Michael Wm. MacGregor and Karina Davidson The five-factor model is a taxonomy of ~rsonali~ traits in terms of five broad dimensions: Openness to Experience, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism. Although evidence suggests that these five factors are useful in studying and modelling normal personality, there is less consensus regarding their ability to model abnormal personality, particularly Eersonali!'.disorders. This study investigated the relationship between the five factor model ofpersonality and personality disorders. Two hundred and fifty undergraduate students completed the Personality Diagnostic Questionnaire-Revised (PDQ-R)as a measure of personality disorders and the Big Five Inventory (BFI-54) as a measure of the five factors of personalty. Results are discussed with respect to the theoretical relationship between personality disorders and the five factor model. 1'28. Channel Surfing Without A Remote Control Tracy L. Taylor(l), Dennis P. Phillips(l,2), & Susan E. Hall(l). Departments of Psychology(l) and Otolaryngology(2) In an auditory gap detection task, three highly practiced listeners were presented with pairs of noise stimuli. Each stimulus consisted of leading and trailing noise bursts which bordered a temporal gap interval: In the test stimulus, this gap interval was varied systematically; in the reference stimulus this gap interval was maintained at a duration of 1 msec and was inaudible. The subject made a forced choice manual discrimination to indicate which of the two randomly presented stimuli contained the test gap. The dependent variable of interest was the shortest temporal gap that could be detected reliably. Subjects performed this task under conditions in which the perceptual channel used to define the leading and trailing edges of the gap was manipulated with respect to central frequency and laterality. In other words, perceptual channels were defined according to frequency and ear, such that the leading and trailing noise hurts shared no or complete spectral overlap and were presented to the same or to different ears. Results demonstrated poorer gap detection for across-channel (>20 msec) than for within-channel(< 5 msec) conditions, indicating that having to extract temporal information across frequency or ear limits the ability to resolve a temporal gap. It is noted that the thresholds observed in the across-channels conditions could be responsible for the +20 to +40 msec voice onset time (VOT) that typically marks the categorical boundary between voiced and voiceless stop consonants."}}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T26", "patch": {"title": "Webicising Your Survey, or How To Adminster Surveys over the World Wide Web", "authors_raw": "Billy Schmidt", "abstract": "World Wide Web technology can act to decrease the amount of time, effort and costs incurred through survey research. Additionally, this medium opens one's subject pool to a much wider, or specialized, audience than can be accessed through conventional channels. This talk will introduce the audience to the requirements, methods, and potential problems that are encountered when carrying out survey research on the World Wide Web."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "P1", "patch": {"abstract": "Animal models of working memory have traditionally used a delayed matching-to-sample problem with visual or spatial stimuli. We have developed a more ethologically valid procedure to assess working memory in the rat using olfactory stimuli. 1bis task utilizes a go-left/go-right procedure and thus eliminates both the ambiguity of null responses inherent in the go/no go olfactory learning paradigm and the problem of mediating behaviours which plague other putative tests of working memory such as the delayed matching-to-position task (Stanhope et al., 1995, Psychopharmacology, 122, 268-280). Five rats were trained on a continuous delayed match/non match-to-sample (CDM/NMS) task in an operant olfactometer with four different delays (3, 30, 60, and 120 sec) between the sample and choice odors. The percent correct in this task decreased with increasing delay, indicating a working memory function and suggesting that this procedure is a good model for testing drugs which influence short-term memory. When a stable baseline level of performance was reached, the effect of the central muscarinic antagonist scopolamine hydrobromide (HBr) was assessed. Many experiments suggest that scopolamine has a detrimental effect on learning and memory processes (Smith,1988, Brain Research Reviews, 13, 103-118). However, other studies suggest that the effect of scopolamine may be due to something other than memory impairment (Herremans et al., 1996, Brain Research, 711, 102-111). We injected rats i.p. 30 minutes before testing on different days with one of five treatments: saline, 0.3 mg/kg scopolamine methylbromide (a peripherally acting muscarinic antagonist), 0.03 mg/kg scopolamine HBr, 0.1 mg/kg scopolamine HBr, and 0.3 mg/kg scopolamine HBr. There was a significant decrease in performance with increasing delays and a significant decrease in percent correct as the dose of scopolamine HBr was increased. There was no interaction between drug and delay. The general decrease in percent correct was interpreted as indicating an effect of scopolamine on a non-mnemonic process which influences performance in the CDM/NMS olfactory learning task. It is suggested that scopolamine induces a failure to attend to relevant information."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Yoon, Myong G. and Connolly, John F.", "abstract": "We studied the characteristic patterns of neural responses of the human brain to various combinations of semantic anomalies and/or verb inflectional disagreements during rapid reading of compound sentences by analyzing the event related brain potentials (ERP) recorded from normal adult subjects. [l] ERP of semantically anomalous verbs showed negative shifts peaking at about 400 msec (N400) with respect to the semantically appropriate verbs. The onset time of the N400 responses depended on the syntactic contexts of the verbs. [2] ERP of inflectionally incorrect verbs made positive shifts at about 600 msec (P600) with respect to control verbs. A repetition of the inflectional disagreement in the second clause diminished the P600 response. The result suggests that the repeated inflectional disagreement tends to be ignored by the neural mechanism which has responded to the previous inflectional disagreement as P600. [3] The predominant component of neural responses to semantically anomalous and inflectionally incorrect verbs was P600 rather than N400. Thus inflectional disagreement (rather than semantic anomaly) seems to be a predominant linguistic feature, detected by those neurons whose activities happened to be monitored by our recording methods. [4] Inter-sentential influence of the semantically anomalous transitive verb (with respect to its subject) upon its (acceptable) object; ERP to the object words of semantically anomalous verbs showed large negative shifts during a period between 300 and 750 msec. The magnitude and duration of the negative shift in the object word was far grater than that in the anomalous verb itself. The result reveals the prominent influence of the two diffemet sentential contexts on the same terminal words . [5] Inter-sentential influence of inflectional disagreement of semantically normal transitive verb upon its appropriate object in the second clause; ERP to the object words of the inflectionally incorrect normal verbs showed large negative shifts during a period beginning 300 msec. This large negative shift in the object words reflects the influence of the preceding inflectional relations between the subjects and the verbs in the compound sentences. Tl 7. Gender differences in anxiety sensitivity dimensions Stewart, S. H., Taylor, S., & Baker, J. M. The present study examined whether there are gender differences in the hierarchical factor structure of the Anxiety Sensitivity Index (ASI), and/or patterns of ASI factor scores. Principal components analyses on the ASI items of male (N =290) and female (N =528) students revealed nearly identical lower-order factor structures across genders (i.e., physical, psychological, and social concern factors). Nearly identical unidimensional higher-order solutions were also found across genders. Analyses on ASI lower-order factor scores showed that: females scored higher than males only on the physical concerns factor; females scored higher on the physical concerns factor than on the psychological and social concerns factors; and males scored higher on the psychological and social concerns factors than on the physical concerns factor. Females also scored higher than males on the higher-order ASI factor. The study provides support for the conceptual distinctions between the three lower-order ASI factors, as well as the first empirical demonstration of a hierarchical structure for the ASI. Men and women also appear to differ on AS dimensions in ways consistent with sex role socialization practices. Tl 8. Memory bias for food information in restrained eaters Anne Israeli and Sherry Stewart Research on cognitive patterns in individuals high in dietary restraint indicate an attention bias toward food related information (see Francis, Stewart, and Hounsell, in press). The cwrent study was conducted to see if restrained eaters show a memory bias for food words in comparison to animal words (control list) in relation to individuals low in restraint Thiny females (Mean age= 21.50, SD= 2.97) encoded a list of words (15 food, 15 animal) presented in an incidental learning task. Participants were then asked to freely recall as many words as they could remember and fill out questionnaires including the Restraint Scale (Herman & Polivy, 1980). Participants were classified as high in restraint (n=16) and low in restraint (n=14) on the basis of the scale. Preliminary analyses indicate that individuals high in restraint remember more food than animal words and individuals low in restraint do not demonstrate such a bias. The results support (Bemis-Vitousek & Hollon's (1990) theory that restrained eaters have highly organized cognitive structures (schema) which permit then to avoid dangers (food) in their environment"}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T34", "patch": {"abstract": "The Psychology Department home page officially went on the World-Wide Web on\nNovember 29th, 1996. The site lives on a server provided by the University Computing\nand Information Services, and a log is kept of all visits to the pages in the site. Every time a page is visited, information is logged about the visitor. In this talk, we'll have a look at\nwhat these \"footprints\" in the log tells us about who has visited the site, where they come\nfrom, and what gets looked at. Secret features of the Psychology site will be revealed. The\nfeedback features of the site will get special attention."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T37", "patch": {"abstract": "Given the lack of research quantifying pain during various dental hygiene procedures, pain and pain coping attempts were explored in 48 patients (27 male, 21 female) undergoing routine dental hygiene treatment Dental anxiety and self-efficacy of pain coping attempts were also explored in relation to pain. The majority of patients (79%) report none or very little pain during clinical procedures. In direct contrast, 21 % of sample reported pain scores that were extreme in comparison to the majority. Empathic discussions with the hygienist, self-distraction from the pain, and information seeking from the hygienist, were the most often employed pain coping strategies. In dividing the sample by pain reports (i.e., low and high pain), no group differences in regards to dental anxiety, age, education, brushing habits, or the degree of tre~tment difficulty were found. However, the low pain group flossed more (t=3.01, l2.,.<.005)and had greater levels of self-efficacy for pain coping attempts (t=2.28, l2.,.<.027)than did the high pain group. There were no differences in how many pain coping strategies were reported between low and high pain groups as well as low and high self-efficacy for pain coping. Results suggest that feelings of personal control during dental hygiene treatment may be a factor in successful pain management. Future research is discussed in terms of other trait-like cognitive factors such as pain catastrophizing. 18 Behaviors caregivers use to determine pain in non-verbal, cognitively impaired children Patrick J. McGrath, Christina Romos, Carol Camfield, Mary Ann Campbell, Allan Hennigar Primary caregivers of 20 children (age=14.5 years and language level=lO months) were recruited and interviewed to recall 2 instances of short sharp pain and 2 of longer-lasting pain and describe their child's behaviour. Transcribed interviews were reviewed and sets of non-overlapping items were developed. Thirty one behaviours were extracted from the interviews. The specific behaviors were often different from one child to another but the classes of behaviors (Vocal, Eating/Sleeping, Socia1/Personality, Facial Expression, Activity, Body & Limbs and Physiological) were common. Relibility of using the checklist on interviews was good (kappa=.77). The checklist has excellent content validity and will be useful for caregivers of cognitively-impaired, non-communicating children to report on pain behaviors."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Shimohigashi, I. M. and Meinertzhagen, I.A.", "abstract": "Gap junctions are the structural contacts that mediate electrical coupling between neurons in nervous systems. In vertebrates, gap junctions form from connexin proteins, but in invertebrates the corresponding proteins remain elusive. Recently, however, the shaking-B gene in Drosophila is suggested to encode a connexin-like protein, and mutants of shaking- B, including Passover, a null mutant with a defective escape jump, exhibit coupling defects. An antibody raised against the shak-B peptide expresses in the the lamina, where terminals of the eye's photoreceptors are electrically coupled by gap junctions. Compared with the wild type, there are significantly fewer (ca 20%) gap junctions in the shak-B mutant, but only in the upper levels of the lamina. At deeper levels, the numbers are smaller in both mutant and wild type, and both the same. Thus, the lamina's population of gap junctions is partitioned into at least two strata, and the numbers in the mutant imply the existence of at least two genetic factors, possibly proteins, encoding the number of gap junctions.  Neural Statistics, Human Failing, and the Backward Propagation of Error '1'45:- D.A. Santor This brief talk introduces the basics of neural networks and machine learning and illustrates how for some (if not many tasks) we're better off not relying on human judgement."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T47", "patch": {"abstract": "In vertebrates, the blood-brain barrier (BBB) is located in the brain capillary walls and stabilizes the brain's micro-environment, protecting it from potentially harmful incursions of blood chemicals, etc. The evolution of the barrier mechanism is not easy to study by comparative methods, since all known vertebrates have it. The other larger group of terrestrial colonizers, winged insects (Pterygota), also have a BBB with the same role at the surface of the CNS, and which extends out into the eye. In trying to trace its evolution, we have looked to see if the eye barrier is present in the more primitive wingless insects (Apterygota), from which pterygotes originally evolved back in the Paleozoic era. We collected Petrobius maritimus (jumping bristletails) of the most primitive extant apterygote family Machilidae (Archaeognatha) on the shore near Parrsboro. Compared to other apterygotes, they have very well developed compound eyes. A colony of about 40 has been kept successfully for about 6 months in the lab. Using microelectrodes to pressure-inject small fluorescent tracers into the haemolymph (blood) of the head. we observed that these dyes lit up the eyes within a few minutes of injection. Specimens fixed and sectioned showed that dye is indeed present in the eye, concentrating particularly in the outermost optical layer, the cornea, which could only have reached by diffusing up from the base of the eye. We are currently setting up to check this, using electron-microscope tracers. Next, bugs were injected on a tilt stand (goniometer) mounted directly on the microscope, allowing fluorescence emission from part of the eye surface to be measured optically in real time with a sensitive detector. The measured time profiles confirm that dye uptake is extremely rapid (tl/2 = 0.4 - 1.4 min), although it then disappears again from the eye. Finally, the path-length for diffusion into the eye has been measured and the expected diffusion profile modelled, from a solution to the diffusion equation for the case with no barrier. This predicts similar values of 11/2 (0.8 - 1.1 min) without further assumptions, confirming that the eye space must be completely open to the circulation. The situation in flies (advanced pterygotes) is quite different, with very slow penetration and loss of dyes. The key reason for the lack of a barrier in machilids may be the primitive stage of evolution of the tracheal system in the group, which needs upgrading before barriers cutting off the retina become feasible."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9", "patch": {"abstract": "The parasitic wasp Cotesiacongregatainjects its eggs into the larvae of the tobacco\nhorn worm, Manducasexta. Homworms were found to feed normally during the growth\nof the parasitic wasps. However, M. sexta stopped feeding several hours prior to the\nemergence of the wasp larvae. Hosts were not debilitated by the parasites and survived\nanother 2 weeks without feeding after the wasps emerged. In the field, unparasitized M.\nsexta ate C. congregatapupae (n=l0/10) suggesting that the suppression of host feeding\nprevents predation of the parasitic wasps by the host. The decline in host feeding correlated\nwith a long-lasting increase in the concentration of octopamine in the host's hemolymph\n(22.2 ± 2.1 pg/µL (n=7) to 143.7 ± 7.8 pg/µL hemolymph (n=16)). Injections of\noctopamine depressed feeding in unparasitized M. sexta. The wasp larvae were not the\nsource of the host's increased octopamine. Feeding was also temporarily depressed in M.\nsextaby injecting sephadex beads, bacteria (Serratiamarcescens)or lipopolysaccharides\n(derived from S. marcescens).In all 3 cases, octopamine concentration in the hemolymph\nincreased after injection (18.7 ± 4.2 to 54.7 ± 7.8 pg/µL hemolymph for bacteria-injected,\nn=lO)). Feeding resumed with the decline in octopamine levels. Sephadex beads, bacteria,\nlipopolysaccharides and the emerging wasp larvae all activate the host's immune system.\nThe data are consistent with the hypothesis that part of the parasite's ability to suppress\nhost feeding involves permanently activating mechanisms that suppress feeding during an\nimmune challenge.\nTl 0. Perceptions of movement\nJohn Fentress\nAnimal behavior is something of a mobile projective test, no matter how objective we try\nto be. What cues do we use, for example, to interpret the actions of other creatures? Part\nof the answer depends upon our measurement systems: \"What you measure is what you\nget!\" Of equal importance, measurements are inevitably incomplete and thereby can be\nfilled-in through often undefined expectations, biases, and the like. We have thus\nlaunched a pilot project in which standardized behavior tapes and computer representations\nof movement are presented to people under different settings. The results can be scary (as\nin scare, not scar). It is clear that: a) cues can be used in an idosyncratic manner, b)\nbackground events can change perceptions of behavior, and c) internal expectations of the\nobserver can dictate what is recorded, and how these recordings are interpreted. Certainly\nthe definition of objectivity must move beyond the position of shared bias. There may be a\nrich field for cognitive psychologists as well as ethologists to explore here. Suggestions\nare solicited.\n\nTl 1. Behavioral sequences in canids: a new perspective on the plasticity of\naction and movement patterns\nSimon Gadbois\nImportant dimensions of behavioral patterns may have been overlooked in the past because\nof (1) the species chosen, (2) the action patterns investigated and (3) the methods of\nanalysis selected. The issues of intentionality (control) and automaticity, plasticity and\nstereotypy, stochasticity and derterminism are reviewed in the light of new observations on\ncaching sequences in canids. I will also discuss the pertinence of the concept of intensity\npatterns in behavioral sequences, which are often ignored to the profit of seguential\npatterns. An analogy with prosody in linguistics is suggested for the development of future\nmodels of temporal organization of behavior."}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T36", "patch": {"abstract": "The fruitfly, Drosophila melanogaster, has long been used a vital tool for neuroscientific research of a genetic and anatomical nature. Because of its stereotypical pattern of development and its relatively simple nervous system, Drosophila is a powerful tool for understanding the relationship between gene and neurotransmitter expression and development. I will present several views of the development of this simple nervous system, considering how information about gene and neurotransmitter expression can be related to the actual anatomy of the developing CNS. Semi-thin sections of embryonic tissue have been serially aligned and, from these sections, I have developed a computerised, three-dimensional anatomical atlas of the Drosophila nervous system. Images of this atlas will be considered, alongside images produced via fluorescence immunohistochemistry and confocal microscopy. Behavioural Differences in MHC-Congenic Mice: The Step-Down Passive ~ Avoidance Test Tim Bredy, Will Moger and Richard Brown Although there are a multitude of physiological and pathological traits in which the major histocompatibility complex (MHC) might influence behaviour (lvanyi, 1978, Proc. R. Soc. Lond. B, 202, 117-158), MHC-congenic mice have primarily been tested for mate selection and individual recognition by odour (Yamazaki et al., 1976, J. Exp. Med.,144, 1324-34; Manning et al., 1992, Nature, 360,581-583). The present experiment investigated the possiblity that two strains of MHC congenic mice (C57Bl/6J vs. B6 H-2K) would differ in their ability to learn and remember a passive avoidance task. Glucocorticoids influence learning and memory (Smith, 1996, Beh. Brain Res., 78, 25-36) and there are strain differences in hippocarnpal glucocorticoid binding capacity in mice (Patacchioli et al., 1990, Beh. Brain Res., 37, 185-188). Plasma corticosterone concentrations were therefore measured using radioirnrnunoassay following the passive avoidance test. There was a significant strain difference in the ability of the no shock control group to habituate to the step-down passive avoidance apparatus that can be attributed to a strain difference in learning. The results indicated no strain differences in retention. Corticosterone levels are presently being analyzed. Strain differences in passive avoidance learning and in corticosterone levels may explain some of the MHC-related strain differences in mate selection, intermale aggression and other behaviours."}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T4", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Duquesnay, Renee and Robertson, Harry A. and Rusak, Benjamin", "abstract": "Circadian rhythms are synchronized primarily by cues from daily light-dark cycles. Light\nthat occurs at a time of day when it can shift (and therefore synchronize) the internal\ncircadian clock also causes increases in gene expression in cells of the suprachiasmatic\nnucleus (SCN). We have investigated whether blockade of this increased gene expression\nlocally in the SCN can alter the phase-shifting responses of the circadian system of\nhamsters to light. Hamsters were implanted with indwelling cannulas aimed at the SCN and\nwere housed in constant darkness. Hamsters received either control injections or injections\nof antisense oligonucleotides for the IEGs c-Fos and JunB into the SCN at circadian time\n(CT) 12 and were exposed to a 30 min light pulse at CT 18.\nPreliminary results indicate that the antisense oligonucleotides can reduce the phase-shifting\neffects of light, and suggest that gene expression induced by light plays a role in mediating\nlight effects on the circadian pacemaker."}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"abstract": "Activation of D1 and D2 dopamine receptors in the nucleus accumbens (NAc) is important for the rewarding effect of various reinforcers including brain stimulation. Blockade of D2, but not D3 or D4, receptors in this region with dopamine antagonists increases the threshold of reinforcement for brain stimulation. Activation of D 1 receptors is necessary to activate D2 receptors._ In the present study, the reward mechanism within NAc was studied by using falphostin C, a selective inhibitor of protein kinase C. The subjects were 42 male albino rats--:-nachof them was implanted with a bipolar electrode into the medial fore brain bundle and two cannulae bilaterally into NAc. They were trained to press a bar to receive electrical stimulation, and the threshold of reinforcing effect was measured before and after the injection of calphostin through the cannulae. Bilateral injection of calphostin into NAc increased the threshold of reinforcing effect in 2 hours and the effect reached the maximus in 4-6 hours. Recovery was observed in 24 to 48 hours after injection. Unilateral injection, either ipsilateral or contralateral to the electrode, was not effective. The results suggest that the rewarding effect of medial fore-brain stimulation is mediated by the activity of protein kinase C in NAc neurons. \n  \n  Symposium To Hebb and Beyond Donald Hebb was one of Canada's most famous and distinguished scientists, whose contributions were manifold and writings prolific. Hebb is widely recognized for his neo- connectionist assumption that correlated firing results in improved synaptic transmission (increase in connection weight) and his proposal of the cell assemblies. Hebb was a major advocate of psychology as a science and was a major force in directing its evolution in the 20th century. In order to examine Hebb and his work in a broader context, we will attempt to situate Hebb and his ideas within history, both in terms of the people who influenced him as well as in how his ideas shaped (or failed to shape) subsequent researchers. Some of the areas influenced by Hebb include LTP,kindling, neural networks, animal learning and memory, mental imagery, stopped retinal image, pain, aging and the role of early experience in cognitive and perceptual development. A life history of Hebb connecting significant life events to the various areas of interest integrates the diverse fields in which Hebb made a notable impact. For example, the publication of the Organization of Behavior ( 1949), which was influenced by the writings of William James and Santiago Ramon y Cajal, has exerted an ever-growing influence on those interested in mind, brain and how brains implement mind. What does that robot want from me now? Young children's abilities to repair contingent queries. Suzanne Ferrier The ability of two-year-old's to respond differentially to specific and general contingent queries was examined with the use of an immobile robot as the conversation partner. Twenty-one 2;9-year-old and 21 2;3-year-old children were queried (5 specific and 5 general) immediately following 10 of their spontaneous utternaces in a free play session. The type of response strategy (repetition or specification) was coded for each queried utterance. Regardless of age, children tended to respond to a general query with an exact repetition of their original utterance. Age differences were found, however, in their replies to a specific query. The 2;9-year-olds most often replied with the specific information requested, whereas the 2;3-year-olds often repeated their original utterance, providing their partner with too much information. These findings suggest that it is not until 2;9 years of age that children efficiently satisfy their communicative partner's informational needs when conversational exchanges involve only linguistic cues. Temperature Selection and Use of Torpor by the Marsupial Sminthopsis Macroura Xiaowei Song* and Fritz Geiser Department of Zoology, School of Biological Sciences, University of New England, Australia *present address: Rusak Lab, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University Many small mammals display daily torpor to minimize energy expenditure during the rest phase when faced with unfavorable environmental conditions. However, given a choice of thermal environments, it is not clear whether these daily heterotherms select ambient temperatures based on whether these minimize metabolic rates during torpor or during normothermia. It is also not clear whether they prefer being normothermic or torpid. In this study, we investigated temperature selection, activity patterns body temperature patterns, and the use of torpor in Sminthopsis macroura in a thermal gradient when food was freely available or restricted. Animals employed torpor regularly immediately after cessation of activity even when excess food was provided. Nevertheless, they selected high ambient temperature near the zone of thermoneutrality during both normothermia and torpor. Reduced food supply did not affect either temperature preference during torpor. Our study shows that S. macroura selected a high ambient temperature to reduce energy costs during normothermia. Nevertheless, daily torpor was frequently employed at the high temperature, especially when food was restricted. Measurement of Pain in Non-verbal, Cognitively Impaired Individuals Lynn Breau, Patrick J. McGrath, Carol Camfield, Christina Rosmus, G. Allen Finley A preliminary investigation of the properties of the Non-communicating Children's Pain Checklist was conducted. Caregivers of 38 individuals with Cerebral Palsy, Austism/PDD or a neurological disorder completed the checklist at home: twice when that person was in pain, once when they were in distress, and once when they were calm. Caregivers also completed the Checklist concerning their participant's past pain behaviour in general. Analyses were conducted to assess the Checklist's internal consistency, concurrent validity, sensitivity, specificity, and reliability. The results indicate that, when used by caregivers on actual events in a natural environment, the checklist can discriminate between calm and pain, is reliable over time, correlates with a visual analogue measure of pain, and is internally consistent. No differences were found between diagnostic groups, although reported behaviour did vary as a function of the relationship of the caregiver to the individual, and that individual's level of verbal comprehension. Evidence Based Decision Making: Construct Validity of a Sodium Amobarbital Recognition Memory Protocol McGlone, J., Black, S.E., Evans, J., Grantmyre, A., Moscovitch, M., Parkin, A., Sadler, M., Sita, A., Squires,E., Stuss, D., and Wilson, B.A. Purpose: We tested whether the Intracarotid Arnobarbital Protocol had criterion and concurrent validity. It was hypothesized that a recognition memory test designed for intracarotid injections and used to predict the risk of global amnesia prior to an elective temporal lobectomy should identify persons who are severely amnesic due to other neurological causes. •Speech tasks would be unaffected by amnesia, but would identify aphasia. The impact of aphasia on memory outcome would be negligible. Methods: Fifteen persons with severe amnesia and one aphasic were administered a four- item yes/no recognition memory protocol and a speech protocol. No drug injection occurred. Standardized neuropsychological tests were used to divide the amnesic group into those with Global Amnesia (i.e., retain no ongoing memories), Dissociated Amnesia, and Amnesia plus other neuropsychological deficits (i.e., Non-Dissociated). Results: Two Global Amnesic persons obtained scores at or below chance (i.e., failed) on the memory protocol. Unexpectedly, the remaining 13 severely amnesic persons (Dissociated and Non-dissociated), obtained passing memory scores. Amnesia had no impact on the speech protocol. An aphasic individual passed the memory protocol and was impaired on the speech protocol. Conclusions: This IAP memory protocol showed good criterion validity in identifying Global Amnesia, but it was insensitive to other disabling, severe amnesic disorders. Discriminant validity was shown by amnesic persons perf orrning well on IAP speech tasks. These results suggest that this IAP protocol might have validity in predicting a post surgical Global Amnesic disorder, but it did not identify and therefore could not predict other severe amnesic disorders 24 1998 In-House Convention The Effects of Alcohol and Alcohol Expectancy on Responses to Hyperventilation in High Anxiety Sensitive Individuals Alan MacDonald, Rochelle Hutson and Sherry Stewart High anxiety sensitivity (AS) levels are significantly associated with increased beliefs about the tension-reduction properties of alcohol (Karp, 1993). The present study examined the effect that these alcohol expectancies might have on alcohol's reactivity dampening effects in high AS young adults (Baker, MacDonald, Stewart & Skinner, under review), in addition to alcohol's pharmacological anxiolytic effects. A three cell beverage condition design was used to assess the contributions of expectancy vs. expectancy plus pharmacology: told alcohol-given alcohol (A-A, pharmacology + expectancy); told alcohol- given placebo (A-P, expectancy only); and told placebo-given placebo (P-P, control). High AS student participants were randomly assigned to each condition. Following alcohol consumption and absorption, participants underwent a 3 minute voluntary hyperventilation challenge. Preliminary analyses indicate that A-A participants show greater reductions in affective, cognitive and somatic symptoms in response to challenge than A-P and P-P participants. However, A-P participants do not show reduced affective and cognitive symptoms to challenge compared to P-P participants. In fact, correlational analyses suggest a positive relationship between subjective intoxication measures and levels of affective reactivity within the the A-P group (a \"reverse expectancy\" effect), and a negative relationship between these measures in the A-A group. Implications of these results for prevention of alcohol abuse in high AS individuals are discussed. Role of Sulfated Cholecystokinin Octapeptide (CCK-SS) in the Modulation of Separation-Induced Ultrasonic Vocalizations in 12 Day Old Rat Pups Paul D. Mendella, Anna Maria Szczesniak, Richard E. Brown Rat pups emit ultrasonic vocalizations (UV's) when separated from the dam and littermates. Anxiogenic drugs increase UV s, while anxiolytic drugs decerase UV s. The neuropeptide cholecystokinin (CCK) induces anxiety in health human volunteers and in individuals diagnosed with panic disorder. The purpose of the present investigation was to assess the effects of CCK-8S on UVs, locomotor activity, and body temperature in 12 day old rats pups, 15 or 30 minutes following drug treatment. Pups were injecteJ intraperitoneally with either vehicle or CCK-8S (0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0 µg/kg). After 15 minutes, male pups emitted more UVs and less turing behaviour than female pups. This is one of the few studies to find sex differences in rat pup UVs. After 30 minutes CCK-8S (4.0 mg/kg) significantly reduced line crossing frequency. In addition, male pups completed fewer head raises compared to female pups 30 minutes following drug treatment. Neither UV rate or body temperature was significantly altered by CCK-8S after 15 or 30 minutes. These findings suggest that CCK-8S is not directly involved in the modulation of anxiety-related behaviour in the separation-induced UV model of anxiety. Saccharin must be added to the taste cue to condition robust taste preferences Cathy Forestell and Vin LoLordo A reverse-order differential conditioning procedure was employed to condition taste preference in rats. During training, one taste solution (CS+) was presented 3 min after a calorific reinforcer (glucose), and another taste solution (CS-) was presented 3 min after water. For half of the animals, both taste solutions always contained saccharin, whereas for the remaining animals, the tastes were mixed in water. Subsequently, two-bottle tests revealed a significant preference for the CS+ relative condition. These results suggest that without the presence of sacchrin in the CS solutions, conditioned preferences do not occur. Simulating oculomotor behavior within a neural field model S. D. Simpson, R. Klein, T. Trappenberg Oculomotor programming can be viewed as the process of integrating exogenous (environmental) and endogenous (intentional) signals into a unified motor goal. Just as many experimental researchers recognize the importance of understanding both the bottom- up and top-down influences on oculomotor programming, we believe it is important to recognize that computational modeling of such systems should also be constrained by multiple levels of analysis; specifically by behavioral and neurophysiological data obtained from the area of interest. By extending and modifying a current neural field model of oculomotor programming (Kopecz and Schoner, 1996) we have developed a computational account of both behavioral and neurophysiological data from a variety of saccadic paradigms including target location preparation (Munoz & Dorris, this meeting), antisaccades (Everling et al, this meeting), and distractor manipulations. In the model, environmental and endogenous signals are integrated within a buildup layer allowing for competition among possible oculomotor programs. The activity of this buildup layer serves as input to a burst layer whose activity represents a specific oculomotor command. This poster will describe the model's architecture and demonstrate its ability to simulate saccadic reaction time patterns and neuronal activity of buildup and burst neurons within the Superior Colliculus. Possible enhancements to the model will also be discussed ."}}
