{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "P9", "patch": {"abstract": "This study examined the effect of judgment bias on the accuracy in detecting deception. One hundred\nand two participants judged the veracity of 12 video taped statements (6 honest and 6 deceptive) and\nwere asked to make ratings of credibility. Participants were randomly assigned to one of three\nconditions: no bias, honesty bias, or deceptive bias. In the deceptive bias condition, participants were\ninstructed that it was quite possible that the speakers in the videos were attempting to be deceptive. By\ncontrast, participants in the honesty condition were instructed that the speakers were likely to be telling\nthe truth. Participants in the no bias condition were led to believe that the purpose of the study was to\nsimply judge the quality of memory reports and no mention of deception or honesty was made. Overall\naccuracy in detecting deception was at chance level across the three conditions. However, the\ninstructional manipulation did bias judgments and the degree of bias depended on the nature of the\ninstructions. The participants in the no bias condition were significantly less accurate than those\nparticipants asked to focus on either honesty or deception. The frequencies with which deceptive and\nhonest judgments were made also varied across the conditions. The implications of such pre-judgment\nbiases in the context of legal and forensic settings are discussed."}}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T0", "patch": {"title": "A comparison of HS mice in the Barnes Maze and the Morris Water Maze", "authors_raw": "Houghton, Darryl and Stanford, Leanne and Brown, Richard E.", "abstract": "The Monis water maze, which is frequently used as a test of learning and memory in rodents has been criticized as being a stressful paradigm in mice (Van der Staay, 2000: Physiol. Behav. 68, 599-602 & Brooks et al. 2000: Soc. Neurosci Abst. 30, #841.3). This stress may confound learning and memory. The Barnes maze (BM), a visual spatial task in which mice learn to escape from the center of a brightlylit platform into a dark cage through 1 of 16 holes on the periphery, may be a less stressful alternative to the MWM. If these two tasks are accessing similar cognitive processes, measures of learning and memory in the MWM should be highly correlated with those of the BM. To test this hypothesis, we ran 34 Heterozygous Stock (HS) mice (IBG, CO, USA) in both the MWM and the BM. Mice in the MWM showed decreased escape latencies (EL) across days and increased EL on the first day of reversal. Mice in the BM had decreased EL in acquisition, but no increase in EL on the first day of reversal. The number of errors committed in the BM decreased over days and did increase on the first day of reversal. Escape latency and errors within the BM correlated for all measures of learning (.45 < r < .92, p < .0001 to .0072). Separately, each of these tasks has measured learning and memory. In comparing the two tasks, correlations for the escape latencies of the BM and MWM were calculated and all measures of learning [all days combined (r .24, p < .1969), day - one acquisition (r .03, p < .8775), all acquisition (r .13, p < .4822), day-one reversal (r .13, p < .4686), & last day of reversal (r .13, p < .4568)) or memory (r .05) were not significant. There were also no significant correlations between the BM (errors) and the MWM (EL) for any measure of learning [all days combined (r = -.15, p < .4011), day-one acquisition (r .01, p <.9545), all acquisition (r .13, p < .4965), day-one reversal (r=-.18, p < .3004), & last day of reversal (r = .04, p < .8229)) or memory (r =.10 for errors). These data suggest the cognitive processing for these two tasks may be different, and when comparing data between these tasks caution should be exercised."}}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T6", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Loba, Pamela and Stewart, Sherry H. and Klein, Raymond M. and Blackburn, James R.", "abstract": "A set of and in-vivo studies were conducted to identify game parameters that would reduce the risk of abuse of video lottery terminals by pathological gamblers, while exerting minimal effects on the behavior of non-pathological gamblers. Three manipulations of standard VLT game features were explored. Participants were exposed to: a counter which displayed a running total of money spent; a VLT spinning reels game where participants could no longer \"stop\" the reels by touching the screen and sensory feature manipulations. In control conditions, participants were exposed to standard settings for either a spinning reels or a video poker game. For the lab-based study dependent variables were self-ratings of reactions to each set of parameters. A set of 2 x x (game manipulation [experimental condition vs. control condition] x game [spinning reels vs. video poker] x gambler status [pathological vs. non-pathological]) repeated measures ANOVA's were conducted on all dependent variables. The in-vivo study used behavioural ratings as the dependent measure. Finding for both studies suggest that the sensory manipulations produced the most robust reaction differences"}}
