{"year": 2006, "entry_id": "T22", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Mitchell, Donald E. and  Sengpiel, Frank", "abstract": "Continuous monocular deprivation during early postnatal life results in reduced cortical and visual acuity of the deprived eye. However, loss of visual function in one eye after a brief period of compromised vision would appear to be maladaptive. Previously we have reared cats with a daily regimen in which they received variable amounts of MD and BE and subsequently assessed the visual capabilities of the two eyes. Here we report on visual cortex function on the basis of optical imaging of intrinsic signals. As with behaviour, we show that daily amounts of binocular vision as short as 0.5 h allowed normal ocular dominance architecture and visual responses to develop despite much longer periods of MD. However, unlike vision where the outcome appears to be dictated by the proportion of total exposure that is normal, cortical architecture appears to be determined by the absolute amount of binocular vision rather than its relative share. As with behaviour, continuous binocular experience was more effective for cortical development than an equivalent exposure split into two epochs. Normal experience is clearly more efficacious in driving visual cortical development and experience, vision than abnormal experience."}}
