{"year": 2010, "entry_id": "T24", "patch": {"abstract": "The Cognitive Failures Questionnaire (CFQ) is widely used to assess frequency of everyday slips/errors even though its factor structure is unclear. Using data from 2394 female and 921 male undergraduates, the present study compared the principle components structures for 3 through 7 factors, using both orthogonal and non-orthogonal rotations. The best structure was a 4-factor solution with non-orthogonal rotation. For the males, the best was a non-orthogonal 4-factor solution while for the females, the best was a non-orthogonal 3-factor solution. A subset of 484 students completed the CFQ more than once. It demonstrated good test-retest reliability at 1 year.\n5:00-6:00 What is MEG and How Can I Use It?\nAaron Newman\nHalifax is now home to Canada's most advanced magnetoencephalogrphy (MEG) brain imaging system. MEG is a noninvasive tool that offers the temporal resolution of EEG/ERP and spatial resolution than can rival fMRI. However, compared to those techniques it is faster to set up, less affected by head movements, more comfortable for the subject/patient, silent, and does not involve large magnets. This makes it an ideal tool for use with children and various patient populations. Through a partnership between the IWK Health Centre and the National Research Council Institute for Biodiagnostics, Elekta Neuromag OY has installed a 306 channel MEG imaging system and will be situated their North American R&D Headquarters at the IWK Health Centre. This presents a fantastic opportunity for researchers to do cutting-edge work with first-class support. However, as with any technique MEG is not exactly \"plug 'n play\" and requires some understanding to get up and running. In this talk I will briefly describe what MEG is and how it works, and then walk the audience through the process of designing a MEG study, moving a project through the approval process at IWK/NRC, implementing the study, and analyzing the data."}}
{"year": 2011, "entry_id": "P14", "patch": {"abstract": "Neurofilament is the predominant shape‐providing intermediate filament in neurons. Within the visual system neurofilament has been linked to particular cell types and functions. In primate visual cortex the protein is localized most heavily within cells that compose the regions outlining metabolically distinct ‘blobs’. In this study we examined whether the non‐uniform distribution of cell characteristics and physiological functions within the rat somatosensory system is linked to the localization of neurofilament subunits. In adult rats we observed neurofilament‐positive neurons preferentially located outside of metabolically distinct ‘barrels’. Investigation of neurofilament subunits throughout development revealed that for two subunits (medium and heavy) reactivity was initially located most densely within processes that formed barrels. These results demonstrate a distinction very early in postnatal development between the labeling patterns of neurofilament subunits that reveal either cells indigenous to the cortex (light) or processes whose is likely thalamic (medium and heavy)."}}
{"year": 2011, "entry_id": "P7", "patch": {"abstract": "Inhibition of return (IOR) is an orienting phenomenon characterized by slower behavioral responses to spatially cued, relative to uncued targets, when the cue‐target onset asynchronies (CTOAs) are long enough that cue‐elicited attentional capture has dispersed. Here, we implement a short‐term depression (STD) account of IOR within a neuroscientifically based dynamic neural field model (DNF) of the superior colliculus (SC). In addition to the prototypical findings in the cuetarget paradigm (ie., the biphasic pattern of behavioral enhancement at short CTOAs and behavioral costs at long CTOAs), a variety of findings in the literature are generated with this model, including IOR in averaging saccades and the co‐existence of IOR and endogenous orienting at the same location. Many findings that cannot be accommodated by this model could be accounted for by incorporating cortical contributions."}}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"abstract": "Inhibition of return (IOR) is thought to improve the efficiency of visual search behaviour by biasing attention, eye movements, or both, toward novel stimuli. Previous research suggests that IOR might arise from sensory, attentional or motor programming processes. In the present study, we were interested in determining if IOR could instead arise from a simple late-stage motor output bias, independent from effects on earlier processes. Participants made consecutive saccades (from a common starting location) to central arrowhead stimuli. We removed the possible contribution of sensory/attentional and motor preparation effects in IOR by allowing participants to fully prepare their responses in advance of an execution signal. When responses were delayed to allow response preparation, we continued to observe IOR. Our data therefore provide evidence that IOR can result from a simple motor execution bias that may arise from inhibitory effects on motor output neurons controlling the extraocular muscles directly.\nDEBATE: Open vs traditional peer-reviewed publishing in science\nAaron Newman, Jon Fawcett, Mike Lawrence, Heath Matheson, and more\nThe world of publishing, both within academia and more broadly, has been revolutionized by digital technology. With the technology necessary to distribute one's work available to virutally everyone, it is clear that the old paradigms cannot be maintained. At the same time, scientific publishing has a long and proud tradition of curation through rigourous peer review. While few would argue that peer review is a bad thing, we are also aware that peer review has a dark side: irrational reviewers (positive or negative, though we focus more on the latter); coldly rational reviewers who deliberately sabatoge manuscripts to prevent being scooped; editors who lack the expertise to evaluate arguments properly; and the fact that journals deliberately restrict themselves to the publication of the \"best\" papers in order to improve their reputations, rather than because all rejected papers are \"bad\" science. As well, in moves reminiscent of the music industry over the last 15 years, we have witnessed academic publishers take coprporate and legislative steps to protect their profit margins at the expense of academic freedom, for instance by requiring libaries to purchase \"bundles\" of journals at great expense, including journals that the libraries do not want, as well as publishers' support of recent legislative moves in Canada and the US to radically strengthen copyright protection at the expense of academic freedom. Against this draconian landscape, however, academics are faced with the reality that our careers, including hiring, promotion, and funding decisions, hinge not only on how much we publish, but where. In this debate, one side will argue in favour of open publishing and highlight current best practices, while the other side will argue in favour of a relatively unchanged status quo. Arguments and rebuttals will be followed by an open discussion with the audience."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50", "patch": {"abstract": "While quantitative methods in psychology and neuroscience have traditionally been dominated by the \"null hypothesis significance testing\" (NHST) philosophy of statistics, recent advances in computing have permitted alternative approaches, most notably Bayesian methods. This talk will briefly distinguish the philosophical backgound of NHST and Bayesian methods followed by a walk-through of a simple Bayesian analysis. The talk will conclude with discussion of the power of Bayesian methods to address more advanced analyses.\nFinal Symposium\nPsychology and Neuroscience: Why our name without \"and neuroscience\" would not smell as sweet\nDescartes made a sharp distinction between conscious processes of the mind or rational soul and mechanical material processes of the body. This distinction was effective and had long-term consequences that included separating the disciplines of psychology and neurobiology. Why this happened and why we are now able to reintegrate psychology and neuroscience is the subject of this symposium.\nWhy psychology and neuroscience separated as sciences\nJohn Barresi\nFor Aristotle psychology was an integral part of the biology of animate beings. But, with the rise of Christianity and its emphasis on Plato's earlier idea of the immortality of the rational human soul, Western thinkers were ready for Descartes' revolutionary theory, which distinguished sharply between the conscious rational soul of humans and body-machines. While subsequent thinkers rejected Descartes' idea that all other animals were mere automata, without conscious minds, the majority of 18th and 19th century scientists continued to distinguish conscious processes of minds and purely material processes of animate bodies, including the brain. A consequence of this historical development has been that psychology and neurobiology have been separate disciplines until quite recently.\nHow Donald Hebb brought psychology and neuroscience back together\nRichard Brown\nIn the 1940's, there were many \"Schools\" of psychology, such as Gestalt Psychology, Structuralism, Functionalism, Behaviourism, etc., each of which looked at behaviour in a different way. There were also a plethora of \"physiological\" theories of behaviour proposed by Pavlov, Lashley, Morgan, and others. Each theory focused on a different aspect of behaviour: learning, memory, development, motivation, emotion and clinical problems. What Hebb did, with two simple concepts, the modifiable synapse and the cell assembly, was to provide a neural mechanism which could account for all of the different categories of behaviour that psychologists were struggling to explain with their separate theories. The result was to change Psychological theory and reintroduce the idea that a neural mechanism was the basis for all behaviour, normal and abnormal and that one of the aims of Psychology was to understand that physiological mechanism. Hebb's aim was to show that the psychological study of the \"mind\" required a biological approach.\nA neo-Hebbian blueprint for the integration of neuro-psychological science and the mission of our Department\nRaymond M. Klein\nWith Hebb's ideas providing a backdrop, the recent history of our discipline will be related to a (somewhat) personalized history of the department. Divisions based on workplace (laboratory versus clinic), type of work (studies of brain versus behavior; animals versus humans), sub-discipline (development, perception, personality, learning, etc.) and favorite causal mechanism (nature vs nurture) characterize these histories. Importantly, conceptual, methodological and technological innovations have made it possible for us to implement Hebb's neuropsychological vision of the discipline through an integrated effort to understand how nature and nurture shape the neural networks that underlie the organization of our overt and covert behaviors.\nThe future of psychology and neuroscience\nOlav Krigolson\nOur increasing ability to see into the mind has helped scientists adapt theory to match the computations that are actually performed within the brain. For example, rational choice theory would posit that when faced with a decision, one should always choose the response option with the highest utility, or value. However, that is not always the case. When humans play the \"ultimatum game\" frequently people make irrational decisions - they reject proffered money in the name of \"fairness\". Functional imaging has given us insight into why this occurs, and has forced a reconciliation of rational choice theory with psychological theory. As we head into the future, technological advances in human neuroimaging will only allow us to see further into the processes of the mind and explain other phenomenon. For instance, recent advances in neuroimaging have taken us into the realm of mind reading - a technology that knows what we are thinking as we are thinking it. Not only does research like this give us better insight into why we do and say the things we do, but it also puts us right in front of Pandora's Box - forcing to us to an understanding that we might not want to have."}}
{"year": 2015, "entry_id": "P4", "patch": {"abstract": "We used the Triple Test of Anxiety (TTA), Rotarod and the Hebb-Williams (HWM) maze to assess anxiety, motor performance and spatial learning and memory in 5xFAD mice at 6 and 12 months of age. We observed less time spent in the closed arms of the elevated plus maze for the 5xFAD mice, yet they spent more time in the dark box. We found motor deficits in the 12 month old 5xFAD mice on the Rotarod which affected both their latencies and motor learning. While there were no significant differences between the WT and 5xFAD mice in the acquisition phase of the HWM, all the mice had longer latencies and higher number of errors in the hard mazes of the test phase and there was a trend of 5xFAD mice making more errors compared to the WT controls in all three levels of difficulty."}}
{"year": 2015, "entry_id": "T28", "patch": {"title": "Three optical mechanisms in wing spots of a large dolichopodid fly, Liancalus genualis", "authors_raw": "Shaw, Steve", "abstract": "Most flies have plain or darkly mottled wings, but Liancalus males have wing spots that redirect and diffuse sunlight using ~1515 tiny upright hairs, forming a bright signal for conspecifics. When the sun is obscured, a second signal is still possible because the spots fluoresce bluish- white in UV light, an important component of skylight. There is much blue in skylight though, raising the question of whether the fluorescence could even be seen over reflection from the rest of the wing. Reflection, measured with collimated blue light was surprisingly low. Quantification of fluorescence required several steps, and indicated impressive efficiency: only 12 UV photons are required to displace one fluorescent photon from the wing spot. The wavelength distribution in 5000K skylight then dictates that the natural fluorescence-to- reflection ratio will be high, ~19:1. Fluorescent spots should be easy to see. Accordingly, photographs made under natural skylight revealed a spot visual contrast of ~15:1. However, when sky UV was selectively filtered out, spot brightness dropped by only 14-18%. This exposes a third signaling mechanism: the spot’s refractile hairs act as waveguides and pick up skylight but reflect about 17% back. Fluorescence scores at only ~1/6 of this."}}
