{"year": 2016, "entry_id": "P1", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Horne, J. A. and Langille, C. and McLin, S. and Wiederman, M. and Borycz, J.A.1and Tarnogorska, D. and Team, FlyEM Project and Plaza, S. and Xu, S. and Hess, H. and Meinertzhagen, I.A", "abstract": "The antennal lobe of the fruit fly is similar to the olfactory bulb in the mammalian brain in that it is\ndivided into individual glomeruli each of which has it own set of receptor neuron inputs that encode\na particular olfactant. We have undertaken dense reconstruction on glomerulus VA1v in the\nDrosophila antennal lobe and sparse tracing beyond, from an isotropic 8nm stack of segmented\nFIB-SEM images. The image stack encompasses the entire right antennal lobe of a 6-day female\nfly viewed in a frontal plane. This fruitless-positive, sexually dimorphic glomerulus is responsive to\nfly odour (Sakurai et al. Nat. Commun., 4:1825, 2013) and was chosen because it is large,\nenclosing a region much larger than any densely annotated antennal lobe volume to date. Three\nmain classes of neurons populate the glomerulus. We have reconstructed and blindly annotated\nthe synapses of the following: olfactory receptor neurons (ORNs), projection neurons (PNs), and\nlocal interneurons (LINs). In aggregate the 183 cells we have identified represent ~70% of the\nglomerular synaptic connections with more work yet to be done."}}
