{"year": 2018, "entry_id": "T17", "patch": {"abstract": "Reading comprehension, or the ability to understand the meaning of text, is one of the\nmost important skills children learn in school. Understanding how various metalinguistic skills\nsupport reading comprehension is essential to improving literacy curriculum. One skill which is\nrelated to reading comprehension in young readers is prosodic sensitivity, which is an awareness of\nthe rhythmic cues in speech. However, the reason for this relationship is unclear. One possibility is\nthat young readers are aware of how prosodic cues are represented in text, e.g. through punctuation.\nThe proposed research will test the possibility that awareness of how prosodic cues are represented in\ntext mediates the relationship between prosodic sensitivity and reading comprehension in young\nreaders. This will be done by testing 150 grade 3-5 students individually in schools and examining\ntheir reading comprehension, prosodic sensitivity, and awareness of how prosodic cues are\nrepresented in text."}}
