{"year": 2025, "entry_id": "T26", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Tennen, Lucas and Murphy, Nick and Horne, Samantha and DuJohn, Julia and Boyce, Joy and Sherri", "abstract": "Spatial neglect, a common consequence of right hemisphere stroke, leads to attentional deficits and poor\nrehabilitation outcomes. While visual scanning treatment (VST) is a potential intervention, its effectiveness typically\ndepends on therapist-guided sessions exceeding 15 hours, posing challenges in resource-limited settings. SpyTrain, an\nonline VST program, offers intensive, adaptive, game-like scanning practice and has shown validity in healthy controls\n(Aziz et al., 2021), and early efficacy in stroke patients. This study is assessing the feasibility and effectiveness of SpyTrain\nfor treating spatial neglect, focusing on the application of strategies. Patients with right hemisphere stroke and neglect\nare randomized to three different baseline lengths using a non-concurrent multiple baseline single-case design, followed\nby 5 weeks of online VST (5 sessions/week). Outcomes will are measured across phases and analyzed using Tau-U, a\nnonparametric test assessing improvement trends. If effective, SpyTrain could offer an accessible, home-based\ntreatment to support recovery and independence in stroke survivors with neglect."}}
