{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "17", "patch": {"abstract": "Three groups of subjects, normal right-handers (RN), \"normal\"\nleft-handers (LN), and \"inverted\" left-handers who assume a \"hooked\"\nhand-writing posture (LI) 0 pressed a key with the index finger of one\nhand whenever a stimulus appeared to the right or left of a fixation\npoint. Response hand was varied across blocks of trials. For RN\nand LN subjects, RTs were faster when the response hand was the one\nipsilateral rather than contralateral to the stimulus position.\nHowever, this ipsilateral hand-field compatibility effect was not\nobserved in LI subjects. Implications for Levy's ipsilateral motor\ncontrol ex lana • I writing are discussed.\nr,. 18."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25", "patch": {"abstract": "Following reimplantation of tectal tissues or reciprocal\ntransp-lantatian between a tectal tissue and a cerebellar (or forebrain)\ntissue in the adult goldfish, stru~tural changes in the optic tectum\nare examined by Golgi staining and autoradiographic methods. In cl.11\ncases the changes in cytoarchitecture are consistent with the normal\npattern of connection of optic fibers from the retina to the optic\ntectum."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "6", "patch": {"abstract": "The synapses of the perforant pathway from the entorhinal\ncortex to the fascia dentata are organized in a clearly laminar fashion.\nThose fibres orginating most laterally in the enterhinal area terminate\nmost distally on the granule cell dendrites, while the most medially\noriginating fibres terminate most proximally. This system has been\nclassically regarded as a functional unit. Physiological studies of\nshort-term synaptic plasticity, however, suggest two functionally dis-\ncrete subsystems. This data is in agreement with recent histochemical\nstudies."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8", "patch": {"abstract": "Depending on the requirements of the situation, it is\nbelieved that an organism, such as a pigeon, can either remember a\nstimulus or a future behaviour required by the present stimulus. Honig\nhas shown that in situations in which a pigeon is only required to\nremember whether to peck or not, remembering occurs over longer inter-\nvals than are normally found with procedures which require the recall\nof a stimulus. The present research uses a procedure which also requires\nonly that the pigeon remember whether to respond or not, It is simpler\nthan those that have been used previously. Since this seems to produce\nas much recall in pigeons as Honig's procedure, this hypothesis is\nVO\"r2_<._ 9."}}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "11", "patch": {"abstract": "Are hospitalized children under stress? Does the existence of a\nplayschool in the hospital reduce this stress? In this initial study, the\nplay behaviour of hospitalized children was compared with that of children in\na daycare center. Differences in levels of play, social behaviour and\n\"emotional\" displays wi 11 be discussed."}}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "8", "patch": {"abstract": "The work presented here is an attempt to obtain a test sensitive to\nright hemisphere processes. Experiments with stick figures, extracted from the\n16 segments obtained from a 3 x 3 matrix, appear promising. A three-segment\npart, either contained within a foveally-presented six-segment figure or not,\nwas briefly exposed in the left or right visual field. Decisions (part\nincluded in the figure or not) were made quicker for \"easy\" parts (e.g.\ntriangles) in the right visual field, and for \"difficult\" parts (unconnected\nand scattered) in the left. These data suggest?- method for evaluating\nperceptual and memory representations in the two hemispheres."}}
{"year": 1983, "entry_id": "10", "patch": {"abstract": "The pupil response (PR) in insect eyes is a rapid, profourid darkening\nbrought about by illumination, supposedly caused by migration of\nscreening pigment granules (SPGs) inside the photoreceptors. Incidental\nobservations revealed surprisingly large changes in optical transmission\n(>90%), in eye mutants largely lacking pigments (<1% normal). In EM\nsections, SPGs are largely absent, suggesting that- the conventional\nexplanation for the PR is incorrect. Suggestively, mitochondria\ncongregate distally in certain photoreceptors, with a distribution\ncharacteristic of the PR. The pupil pigment, possibly associated with\nthese mitochondria, dissolves away during EM fixation."}}
{"year": 1984, "entry_id": "19", "patch": {"abstract": "I have trained two female Savannah baboons to choose the odd visual\nstimulus of the three presented in a modified Wisconsion General Test\nApparatus. At present I am using photographs of fruit, leaves, and\nobjects found around the monkey room as visual stimuli. I test for\ncategorization by occasionally giving probe trials in which the three\nstimuli are different, but two fall within the same category (fruit or\nleaves). Each baboon shows a tendency to choose the od<l member of the\ntrio, thus classifying the two fruits or two leaves together."}}
{"year": 1984, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"abstract": "This research investigates hemispheric asymmetries in the perception and\nidentification of both positive and negative emotion. The main purpose\nwas to identify conditions under which an overall left visual field\nadvantage obtains for all emotion and those in which a dissociation is\nfound for positive and negative emotion. Pairs of faces were presented\nsuch that one face was presented to each visual field. The pairs\nconsisted of either happy and neutral or sad and neutral faces. Righ-\nhanded subjects were required to respond to the faces that 1) were more\nemotional, and 2) made them feel either better or worse. The dependent\nmeasures were the latency and accuracy of respones. The main finding was\nthat visual field asymmetries depended on the task requirements. When\nasked to respond to the more emotional face visual field differences\nvaried primarily as a function of the sex of the subject. However, both\nsexes showed an overall left visual field advantage for better and worse\njudgements. Support was not provided for the idea of differential\nhemipsheric specialization for positive and negative emotion. Results\nare discussed in light of previous findings suggesting that males and\nfemales tend to use different strategies in such tasks."}}
{"year": 1985, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"abstract": "Studies of odour preferences were examined in an effort to·answer some\nquestions regarding the interpretation of such preferences as evidence\nfor a \"maternal pheromone\". Some odorous substances, in particular,\nfeces and ventral scent gland sebum, both of which are copiously produced\nby lactation females, are preferentially approached by preweanling pups.\nThe attractiveness of an odour to pups may, in part, be a function of the\nodour's saliency, its familiarity, or its similarity to other, already\nfamiliar odours. Unfamiliar odours can be made attractive by exposure,\nand familiarity with an odour seems to be both necessary and sufficient\nto increase the attractiveness of that odour, whether it is produced by a\nconspecific or not. Simple exposure has been shown to be effective in\nestablishing an odour as attractive but this attraction may be increased\nif conditioning contingencies are also present. Since the attractiveness\nof maternal odours can be explained simply by assessing the role of\nfamiliarity, the concept of a \"maternal pheromone\" is not necessary and\nis not parsimonious with the data. Furthermore, it is not successful in\nexplaining the modifiability of odour preferences through experience."}}
{"year": 1987, "entry_id": "23", "patch": {"abstract": "We examined sexual behaviour and odour preferences in mated pairs of\ngerbils. They were given sexual behaviour tests with their own mate and\nwith a novel partner. We predicted that gerbils would show more sexual\nbehaviour and less aggression to familiar partners. While many of the\nbehaviours showed this trend, the differences were not significant. Steve\nHolman has been repeating this experiment and I hope he has significant\nresults by now. In a second experiment we examined responses of gerbils\nhoused in mixed- or same-sex pairs to the urine odours of their cage-mates\nand novel gerbils. Gerbils housed in mixed-sex pairs approached and\ninvestigated the odour of their cage-mate and produced more modulated\nultrasounds in the presence of this odour than in the presence of the odour\nof a novel gerbil. Gerbils housed in same sex pairs showed no such\ndifferential responsiveness to the odour of their cage-mates. Odour may be\nused for individual recognition and function to reduce aggression in social\ninteractions between mated pairs of gerbils.\n24:"}}
{"year": 1988, "entry_id": "5", "patch": {"abstract": "Raclopride, a dopamine antagonist, has a high affinity for D2 receptors\nbut extremely low affinity for Dl receptors, Intraperitoneal injection of\nraclopride suppressed bar-pressing for food (CRF and VI-30 sec), ventral\ntegmental stimulation, and intravenous heroin infusion in the rat. The\ndegree of suppression was related to the dose, and the maximal effects\nwere observed from 30 to 180 min after injection, Raclopride injection\ninto the nucleus accumbens suppressed ipsilateral tegmental self-\nroles of experience, b) rules of generalization, and c) the organism's\nhandling of incomplete or distorted information. This talk is designed to\nhighlight some of these issues, with reference to existing literature and\npotential experimental approaches for future work. Naturally, mice and\nwolves will play a key (but not exclusive) role here!"}}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "28", "patch": {"abstract": "subjects were 16-19 day old mice of two congenic strains (C57BL/6J and B6-ARK-H-2k), which\ndiffer only in the major histocompatibility complex on chromosome 17. We tested the preferences of\nthese mice for maternal odours of lactating females of the two strains on two different diets. Pups\nwere attracted more to odours from lactating females of the same strain and on the same diet as their\nmother to lactating females of the other strain or those on the other diet. These results indicate that\npups may \"imprint\" on different components of the maternal odour. Dietary information so learned\nmay be used to direct food choices and genetic infonnation to influence the choice of social partners\nand mates.\n2 9."}}
