{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T20", "patch": {"abstract": "The suprachiasmatic nuclei (SCN) of the mammalian hypothalamus function as a\npacemaker which controls mammalian circadian rhythms. The SCN receive photic\ninput via the geniculohypothalamic tract (GHT), an indirect visual pathway arising\nfrom cells in the intergeniculate leaflet (IGL) of the lateral geniculate body, with\nneuropeptide Y and GABA being likely neurotransmitter candidates. The SCN also\nreceive direct visual input via the retinohypothalamic tract (RHT), and evidence\nsuggests that the excitatory amino acid glutamate mediates neurotransmission in the\nRHT. Recent reports have demonstrated the presence of ionotropic excitatory amino\nacid receptors of the NMDA and non-NMDA receptor subclasses in the SCN. In\naddition, metabotropic excitatory amino acid receptors have been located in the\nSCN. To date, very little information is available on the effects of metabotropic\nreceptor activation in the SCN, however, initial studies in our laboratory have\ndemonstrated that 1S,3R ACPD, a specific metabotropic receptor agonist, causes a\ndose-dependent increase in neuronal activity in the SCN in vitro. Further studies\naim to pharmacologically characterise metabotropic glutamate receptors in the SCN\nand elucidate the role of this receptor type in the SCN in vivo."}}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T16", "patch": {"abstract": "There are many reports in the literature of finickiness in rats which have been shocked\nbut not in rats which have not been shocked. Finickiness is a suppression of\nconsumption of for example a bitter tasting solution relative to baseline consumption\nlevels. In studies reported previously (for example see Job and Barnes, 1995,\nBehavioralNeuroscience,109, 106-116) the finickiness effect has been reported only\nfollowing the sorts of shock parameters that result in learned helplessness, 100+\nshocks of 2-60s in duration. Previous work done in our lab had incorporated a one\nhour shock session of 60 2-s shocks and had failed to show a relationship between\nshock and alcohol consumption. In order to address the possibility that this failure\nresulted from a failure to produce differences in level of stress or fear between our\nshock and no-shock rats we sought independent evidence that animals shocked in our\nexperiments experienced more \"stress\" than animals which were not shocked. Using\nour shock parameters in annickiness experiment we showed that shocked rats did\nsuppress their consumption of quinine relative to baseline levels of water consumption\nwhile no-shock rats did not."}}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T26", "patch": {"abstract": "In recent decades, attentional biases along three-dimensional spatial coordinates have been a topic of increased interest. However, physical boundaries, as well as methodological restraints have precluded a thorough and systematic investigations of human performances along these planes. The currentstudy proposed to address some of these limitations by investigating line bisection and visual orientation performances along horizontal and vertical planes in peripersonal (within hand's reach) and extrapersonal (outside of hand's reach) space. Subjects bisected a total of 72 computer-generated horizontal and vertical lines projected in each spatial location. Furthermore, on any given trial, horizontal lines appeared at the top, centre or bottom of the screen, while vertical lines appeared at the left, centre or right of the screen. As well, a bisecting cursor appeared at either end of each line. In the visual orientation task, subjects reponded to 229 validly or invalidly cued targets in each spatial location. On any given trial, targets appeared at the top left, top right, bottom left or bottom right of the screen. Overall, horizontal and vertical lines were bisected to the left and above the midpoint, respectively. Moreover, analyses of variance revealed that bisecting biases varied significantly in peripersonal and extrapersonal space contingent upon bisector and line position on the screen. Overall, subjects responded more quickly to validly than invalidly cued targets. Analyses of variance revealed that response time also varied significantly and differently along horizontal and vertical planes in peripersonal and extrapersonal space. These findings are discussed in light of current models of visual attention. ~"}}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T1", "patch": {"abstract": "In experiment 1 an aqueous solution of amyl acetate was used as an odour cue for illness\nusing a one-bottle choice test with CS-US intervals ranging between 15 minutes and 8\nhours. The results showed that amyl acetate was an effective cue for illness with CS-US\ndelays up to two hours. In experiment 2 the effects of the muscarinic antagonist\nscopolamine HBr on odour aversion learning was examined using both one and two bottle\nchoice tests. Injection of scopolamine HBr (0.01 and 0.1 mg/kg) 30 minutes prior to the\nconditioning trial suppressed fluid intake on the conditioning trial, but did not disrupt\nacquisition of an illness-induced aversion to the amyl acetate solution. Injection of\nscopolamine HBr (0.1 mg/kg) 15 minutes after the conditioning trial did not suppress fluid\nintake and did not interfere with acquisition of an illness- induced odour aversion.\nExperiment 3 assessed the effects of the NMDA receptor antagonist MK-801 on acquisition\nof an odour aversion. MK-801 (0.05 mg/kg) did not interfere with acquisition of an odour\naversion. Experiment 4 examined the effects of odour exposure only on acquisition of an\nillness odour aversion. The results demonstrated that fluid intake appears to be necessary\nfor an illness-induced odour aversion to form. These results challenge the Sensory and '.'.r(_.\\l)}'t-\nGate Channeling theory that only tastes are capable of acting as cues for illness in food\naversion learning (Rusiniak, Hankins, Garcia & Brett, 1979). These experiments also\ndemonstrated that glutamatergic and cholinergic neurotransmitter systems appear to play ~-\nlittle or no role in acquisition of an illness-induced odour aversion."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16", "patch": {"abstract": "We studied the characteristic patterns of neural responses of the human brain to various combinations of semantic anomalies and/or verb inflectional disagreements during rapid reading of compound sentences by analyzing the event related brain potentials (ERP) recorded from normal adult subjects. [l] ERP of semantically anomalous verbs showed negative shifts peaking at about 400 msec (N400) with respect to the semantically appropriate verbs. The onset time of the N400 responses depended on the syntactic contexts of the verbs. [2] ERP of inflectionally incorrect verbs made positive shifts at about 600 msec (P600) with respect to control verbs. A repetition of the inflectional disagreement in the second clause diminished the P600 response. The result suggests that the repeated inflectional disagreement tends to be ignored by the neural mechanism which has responded to the previous inflectional disagreement as P600. [3] The predominant component of neural responses to semantically anomalous and inflectionally incorrect verbs was P600 rather than N400. Thus inflectional disagreement (rather than semantic anomaly) seems to be a predominant linguistic feature, detected by those neurons whose activities happened to be monitored by our recording methods. [4] Inter-sentential influence of the semantically anomalous transitive verb (with respect to its subject) upon its (acceptable) object; ERP to the object words of semantically anomalous verbs showed large negative shifts during a period between 300 and 750 msec. The magnitude and duration of the negative shift in the object word was far grater than that in the anomalous verb itself. The result reveals the prominent influence of the two diffemet sentential contexts on the same terminal words . [5] Inter-sentential influence of inflectional disagreement of semantically normal transitive verb upon its appropriate object in the second clause; ERP to the object words of the inflectionally incorrect normal verbs showed large negative shifts during a period beginning 300 msec. This large negative shift in the object words reflects the influence of the preceding inflectional relations between the subjects and the verbs in the compound sentences."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T37", "patch": {"abstract": "Given the lack of research quantifying pain during various dental hygiene procedures, pain and pain coping attempts were explored in 48 patients (27 male, 21 female) undergoing routine dental hygiene treatment Dental anxiety and self-efficacy of pain coping attempts were also explored in relation to pain. The majority of patients (79%) report none or very little pain during clinical procedures. In direct contrast, 21 % of sample reported pain scores that were extreme in comparison to the majority. Empathic discussions with the hygienist, self-distraction from the pain, and information seeking from the hygienist, were the most often employed pain coping strategies. In dividing the sample by pain reports (i.e., low and high pain), no group differences in regards to dental anxiety, age, education, brushing habits, or the degree of tre~tment difficulty were found. However, the low pain group flossed more (t=3.01, l2.,.<.005)and had greater levels of self-efficacy for pain coping attempts (t=2.28, l2.,.<.027)than did the high pain group. There were no differences in how many pain coping strategies were reported between low and high pain groups as well as low and high self-efficacy for pain coping. Results suggest that feelings of personal control during dental hygiene treatment may be a factor in successful pain management. Future research is discussed in terms of other trait-like cognitive factors such as pain catastrophizing."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"abstract": "Gap junctions are the structural contacts that mediate electrical coupling between neurons in nervous systems. In vertebrates, gap junctions form from connexin proteins, but in invertebrates the corresponding proteins remain elusive. Recently, however, the shaking-B gene in Drosophila is suggested to encode a connexin-like protein, and mutants of shaking- B, including Passover, a null mutant with a defective escape jump, exhibit coupling defects. An antibody raised against the shak-B peptide expresses in the the lamina, where terminals of the eye's photoreceptors are electrically coupled by gap junctions. Compared with the wild type, there are significantly fewer (ca 20%) gap junctions in the shak-B mutant, but only in the upper levels of the lamina. At deeper levels, the numbers are smaller in both mutant and wild type, and both the same. Thus, the lamina's population of gap junctions is partitioned into at least two strata, and the numbers in the mutant imply the existence of at least two genetic factors, possibly proteins, encoding the number of gap junctions."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9", "patch": {"abstract": "The parasitic wasp Cotesiacongregatainjects its eggs into the larvae of the tobacco\nhorn worm, Manducasexta. Homworms were found to feed normally during the growth\nof the parasitic wasps. However, M. sexta stopped feeding several hours prior to the\nemergence of the wasp larvae. Hosts were not debilitated by the parasites and survived\nanother 2 weeks without feeding after the wasps emerged. In the field, unparasitized M.\nsexta ate C. congregatapupae (n=l0/10) suggesting that the suppression of host feeding\nprevents predation of the parasitic wasps by the host. The decline in host feeding correlated\nwith a long-lasting increase in the concentration of octopamine in the host's hemolymph\n(22.2 ± 2.1 pg/µL (n=7) to 143.7 ± 7.8 pg/µL hemolymph (n=16)). Injections of\noctopamine depressed feeding in unparasitized M. sexta. The wasp larvae were not the\nsource of the host's increased octopamine. Feeding was also temporarily depressed in M.\nsextaby injecting sephadex beads, bacteria (Serratiamarcescens)or lipopolysaccharides\n(derived from S. marcescens).In all 3 cases, octopamine concentration in the hemolymph\nincreased after injection (18.7 ± 4.2 to 54.7 ± 7.8 pg/µL hemolymph for bacteria-injected,\nn=lO)). Feeding resumed with the decline in octopamine levels. Sephadex beads, bacteria,\nlipopolysaccharides and the emerging wasp larvae all activate the host's immune system.\nThe data are consistent with the hypothesis that part of the parasite's ability to suppress\nhost feeding involves permanently activating mechanisms that suppress feeding during an\nimmune challenge."}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T29", "patch": {"abstract": "Immediately following an uninformative peripheral stimulus (cue) there is a short-lasting facilitation of response times in the region of the cue which is followed by a longer lasting inhibition. This inhibitory effect of the cue upon subsequent responses to targets was named inhibition of return (IOR) to capture the dominant interpretation that, after having oriented to a location in space, attention is inhibited from returning there. This phenomenon has been the subject of intense interest because of its putative role in improving our ability to forage the visual environment for consequential information (Posner & Cohen, 1984; Klein, 1988; see Taylor & Klein, in press, for a review). I will present evidence from various methods in cognitive neuroscience which converge on: oculomotor programming as the cause of the inhibition, localization dependent processes as affected by the inhibition, enhanced search efficiency as one function of the inhibition, and the superior colliculus as the main neural structure involved in generating the inhibition. @"}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T36", "patch": {"abstract": "The fruitfly, Drosophila melanogaster, has long been used a vital tool for neuroscientific research of a genetic and anatomical nature. Because of its stereotypical pattern of development and its relatively simple nervous system, Drosophila is a powerful tool for understanding the relationship between gene and neurotransmitter expression and development. I will present several views of the development of this simple nervous system, considering how information about gene and neurotransmitter expression can be related to the actual anatomy of the developing CNS. Semi-thin sections of embryonic tissue have been serially aligned and, from these sections, I have developed a computerised, three-dimensional anatomical atlas of the Drosophila nervous system. Images of this atlas will be considered, alongside images produced via fluorescence immunohistochemistry and confocal microscopy."}}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"abstract": "Activation of D1 and D2 dopamine receptors in the nucleus accumbens (NAc) is important for the rewarding effect of various reinforcers including brain stimulation. Blockade of D2, but not D3 or D4, receptors in this region with dopamine antagonists increases the threshold of reinforcement for brain stimulation. Activation of D 1 receptors is necessary to activate D2 receptors._ In the present study, the reward mechanism within NAc was studied by using falphostin C, a selective inhibitor of protein kinase C. The subjects were 42 male albino rats--:-nachof them was implanted with a bipolar electrode into the medial fore brain bundle and two cannulae bilaterally into NAc. They were trained to press a bar to receive electrical stimulation, and the threshold of reinforcing effect was measured before and after the injection of calphostin through the cannulae. Bilateral injection of calphostin into NAc increased the threshold of reinforcing effect in 2 hours and the effect reached the maximus in 4-6 hours. Recovery was observed in 24 to 48 hours after injection. Unilateral injection, either ipsilateral or contralateral to the electrode, was not effective. The results suggest that the rewarding effect of medial fore-brain stimulation is mediated by the activity of protein kinase C in NAc neurons."}}
{"year": 1999, "entry_id": "T22", "patch": {"abstract": "There is currently debate regarding the effect of cues on the learning of subjects with Alzheimer's\nDisease (AD). Some have suggested that cuing is particularly important in AD, whereas others don't\nsupport this facilitation effect. This study examined responses on the Buschke Cued Recall Test\n(BCRT) to compare free and cued recall in groups of subjects in the Canadian Study of Health and\nAging with either AD or isolated memory impairment. Subjects with isolated memory impairment\nperformed better than the AD subjects on all measures. However, both groups benefitted to a similar\nextent from cues on the initial learning trials and both had a similar rate of learning on the free recall\ntrials. The quantitative but not qualitative differences in performance of the groups suggests that many\nsubjects with isolated memory impairment are in the pre-clinical stages of AD. The positive learning\nslope for the AD group suggests that a cued recall procedure can facilitate learning in AD subjects.\nKeynote Speech:"}}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T14", "patch": {"abstract": "Replacing the clogged arteries feeding the heart is a well-established operation for patients with\nischemic heart disease. It is called coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG). The traditional methods of\nplacing the patient on a heart-lung machine during the operation will be compared with a newer\ntechnique of operating on the beating heart. This talk reviews the literature and outlines a randomized,\nprospective, clinical trial comparing the neuropsychological and quality of life outcomes of patients\nundergoing these two techniques. The aim of this study is to evaluate longer term (six month)\npsychosocial outcomes. For the first time, the goal is to investigate the outcomes of women compared\nto men. Students looking for comprehensive projects over the next 3 years, persons interested in\ncritiquing the proposal, and the mildly curious are most welcome.\nTl 5."}}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T16", "patch": {"abstract": "This project investigated the influences of child age and parent informant (mother versus father report)\non the associations between parenting practices and conduct problem behaviour in a community sample\nof children aged 5 to 12. Valid sample size for the computed regressions varied from 335 to 339.\nParenting practices were assessed using a modified version of the Alabama Parenting Questionnaire\n(APQ; Frick, 1991). Conduct problems were defined by DSM-IV criteria for Oppositional Defiant\nDisorder (ODD) and Conduct Disorder (CD), and assessed through the use of the Assessment of\nDisruptive Symptoms, DSM-IV Version (ADS-IV; Pelham, Gnagy, Greenslade, & Milich, 1992). Both\nmothers and fathers acted as informants for the two questionnaires. Preliminary analyses suggest that\nthe parenting practices of maternal involvement, poor monitoring and supervision of children's\nactivities, as well as inconsistent discipline, are significantly associated with number of CD and number\nof ODD symptoms in children. The magnitude of these associations varied according to whether it was\nthe mothers or the fathers who reported the practices. In contrast with previous research in a clinical\nsample, results did not show a significant child age trend in the associations. This project has significant\nimplications for the parent training component of the psychosocial interventions that are currently used\nfor CD and ODD.\nTl 7."}}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15", "patch": {"abstract": "This study will examine the predictive validity of attachment security and pain behaviour following both\neveryday pain incidents and acute pain incidents. The present study will be conducted with a cohort of\nfifty, five-year-old children, followed since 6 months of age, and their mothers. The children's faces will\nbe videotaped during their 5-year medically indicated inoculation shot. Children's pain reaction will be\ncoded using the Children's Facial Coding Scale and parent-child interactions will be assessed with the\nChild Adult Medical Procedure Interaction Scale. Following the needle, both mothers and children will\nprovide ratings of subjective pain intensity and pain behaviour. Mothers will also complete diaries\nfollowing four everyday pain incidents that their child experiences. Included in the diary is information\nconcerning the child's reaction and subsequent parental response. Quality of attachment will be assessed\nusing a Separation-Reunion procedure, the Separation Anxiety Test, and the Pain and Relationship Task.\nIt is hypothesized that attachment security classification will predict children's response to and\nbehaviour following painful incidents. The mediating effect of maternal sensitivity, initially collected at\nboth 6 and 18 months of age, will be also examined. Multimodal procedures will also be used to\nexamine the role of third variables that may account for these potential relations. These will include\nreceptive language, emotional regulation, and emotional awareness.\nTl 6."}}
{"year": 2002, "entry_id": "P10", "patch": {"abstract": "The purpose of this research was to create a comprehensive database of behavioral phenotypes for inbred mouse strains. We examined the behaviour of twenty-four A/J, Balb/cByJ and Molf/ei mice on measures of exploration, anxiety, learning and memory in a standardized test battery (Brown et al., 2000). Anxiety-related behaviors were measured using the elevated zero maze, elevated plus maze and light-dark box test. Exploration and locomotor ability were tested in the open field and Rota Rod. Spatial memory was examined using the Morris water maze and Barnes maze. There were significant differences among the three strains. The A/J strain was the most anxious in the elevated plus maze, elevated zero maze and the light/dark box. The Molf/ei had the greatest locomotor ability and explored to a greater extent in the open field than the other strains. In addition, the Molf/ei strain had the best spatial ability of the three strains in both the Barnes maze and Morris water maze. Pl 1."}}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T16", "patch": {"abstract": "Caffeine is the most widely used psychostimulant in the world. However, neuronal mechanisms\nmediating its stimulatory effect are not well understood. We recently reported, using c-Fos as a\nmarker for neuronal activation, that psychostimulant doses of caffeine induce activation of\nhypocretin/orexin-containing neurons which play an important role in arousal. Here we\nexamined whether other components of the arousal system, specifically aminergic neuronal\ngroups, are also activated by caffeine, by using dual immunostaining for c-Fos and aminergic\ntransmitter markers. We found that low locomotor-stimulant doses of caffeine (10 and 30 mg/kg,\ni.p.) increase Fos immunoreactivity in noradrenergic neurons in the locus coeruleus and\nhistaminergic neurons in the tuberomammillary nucleus, as well as in orexin-containing neurons\nof the hypothalamus, but not in serotonergic neurons in the dorsal raphe nucleus. A higher,\nlocomotor-depressant dose of caffeine (75 mg/kg, i.p.) induces c-Fos expression in all of these\nneurons. Dopaminergic neurons in the ventral tegmental area and substantia nigra did not\nrespond to caffeine with changes in c-Fos expression. These results indicate that caffeine induces\nc-Fos expression differentially among aminergic arousal-related cell groups. The noradrenergic\nand histaminergic neurons and orexin-containing neurons which are activated at low doses of\ncaffeine might play a role in mediating behavioral activation induced by caffeine.\nTl 7)"}}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T19", "patch": {"abstract": "Cooper's (1994) model of drinking motivations distinguishes between two groups of\ndrinkers at risk of drinking problems - those who drink to enhance positive mood and\nthose who drink to cope with negative mood. We investigated whether these groups\ndiffer in their activation of implicit alcohol cognition following mood induction.\nParticipants were 86 undergraduates with elevated scores on the Enhancement or Coping\nMotives (EM or CM) subscale of the Drinking Motives Questionnaire. Participants in\neach motive group were randomly assigned to a musically-induced positive or negative\nmood condition. A modified Stroop (1935) task, involving color-naming of alcohol and\nnon-alcohol control words, was administered following mood induction. As\nhypothesized, EM drinkers in the positive (but not negative) mood condition showed\nsignificantly longer color-naming speeds for alcohol vs. control words indicating\ninterference in color-naming by the content of the alcohol words. Even though CM\ndrinkers in the positive mood condition did not show evidence of selective processing of\nalcohol cues (as expected), CM drinkers in the negative mood condition also failed to\nshow evidence of alcohol interference. Overall, CM drinkers showed significantly longer\ncolor-naming latencies than EM drinkers suggesting possible ceiling effects in the CM\ngroup. Theoretical and clinical implications will be discussed.\nNew poster\nPl I)"}}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T20", "patch": {"abstract": "People show great variation in their language and reading proficiency, even within the normal\npopulation. Historically, language function was viewed as somewhat separate from basic\nperceptual and cognitive processes. Some experts now suggest that problems with auditory and\nvisual perception underlie language disorders. In particular, dyslexia has been theorized to be a\ntemporal processing disorder, in which children cannot normally perceive auditory and/or visual\nevents that occur quickly in time. Over the past 15 years, many studies have provided empirical\nsupport for this theory of language function, but most of this research has specifically targeted\nhighly-selected and clinically-impaired children or adults. Therefore, the present study will aim\nto identify the basic perceptual skills that are most highly correlated with language and reading\nabilities in normal subjects (ages 6 to 17). The same subjects will complete various tests of\nauditory and visual temporal processing, language, and reading performance. Statistical analysis will then identify the basic perceptual skills that covary with language and reading proficiency.\nThis research will help us understand the development of language in the general population, and\nwill have implications for the treatment of developmental language delay in children.\nT2 l)"}}
{"year": 2010, "entry_id": "T24", "patch": {"abstract": "The Cognitive Failures Questionnaire (CFQ) is widely used to assess frequency of everyday slips/errors even though its factor structure is unclear. Using data from 2394 female and 921 male undergraduates, the present study compared the principle components structures for 3 through 7 factors, using both orthogonal and non-orthogonal rotations. The best structure was a 4-factor solution with non-orthogonal rotation. For the males, the best was a non-orthogonal 4-factor solution while for the females, the best was a non-orthogonal 3-factor solution. A subset of 484 students completed the CFQ more than once. It demonstrated good test-retest reliability at 1 year.\n5:00-6:00"}}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44", "patch": {"abstract": "Inhibition of return (IOR) is thought to improve the efficiency of visual search behaviour by biasing attention, eye movements, or both, toward novel stimuli. Previous research suggests that IOR might arise from sensory, attentional or motor programming processes. In the present study, we were interested in determining if IOR could instead arise from a simple late-stage motor output bias, independent from effects on earlier processes. Participants made consecutive saccades (from a common starting location) to central arrowhead stimuli. We removed the possible contribution of sensory/attentional and motor preparation effects in IOR by allowing participants to fully prepare their responses in advance of an execution signal. When responses were delayed to allow response preparation, we continued to observe IOR. Our data therefore provide evidence that IOR can result from a simple motor execution bias that may arise from inhibitory effects on motor output neurons controlling the extraocular muscles directly."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50", "patch": {"abstract": "While quantitative methods in psychology"}}
{"year": 2024, "entry_id": "P44", "patch": {"abstract": "Good sleep health plays a vital role in adults' overall health and well-being; however, access to evidence-based sleep health resources is limited. The current study aims to assess the usability and feasibility of the ABCs of SLEEPING for Adults mobile app which provides evidence-based recommendations to improve sleep health based on an assessment of current sleep habits. Twenty adults will a) review and use the app, b) participate in an interview where they will provide feedback on the usability of the app by answering questions based on Morville & Sullenger's (2010) \"User Experience Honeycomb\" framework, and c) provide feedback pre- and post-intervention via questionnaires to assess the app's feasibility (including its implementation and preliminary effectiveness). The feedback from participants who reviewed and used the app will be incorporated into a modified version. This app has the potential to be an accessible resource for adults to promote sleep health, and if deemed usable and feasible, our next steps will be to test the full-scale effectiveness."}}
