but does not interfere    with cerebral protein\n                o-Jv~i,~                 synthesis,   does not produce amnesia.    I now report that aminoglutethi-\n                         ~,              rnide suppresses adrenomedullary function (secretion       of epinephrine),\n0~                                       and that it produces amnesia if epinephrine is supplemented.\n~\\.~_,\n~~ \\                             22.     N. t\\llen   & J.       Barresi   - Competence Information and Extrinsic      Reward\n-'\\\\y-,\\J~\\\\                                                                Effects on Intrinsic  Motivation.\n~~\\    1\nru'))::i/\n                                                   Extrinsic reward has been shown to decrease rather than\n                                         increase performance (or liking) of intrinsically         motivated activities.\n~~~~f~                                   It has also been found that performance information (positive or\n> ~\\1'0 ~                                negative) changes intrinsic      motivation in the direction of the com~\n,~,.:'()", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 17 at: 'M. Cynader'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Orthographic and Semantic Access to the Memory Trace.", "authors_raw": "M. Ozier", "abstract": "The episodic memory trace was studied by having subjects\n      attempt to access the memory trace according to different           types of\n      retrieval     codes.  The results    indicated that the first letter of the\n      name of a word may function as a retrieval         code only if it is inten-\n      tionally     marked as such, whereas the categoric meaning of a word is\n      marked for retrieval     purposes automatically.      In addition,   it was\n      found that the names of words are not linked directly           to one another\n      in the lexical dictionary,        but the meaning of words have direct\n      connections.      These results have implications     for theories of encoding\n      specificity,     the organization    of the mental lexicon, and a speech-\n      production hypothesis of initial-letter        cueing effects.\n\n27.   K. Bloom·_ Neonatal    Assessment as a Model for Medical/Social        Change.\n\nNeonatal assessment is a structured        procedure in which\n      defined behaviors are observed and elicited.           This process yields\n      not only an objective description       of the newborn's medical and\n      behavioral   status, but also a generalized       affect upon the quality\n      of the observer's    subjective    judgments.    In the former and traditional\n      way, the assessment procedure is used as a dependent variable.             In\n      the latter way, assessment is viewed as an independent variable or\n      treatment of the adult (e.g., pediatrician,          parent, child-care\n      specialist).     The value of structured      behavioral assessment for\n      teaching, primary medical care and research will be illustrated            with\n      examples from pediatrics,       developmental and clinical    psychology.\n\n9.\n\n28.   T. Whalen - The Power of Learning Theories.\n\nThe nature of a theory of learning may be determined using\n      theoretical   machines called finite automata.   There is some finite\n      automaton which will behave in the same way as any organism.        As an\n      organism learns, however, it changes its behaviour.      Therefore, there\n      will be a way to change a finite automaton so that it also behaves in\n      this new way: A description     of these changes will be equivalent to a\n      theory of learning.    If it can be shown that a particular    process is\n      required to alter a finite automaton so that it learns appropriate\n      behaviour, a theory of learning must also incorporate     this process.\n      For example, if it can be shown that something more than stimulus-\n      response associations   are required for a \"naive\" finite automaton\n      to learn some behaviour, then S-R theories will not be sufficient       to\n      account for this lea", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25 at: 'M. Ozier'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "6-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Social Play Levels in Young Rhesus Monkeys.", "authors_raw": "L. White", "abstract": "Levels of social play of immature rhesus monkeys living in\n         small captive groups are extremely variable,      and depend, to some extent,\n         on the composition of the social group.. It can be difficult       to pick out\n         developmental changes in the social play tendencies of a single individ-\n         ual, as any change in interaction    level or type is the result of changes\n         in the behaviour of both interacting     animals.   Here the importance of\n         studying individual  behaviour in the context of the social group is\n         emphasized, and an attempt is made to assign responsibility      for changes\n         in play level more to one play partner than to the other.\n\n3.\n                             8.     T. Whalen - Remembering Processes                        in the Pigeon.\n\nDepending on the requirements of the situation,                           it is\n                                            believed that an organism, such as a pigeon, can either remember a\n                                            stimulus or a future behaviour required by the present stimulus.                                      Honig\n                                            has shown that in situations                in which a pigeon is only required to\n                                            remember whether to peck or not, remembering occurs over longer inter-\n                                            vals than are normally found with procedures which require the recall\n                                            of a stimulus.    The present research uses a procedure which also requires\n                                            only that the pigeon remember whether to respond or not,                               It is simpler\n                                            than those that have been used previously.                        Since this seems to produce\n                                             as much recall in pigeons as Honig's procedure, this hypothesis is\n                                            supported.            ·.         .                             ·..       . _,,--.~ _,,-. _..,,,.--\n                                                                                                                                            _,,..,,...\n                                                                                                                                                  __,,,----\n           ,,.1,J~,,...__/--~,_,,,,_,,,...._~.               ~ ____,,,\n                                                                   ,./,._,,. _ ~- •. - ---•./. /. ~ /   ./ • ./                                    ----", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 6 at: 'L. White'"}
