{"year": 1984, "entry_id": "5-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Trigeminal     Control    Of Ingestive      and Grooming Sequences.", "authors_raw": "K. Berridge", "abstract": "We're currently      examining sensorimotor         interactions      in the production     of\n                            taste-elicited        fixed action     patterns      and grooming sequences         in rats.\n        -~         ,·       We're employing a trigeminal         deafferentation         procedure    that eliminates\n                           j.?,c,ti le input from the face and mouth while preserving                 intact  all motor\n  fll-'     •\n                    t,\n           'i~J.l_,J1_\n                            efferent\n                      ·,, v issues:\n                                           and gustatory    afferent\n                                          1) the role of non-taste\n                                                                          neurons.\n                                                                         afferent\n                                                                                          This study addresses\n                                                                                      information    in the assessment\n                                                                                                                      two\n\nltU~, \\. 01', of food palatability,                      and 2) the role of tactile           sensory feedback in the\n             ,.jjj_;>•      production      of ingestive   and grooming movements and sequences.\n   .     ~ 1,,,   ----           •\n  1;1,   •\n                    7.   J. Barresi     & E. Wyatt\n                         Dead or Alive:        When Motion Becomes Intention.\n                         ------\n                         A single      object    moved on a Apple-controlled           monitor     according     to a\n                         quantifiable      rule.    Human observers      were asked to evaluate       its motion on\n                         six Likert Scales:         Mechanical,    Random, Purposive,       Intelligent,       Alive,\n                         and Human. The proportion              of foreward   versus    27° turns of the object\n                         affected     judgements on some of these scales.            Whether or not the object\n                         occasionally        stopped and changed direction          also affected        judgements.\n                         However, complex interactions              involving   sex of subject        and stimulus\n                         appearance argue against any simple interpretation               of these results.\n\n2", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 5 at: 'K. Berridge'"}
{"year": 1985, "entry_id": "5-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Effects      of Paraventricular    Nuclei Lesions on Entrainment               of Circadian Activity     Rhythms to Restricted   Feeding in the Rat", "authors_raw": "R. Mistlberger     & B. Rusak", "abstract": "Periodic      food availability       cycles     (2h food - 22h fast)        can entrain       a\n           variety    of circadian    rhythms in rats.         The phase angle of entrainment           is\n           such that these rhythms anticipate             the daily mealtime;       for example, the\n           rat becomes active 2-3h before mealtime.              The neural mechanisms mediating\n           anticipatory,      food entrainable      rhythms are functionally          and antomically\n           distinct     from those controlling        free running,      light entrainable       rhythms\n           since suprachiasmatic           nuclei lesions      abolish    or severely    disrupt     free\n           running but not food anticipatory            rhythms,     Previous attempts     to localize\n           critical     components of the food entrainment             mechanism indicate      that the\n\n2\n\npineal     and adrenal           glands,     the hypophysis         and the ventromedial\n              hypothalamus      are non-essential.           The present    study investigates        whether\n              the paraventricular            nuclei    (PVN) might be involved,          in view of their\n              purported     role in the regulation            of food intake and the preminence              of\n              food intake       over light        in the phase control         of certain     PVN receptor\n              rhythms.      Circadian         locomotor     rhythms    were monitored        in 9 rats on\n              restricted     food schedules (2h diurnal           mealtime) for 2 weeks prior to and\n              3 weeks after        bilateral        PVN ablation.       Six rats     displayed      signs of\n              obesity typically        associated      with PVN lesions.      Anticipatory     activity    was\n              markedly attenuated            in 3 of these rats and largely            unaffected       in the\n              remaining     6. The animals will be tested              again after several         months to\n              assess the stability         of this effect.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 5 at: 'R. Mistlberger'"}
{"year": 1987, "entry_id": "23-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Comparison of pavlovian   conditioned  inhibition                  procedures   having different temporal arrangements  of excitor and inhibitor                  on nonreinforced    trials", "authors_raw": "c. Reed-Elder,       v.M. LoLordo", "abstract": "Pigeons were trained           with simultaneous           (Sim) or serial    (Ser) Pavlovian\n    conditioned    inhibition       procedures.       Transfer of inhibition      was tested.        In\n    the first   test,   the inhibitor       was presented in various temporal arrangements\n    with the training       excitor    (transfer     across procedures).       In the second test,\n    the inhibitor      was presented         in compound with a second excitor             (transfer\n    across excitors).         Inhibitors       conditioned      with Ser procedures      suppressed\n    responding     both Sim and Ser trials               but did not suppress       responding       to\n    another excitor.       Inhibitors     established       with a Sim procedure       transferred\n    across excitors     but showed poor transfer            to Ser procedures.\n\n8\n\n2 5. R. 0 ' Shea\n\nOrientation          tuning   and binocularity         of binocular-rivalry   adaptation    in human\n    vision\n\nSubjects      viewed adaptation          stimuli       for l minute.        Then two rival       test\n    gratings,      differing    in orientation         from each other by 90 , were presented\n    one to each eye, for l minute and subjects                 recorded binocular       rivalry.     When\n    one eye was adapted,          rivalry     alternations      were briefer      for adaptation       and\n    test    gratings       of similar      orientation,        especially       in the adapted        eye.\n    However, when both eyes were adapted                    by rival   gratings,     the duration       of\n    rivalry    alternations     increased       in both eyes equally,         to produce symmetrical\n    U-shaped orientation            functions,         This implies       that rivalry      adaptation\n    affects    only binocular      units in the human visual system,·\n\n26, M, Brennan\n\nIndividual          Differences      in Attention:           Type~     and Type Band      Cognitive\n     Failure\n\nA significant       negative    correlation        was found between         two self-report\n     measures:      the JAS (Jenkins Activity          Survey) and the CFQ (Cognitive         Failure\n     Questionnaire).         The JAS is used to distinguish                  Type A from Type B\n     individuals.       The CFQ assesses       a person's      absent-mindedness      and everyday\n     errors,      Thus, the correlation         showed that Type A's reported           low CFQ and\n     Type B's reported      high CFQ, Previous          literature      has shown that ( 1) Type A\n     and Type B individuals       differ    in their attentional", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 23 at: 'c. Reed-Elder'"}
{"year": 1988, "entry_id": "5-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Myriad      Mind:           Steps   Toward~      Science        of Persons.", "authors_raw": "J. Barresi", "abstract": "Psychologists        have given        insufficient        attention        to the possible            use of\n                  biographical         materials        involving       whole     lives     as a data         base     for the\n                  development      of the psychology            of persons.        In a book that           I am currently\n                  working     on, I will argue for an approach                  for using such data which treats\n                  individual       lives       as a unit.         According       to this        approach,         competing\n                  theories       would      be developed           to account        for    the      causal      history      of\n                  particular       lives,       and the power         of these       theories         would    be assessed\n                  relative     to alternative        theories       in terms of their           simplicity,        coherence,\n                  and plausability           in accounting         for the particular           life,     and in terms        of\n                  the generality          and testability          of their    principles         in applying         to other\n                  lives.\n·--------\n            14.   P. Dunham,         F, Dunham and          c. Davis\n                  Mother      Care     and    Other       Care:     Some Differences             in Mother-Infant        Social\n                  Structure:----\n\nWhile studying       the structure      of mother-infant       social                   interactions,         we\n                  encountered     some unexpected      and interesting     differences                       when comparing\n                  mothers     employed   outside    the home and mothers       who care                    for their    infants\n                  full-time     in the home.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 5 at: 'J. Barresi'"}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "28-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Communicative Imitation in mother-infant and stranger-infant dyads during the first year.", "authors_raw": "Maria Legerstee", "abstract": "This study focused on the development of imitation between infants, their mothers and female\n       strangers, and how these behaviors of the participants changed over time. Eight infants were\n       observed longitudinally during the first year of life in natural interactions with the adults. Five\n       behaviors were measured of the interactants: Mouth Open, Eye Open, Lip Protrusion, Smiling,\n       Negative Face and Vocalizing. Lag sequential analyses were performed for each dependent variable.\n       The z-score calculations were subsequently adjusted for the effects of autocorrelations. Significant\n       imitative patterns for all behaviors occurred for the infants and adults at various points throughout\n       development, although the vocalizations of the infants suppressed those of the adults. However,\n       imitative development was not uniform. Peaks in imitative development occurred between 9 and 23\n       weeks for both infants and adults and between 34 and 45 weeks for infant and mother only. Log\n       linear analyses revealed that significantly more imitative responding took place between mother\n       and infant, than between stranger and infant. Differential imitative responsiveness occurred as early\n       as three weeks for mouth open and vocalizations, and significantly more smiles of the mother were\n       imitated throughout development. The study reveals that imitation is an intergral part of infant\n       communication and illustrates the usefullness of this paradigm for investigating the development of\n       imitation during the first year.\n\n30.    Jenny Ryon, Richard Brown, and John Fentress\n\nBringing home the bacon: food provisioning within a captive pack of coyotes (Canis latrans)\n\nSocial behaviour in a pack of coyotes was observed for six years. This report concerns pup and\n       related feeding by adults. All adult members of coyote packs feed young. Some members also feed\n       pregnant and lactating females and yearlings. In our study, feeding began just before the birth of\n       pups and continued for about 24 weeks. One adult male (Obie) was the only individual to feed the\n       mother as well as the pups in the two years pups were born. The mother, another adult male and\n       adult female also.fed the pups in these two years. Obie and the mother but not the other adults also\n       fed the yearlings. All males were vasectomized before the mating season of the third year, thus no\n       further pups were born. Obie continued to feed his mate (the mother in past years) at the appropriate\n       time of year (i.e., just before the expected time of birth, as measured from the time of mating). He\n       also fed his \"pups\" from previous years. He continued this pattern of feeding for four years\n       (until his death) despite the fact that one of the male \"pups\" he fed had", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28 at: 'Maria Legerstee'"}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "32-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "What the eye tells the brain declines with increasing retinal eccentricity: but does it do so differently\n       for good and poor readers?", "authors_raw": "Ray Klein, Glen Berry, Kevin Briand and Barbara D'Entremont", "abstract": "Geiger & Lettvin answer this question affirmatively in a recent article in the prestigious New England\n       Journal of Medicine. In their study normal readers were more accurate at reporting letters near\n       fixation than dyslexic readers, but at greater eccentricities the dyslexics were better. This pattern\n       survived several methodological improvements imposed by psychophysically minded psychologists\n       (W. Dember et al), suggesting a basic difference in the eye-brain interface. Close scrutiny of both\n       studies reveals several methodological flaws, which leave wide open the possibility that the dyslexic\n       and normal readers use different attentional strategies. Following closely the task used by Geiger &\n       Lettvin and Dember, but improving upon their displays to minimize the possibility of strategy\n       differences, we seek to provide a more definitive answer to our title. Other research bearing on the\n       nature of dyslexia may be described.\n\n34.    Alan Kingstone\n\n\"Great Expectations\" and other tales of attention and set.\n\nDelayed crossing the Atlantic Ocean", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 32 at: '3 3. Ray Klein'"}
