{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "19-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Neuromotor maturation and the ontogeny of ultrasonic vocalizations in the California mouse (peromyscus californicus) Ten female and eleven male P. californicuspups from 8 litters were individually marked, weighed and tested for ultrasonic vocalizations (UVs). UVs, locomotion, surface righting, negative geotaxis, acoustic startle reflex and eye opening were recorded from 2 to 30 days of age. UVs at 37, 42, 47 and 52 kHz were digitized and recorded by computer and an event recorder program which was simultaneously used to record locomotor behaviour. Results were analyzed by sex of pup and litter size. Put weight was • negatively correlated with UVs (r=-.58, p<.05). UVs decreased as pups aged (p<.01). Females vocalized more than males (p<.01) and vocalizationsincreased for both males and females after they spent more than 180 sin coordinated movement (p<0.01). There was no effect of litter siu on UVs. After the auditory startle reflex was shown, UVs decreased significantly (p<.01). Although there was no effect of eye openingon UVs, pups from litters of two opened their eyes earlier than pups from larger litters {p<.01). Males opened their eyes earlier than females (p<.05). These results indicate that P. californicus has a pattern of UV development that is related to weight, age, sex, development of coordinated movement and auditory startle reflex. Surface righting, negative geotaxis and eye opening were not related to the developmentof UVs.", "authors_raw": "Sandra L. Wright", "abstract": "• 10-\n\n--   -----    ··--·-------------~---------\n\n21.   Steve Shaw, Kathy Kokic and Don MacIntosh\n      Ears on insect knees\n             Crickets carry a pair of directionally-selectivehearing organs on their forelegs, which they\n             use to home in on the calling songs of potential mates. They are distantly related to\n             cockroaches, which have a simpler organ that until recently was believed to respond only\n             to vibration, but which we showed last year also responds sensitively to sound. The\n             roach subgenual (\"below the knee\") organ is particularly interesting in that it forms a\n             conceptual bridge to explain the evolution of the more elaborate, pure auditory cricket's\n             ear from an ancestral pure vibration receptor. We have found, unexpectedly, that the roach\n             ear is also strongly directional. According to the standard physical theory applied to\n             insect hearing organs, possession of directionality implies the presence of two sound\n             input pathways to the organ. In crickets, the two entry points are an external tympanum\n             on the leg, and internal air tubes (tracheae) connected to openings (spiracles) on the si", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 19 at: 'Sandra L. Wright'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "- 13 -", "authors_raw": "•   J.A. Goldman and J.C. Fentress\n        Does the squeaking wolf always get the response?\n              Research at the Dalhousie Animal Behaviour Field Station (DABFS) is currently\n              examining communication between a mother timber wolf and her pups, during the first 5\n              postnatal weeks. Previous work on activity inside the den, has shown that although the\n              mother rarely responds to her pups' vocalizations with overt behaviours, she does monitor\n              their vocal output by exhibiting subtle changes in ear direction. Now, the pups'\n              responsiveness to the mother's vocalizations is under investigation. A 460-hour\n              videotape database permits examination of vocal and behavioral activity inside the den, as\n              well as, vocalizations which occur outside the den. Pup behaviour is coded for response\n              to the adult 'Squeak', a common social vocalization. Preliminary data suggests that not\n              all 'Squeaks' elicit the same response.", "abstract": "30.    David Colquhoun\n       Neuropsychological assessment of subcortical dementia in\n       Huntington's Disease\n              Individuals with Huntington's Disease and Dementia of Alzheimer's Type (DAT) were\n              examined on a neuropsychological battery designed to assess frontal, memory, and\n              language abilities. The purpose of testing both DAT and HD subjects was to examine\n              the distinctiveness of cortical and subcortical dementias and, by doing so, clarify the\n              possible role that the basal ganglia pathology has in the mediation diverse set of\n              cognitive proc~.      This comparison is especially important in light of the lackof direct\n              comparisons made between HD and DAT. It was hypothesized that deficits in HD would\n              be characterized by focal frontal deficits and subtle declines in memory while DAT would\n              be madced by language difficulties coupled with generafu.edmemory deficits. Preliminary\n              analysis indicates the existence of qualitative differences between HD and DAT which\n              appear to reflect divergent pathological processes. It is proposed that cognitive changes in\n            • HD and DAT support the position that dementia may be differentiated in terms of a\n              cortical/subcorticaldimension.\n\n3 1.   Kazue Semba\n       What does the shape of neurons tell you about what neurons do?:\n       Morphology of cholinergic and non-cholinergic cortically projecting\n       neurons in the rat basal fore brain\n             Neurons appear in different shapes. Whatever factors might be involved for these various\n             shapes to form during development and then change during normal aging (as well as in\n             pathological conditions), neuronal morphology often provides interesting insights as to\n             functions of ind", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28 at: '29. • J.A. Goldman an'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Comprehension strategies of young children Previous research (Shatz, 1978) has indicated that young children are biased to respond to language with action. This study attempted to replicate this finding in a group of 64 24 month olds. These children heard 30 prerecorded sentences differing in syntax presented through a speaker in a robot (thereby eliminating extralinguistic cues such as gesture and gaze). Their responses were videotaped and coded as Action, Informing, or Other. Results indicated that the children were not biased to respond with action, and were able to discriminate among the five sentence types. The data suggest that this discrimination may be based on surface markers such as the presence of an action verb, and the mention of an object present in the immediate context", "authors_raw": "Nameera Akhtar and Philip J. Dunham", "abstract": "- 15 -\n\n36.   Valerie Bolivar and John Barresi\n      The secret to creating life\n            Do humans equate spontaneous movement with being alive and having internal states?\n            Do children think the same way as adults on these issues? Recently, researchers have\n            been grappling with the effects of movement patterns on animacy and intentionality\n            attributions. Unfortunately, most of these researchers have used objects familiar to the\n            subject and hence they are subject to biases associated with previous experience. In the\n            present study, we examine the role of endogenous movement in the attribution of\n            animacy, motivation and internal states to unfamiliar objects. Subjects in grades 1, 4 and\n            7 and university were asked to respond to the following statement \"Tell me a story about\n            what you have just seen\", after viewing a computer generated display consisting of two\n            circular stimuli exhibiting three types of movement Results indicate that age, gender, as\n            well as movement patterns all contribute to differences in these attributions.\n\n37.   Mark Farrell and Raymond M. Klein\n      The effect of regional compactness upon region discrimination time\n      is modulated by oculomotor programming\n            Podgomy & Shepard (1983) demonstrated that reaction time to determine if a target is on\n            or off an attended region decreased with increasing compacbless of that region. Six\n            experiments explored the nature of this compacbless effect and its relationship to visual\n            attention. Subjects viewed a 3 x 3 grid in which there were shaded and unshaded regions.\n            In four experiments their task was to determine a) if a target letter appearing in the shaded\n            or unshaded region was a Tor L, orb) if a target stimulus was presented in the shaded or\n            unshaded region. Eye position monitoring was used to ensur", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 34 at: 'Nameera Akhtar and Philip J. Dunham'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The relationship between catastrophizing and negative affect Two studies were conducted to examine the cognitive-affective correlates of catastrophizing. Catastrophizing has been defined as a tendency to engage in excessively negative cognitions related to aversive stimuli such as pain. Study 1 examined the reliability and construct validity of a self-report measure of catastrophizing cognitions. A 13 item scale, developed for this study was shown to have high internal consistency (alpha = .90). In addition, the scale showed the same relationship with subcomponents of depressive symptomatology shown with clinical measures of catastrophizing. Study 2 examined subjects evaluations of the valiance of positive, negative and pain-related words following a success or failure experience. Results indicated that catastrophizers who experienced success on a problem solving task rated positive and pain-related words more negatively than noncatastrophizers. Study 2 also addressed the test-retest reliability of the catastrophizing measure. The results are discussed in terms of the relationship between catastrophizing and negative affect", "authors_raw": "Scott Bishop", "abstract": "44.        Chris Moore\n                           Imagination and social understanding\n                                 It has been claimed that social understanding is achieved not so much through the\n                                 development and application of a \"theory of mind\" but through the ability to pretend or\n                                 imagine self in situations appropriate to another time or person. In this paper, I discuss\n                                 recent work of ours on social reasoning tasks, in which children's judgements have to be\n                                 made either from a third-person perspective or from an imagined first-person perspective.\n                                 Initial results seem to support the idea that imagined or pretend contexts facilitate social\n                                 reasoning.\n\n,---··\n\n- 18 -\n\n-   -   -·-------                 -~--------                                                                                     --~-   -----   ---\n\n45.   J.H. Brandstatter,H.S. Seyan and I.A. Meinertzhagen\n      The dynamic properties of synapses in the fly's lamina\n            In the first optic neuropile, or lamina. beneath the fly's (Musca domestica L.) compound\n            eye photoreceptor terminals", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 42 at: '4 3. Scott Bishop'"}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T11-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "DOES ATTENTION MEDIA TE THE RELATION BETWEEN\n          CATASTROPHIZING AND PAIN?", "authors_raw": "Scott Bishop", "abstract": "Catastrophizing has been identified as an individual difference variable that\n                 contributes to increased distress reactions during painful experiences.\n                 Catastrophizing has been described as a tendency to engage in pain-related negative\n                 ideation characterized by rumination, magnification of threat, and lack of confidence\n                 and control. Research has been consistent in showing that catastrophizing is\n                 associated with increased pain and emotional distress during painful stimulaton.\n                         However, there has been little research examining the mechanisms that\n                 mediate the relation between catastrophizing and distress reactions. Based on recent\n                 findings in our lab, I will present a model in which will suggest that attentional\n                 processes mediate the relation between catastrophizing and pain. Future research\n                 and implications will also be discussed.\n\nT13.    Michael Antle, Hugh Piggins, & Benjamin Rusak\n\nGetting a GRiP on GRouP GRoPe in the Light\n\nIn rodents, the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus is the\n                  circadian pacemaker. The SCN contains various substances which may be\n                  involved in photic entrainment of the pacemaker. The bombesin like peptide,\n                  gastrin-releasing peptide (GRP) is one such substance. The present study was\n                  designed to determine if GRP would phase shift hamsters housed in continuous\n                  illumination. GRP was found to produce \"light pulse-like\" shifts when injected to\n                  the SCN. These results suggest that GRP may be involved in photic entrainment.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T11 at: 'Tl 2. Scott Bishop'"}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T20-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "MEMORY FUNCTIONS IN MULTIPLE CHEMICAL SENSITIVITY", "authors_raw": "Anne-Marie Brown", "abstract": "Case series of patients with Multiple Chemical Sensitivity (MCS) suggest difficulty\n                                         on several memory tests in addition to cacosmia. Bell (1992) suggested that this\n                                         pattern of symptoms might implicate focal dysfunction of the temporal lobes. To\n                                         test this hypothesis a case control study was initiated to compare the pattern of\n                                         memory loss in MCS, healthy controls matched for age, education and sex and\n                                     : \\ patients with temporal lobectomy on measures of estimated pre-morbid ability,\n                                       ••intelligence, attention, immediate and delayed memory for verbal and nonverbal\n                                         material. Twenty-six employees from a \"sick building\" were referred for extensive\n                                         neuro-psychological evaluations based on impairments documented in cognitive\n                                         screening. The majority had MCS. Group results for MCS patients, controls and\n                                         patients with temporal lobe lesions will be presented.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T20 at: 'T2 l. Anne-Marie Brown'"}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T16-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Tl?.   Stop Waving The Frogs' Legs, Just Pass Me The Toast", "authors_raw": "Steve Shaw and Jane Anne Home", "abstract": "Proximity to high voltage transmission lines and to some electrical equipment can\n              expose the body to low-frequency electromagnetic fields (EMFs). While EMFs are\n              reputedly able to interact with biological tissue, the effects are expected to range from\n              mild to non-existent at the field strengths normally encountered by most of us, although\n              there is some controversy about this. An exception to the supposed subtlety of action is\n              a sledgehammer effect reported five years ago by two British anaesthesiologists using a\n              well-known preparation, the frog's sciatic nerve. They claimed that a short exposure to\n              EMFs generated by a small coil surrounding the nerve is sufficient to disable it for\n              several minutes, after which transmission recovers fully. They attribute this result to\n              direct action by the applied EMF on some component of the nerve, which leads to what\n              they term \"electromagnetic inhibition\" (EMI). The mechanism of action has not been\n              investigated, but might be due to field-induced changes in the distribution of ions in or\n              around the axons, they say.\n                  Sensing a sizeable rodent here while on the look-out for more modern material to\n              incorporate into a teaching lab, we have attempted to retrace the footsteps of these\n              pioneers. We are able to reproduce what looks like their basic EMI phenomenon,\n              although it is not possible to duplicate the exact conditions they used originally because\n              too little detail is given in the published methods. Our preliminary measurements have\n              led us to reject their explanation of EMI and to propose a rival theory, unveiled in\n              public for the first time here: the Electromagnetic Toaster (EMT) hypothesis of nerve\n              inhibition.\n\nT18.    Conflicting Desire And The Child's Theory Of Mind\n\nChris Moore\n\nWe contrast the standard representational theory of mind approach to the understanding\n                     of mental states with an alternative view which has it that theory of mind tasks require\n                     executive functioning or the inhibition of more 'cognitively salient' information. In the\n                     first experiment 3-5-year-olds were tested on their understanding of desire in others\n                     either when they themselves held a strong and conflicting desire or when they had no\n                     strong desire. Results showed that under the condition of having a strong and\n                     conflicting desire, only 5-year-olds were able to recognize that", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16 at: \"Tl?. Stop Waving The Frogs' Legs, Just P\""}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T26-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "1-u     Michael Wm. MacGregor and Karina Davidson", "authors_raw": "O.C.E.A.N. - ology", "abstract": "The five-factor model is a taxonomy of ~rsonali~ traits in terms of five broad\n           dimensions: Openness to Experience, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness,\n           and Neuroticism. Although evidence suggests that these five factors are useful in\n           studying and modelling normal personality, there is less consensus regarding their\n           ability to model abnormal personality, particularly Eersonali!}'.disorders. This study\n           investigated the relationship between the five factor model ofpersonality and\n           personality disorders.\n              Two hundred and fifty undergraduate students completed the Personality Diagnostic\n           Questionnaire-Revised (PDQ-R)as a measure of personality disorders and the Big Five\n           Inventory (BFI-54) as a measure of the five factors of personalty. Results are\n           discussed with respect to the theoretical relationship between personality disorders and\n           the five factor model.\n1'28.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T26 at: 'O.C.E.A.N.'"}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T26-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Channel Surfing Without A Remote Control Tracy L. Taylor(l), Dennis P. Phillips(l,2), & Susan E. Hall(l). Departments of Psychology(l) and Otolaryngology(2) In an auditory gap detection task, three highly practiced listeners were presented with pairs of noise stimuli. Each stimulus consisted of leading and trailing noise bursts which bordered a temporal gap interval: In the test stimulus, this gap interval was varied systematically; in the reference stimulus this gap interval was maintained at a duration of 1 msec and was inaudible. The subject made a forced choice manual discrimination to indicate which of the two randomly presented stimuli contained the test gap. The dependent variable of interest was the shortest temporal gap that could be detected reliably. Subjects performed this task under conditions in which the perceptual channel used to define the leading and trailing edges of the gap was manipulated with respect to central frequency and laterality. In other words, perceptual channels were defined according to frequency and ear, such that the leading and trailing noise hurts shared no or complete spectral overlap and were presented to the same or to different ears. Results demonstrated poorer gap detection for across-channel (>20 msec) than for within-channel(< 5 msec) conditions, indicating that having to extract temporal information across frequency or ear limits the ability to resolve a temporal gap. It is noted that the thresholds observed in the across-channels conditions could be responsible for the +20 to +40 msec voice onset time (VOT) that typically marks the categorical boundary between voiced and voiceless stop consonants. ------------------------~~,·                                                   '11tl,, 1111 T29. Sex Differences: It's Not the Size, It's the Shape", "authors_raw": "Margo Watt & Jeannette McGlone As long ago as 1880, English surgeon James Crichton-Brown reported slight", "abstract": "differences in the brain anatomy of men and women - a few more neurons here in one sex, a few more there in the other. But by far one of the most frequent findings through the years has been that th~us                  the main fiber tract connecting the callOSE!Jl...: two cerebral hemispheres - tends 1o larger in women than in men. It has also been found to vary in shape between the sexes. Researchers, such as deLacoste-Utamsing and Holloway (1982), have speculated that if a larger corp", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T26 at: 'Channel Surfing Without A Remote Control'"}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "We injected 12 day old rats with the cannabinoid agonist CP55,940 (10, 100 or 1000\n       mg/kg) or with combinations of CP55,940 and the cannabinoid antagonist SR141716A (20\n       mg/kg), the opioid antagonist naloxone (1.0 mg/kg), the dopaminergic D1 antagonist\n       SCH23390 (0.5mg/kg) or the benzodiazepine antagonist flumazenil (20 mg/kg). CP55,940\n       dose-dependently reduced body temp., activity levels and the number of UV s emitted.\n       These effects were antagonised by SR141716A, but not by SCH23390, naloxone or\n       flumazenil These results suggest that CP55,940 has anxiolytic effects in rat pups through\n       an action that is specific to the cannabinoid receptor.", "authors_raw": "The Cannabinoid Agonist CPSS,940 Reduces Ultrasonic Vocalizations of\n       Infant Rats\n       Richard Brown, Farhard Dastur, Ashley McLennan and Iain McGregor", "abstract": "4                                                         1996 In-House Convention\n\nT3.   The Influence of the Male California Mouse (Peromyscus californicus) on\n      Pup Survival and Female Reproductive Success\n      Richard E. Brown and Debora Cantoni\n\nThe California mouse is a monogamous rodent in which the male shows a high level of\n      parental care. In our experiments, these mice were required to \"forage\" for food by\n      running in a wheel. Male-female pairs could rear larger litters of pups to weaning than\n      females alone and the pups with both parents grew faster. Single females who reared their\n      pups to weaning had a longer inter-birth-interval than paired females. Our presentation will\n      discuss the behaviour of the male which increases pup survival and facilitates implantation\n      in the female.\n\nT4.   Sexual and Maternal Behavior Correlates of Neuroanatomical Differences\n      Between Inbred Mouse Strains\n      Kara Firth, Paul Neumann and Richard Brown\n\nIn rodents, the preoptic area (POA) of the hypothalamus has been demonstrated to have\n      critical involvement in sexual and maternal physiology and behaviors. Structural\n      differences in the POA have been found between two inbred mouse strains, DBN2J (02)\n      and C57BU6J (B6) (Robinson et al, 1985). The B6 strain lacks a densely packed\n      neuronal cluster (termed 'medioventral pars compacta') that is found in the D2 strain in the\n      POA, on either side of the third ventricle; this compact nucleus may be homologous to The\n      sexually dimorphic nucleus (SON) in rats. Preliminary results (Mathieson and Neumann,\n      unpublished) suggest that this hypothalamic structural variant is an X-linked trait.\n          These strains also show differences on sexual behavior measures such as male sexual\n      performance (McGill and Manning, 1976) and maternal behavior measures such as\n      infanticide (Svare and Broida, 1982; Svare et al, 1984). It is therefore possible that the\n      structural variation between the two strains is responsible for the observed behavioral\n      differences. Specific", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T1 at: 'The Cannabinoid Agonist CPSS,940'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Gender differences in anxiety sensitivity dimensions", "authors_raw": "Stewart, S. H., Taylor, S., & Baker, J. M.", "abstract": "The present study examined whether there are gender differences in the hierarchical factor\n        structure of the Anxiety Sensitivity Index (ASI), and/or patterns of ASI factor scores.\n        Principal components analyses on the ASI items of male (N =290) and female (N =528)\n        students revealed nearly identical lower-order factor structures across genders (i.e.,\n        physical, psychological, and social concern factors). Nearly identical unidimensional\n        higher-order solutions were also found across genders. Analyses on ASI lower-order\n        factor scores showed that: females scored higher than males only on the physical concerns\n        factor; females scored higher on the physical concerns factor than on the psychological and\n        social concerns factors; and males scored higher on the psychological and social concerns\n        factors than on the physical concerns factor. Females also scored higher than males on the\n        higher-order ASI factor. The study provides support for the conceptual distinctions\n        between the three lower-order ASI factors, as well as the first empirical demonstration of a\n        hierarchical structure for the ASI. Men and women also appear to differ on AS dimensions\n        in ways consistent with sex role socialization practices.\n\n10                                                            1997 In-House Convention", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16 at: 'Tl 7. Gender differences in anxiety se'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Memory bias for food information           in restrained    eaters", "authors_raw": "Anne Israeli and Sherry Stewart", "abstract": "Research on cognitive patterns in individuals high in dietary restraint indicate an attention\n        bias toward food related information (see Francis, Stewart, and Hounsell, in press). The\n        cwrent study was conducted to see if restrained eaters show a memory bias for food words\n        in comparison to animal words (control list) in relation to individuals low in restraint\n        Thiny females (Mean age= 21.50, SD= 2.97) encoded a list of words (15 food, 15\n        animal) presented in an incidental learning task. Participants were then asked to freely\n        recall as many words as they could remember and fill out questionnaires including the\n        Restraint Scale (Herman & Polivy, 1980). Participants were classified as high in restraint\n        (n=16) and low in restraint (n=14) on the basis of the scale. Preliminary analyses indicate\n        that individuals high in restraint remember more food than animal words and individuals\n        low in restraint do not demonstrate such a bias. The results support (Bemis-Vitousek &\n        Hollon's (1990) theory that restrained eaters have highly organized cognitive structures\n        (schema) which permit then to avoid dangers (food) in their environment\n\nT19.    A translation of borderline and histronic personality disorders\n        Michael MacGregor, Karina Davidson and Stephanie Gustys\n\nThis paper addresses the translation of Borderline and Histrionic personality disorders into\n        the language of the Five-Factor model of personality. Based on theoretical expectations,\n        we investigated the empirical relationship between the Five-Factors of personality and these\n        two personality disorders in a non-clinical sample. As expected, the personality disorders\n        were characterized by high levels of Neuroticism. For Borderline personality disorder, our\n        expectations regarding Agreeableness were confirmed, however, those for Extraversion\n        were not As well, additional relationships were found between both Openness and\n        Conscientiousness and Borderline personality disorder. For Histrionic personality\n        disorder, our expectations for Extraversion were confirmed, however, those for Openness\n        were not Additionally, both Agreeableness and Conscientiousness demonstrated and\n        unexpected relationship with Histrionic personality disorder. While some of the expected\n        relationships between the Five-Factors and Borderline and Histrionic personality were\n        confirmed. others were not It appears that theoretical or clinical expectations are not\n        necessarily confirmed by empirical findings in a non-clinical sample. Results are discussed\n        in terms of the utility of the Five-Factor model in describing personality disorders.\n\nT20.    Becoming conscious of 'consciousness':               Notes for", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16 at: 'Tl 8. Memory bias for food'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T37-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "", "authors_raw": "18 Behaviors caregivers use to determine pain in non-verbal, cognitively impaired children Patrick J. McGrath, Christina Romos, Carol Camfield, Mary Ann Campbell, Allan Hennigar Primary caregivers of 20 children (age=14.5 years and language level=lO months) were recruited and interviewed to recall 2 instances of short sharp pain and 2 of longer-lasting pain and describe their child's behaviour. Transcribed interviews were reviewed and sets of non-overlapping items were developed. Thirty one behaviours were extracted from the interviews. The specific behaviors were often different from one child to another but the classes of behaviors (Vocal, Eating/Sleeping, Socia1/Personality, Facial Expression, Activity, Body & Limbs and Physiological) were common. Relibility of using the checklist on interviews was good (kappa=.77). The checklist has excellent content validity and will be useful for caregivers of cognitively-impaired, non-communicating children to report on pain behaviors.", "abstract": "", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_cleaned", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T37 at: '18 Behaviors caregivers use to'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T44-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Neural Statistics, Human Failing, and the Backward Propagation of Error '1'45:-", "authors_raw": "D.A. Santor", "abstract": "This brief talk introduces the basics of neural networks and machine learning and illustrates how for some (if not many tasks) we're better off not relying on human judgement. T46.      Recurrent network dynamics Thomas Trappenberg The brain does not process information in a strictly linear fashion. It has rather a large amount of recurrent pathways which we believe are the root of its rich dynamical behavior. In this talk we will discuss some properties of very simple recurrent abstract neural networks. We will demonstrate their behavior with some simulations. T47.      The evolution of the blood-brain barrier in the insect eye: is there a barrier in Archaeognatha? Steve Shaw and Lesley Varney In vertebrates, the blood-brain barrier (BBB) is located in the brain capillary walls and stabilizes the brain's micro-environment, protecting it from potentially harmful incursions of blood chemicals, etc. The evolution of the barrier mechanism is not easy to study by comparative methods, since all known vertebrates have it. The other larger group of terrestrial colonizers, winged insects (Pterygota), also have a BBB with the same role at the surface of the CNS, and which extends out into the eye. In trying to trace its evolution, we have looked to see if the eye barrier is present in the more primitive wingless insects (Apterygota), from which pterygotes originally evolved back in the Paleozoic era. We collected Petrobius   maritimus  (jumping bristletails) of the most primitive extant apterygote family Machilidae (Archaeognatha) on the shore near Parrsboro. Compared to other apterygotes, they have very well developed compound eyes. A colony of about 40 has been kept successfully for about 6 months in the lab. Using microelectrodes to pressure-inject small fluorescent tracers into the haemolymph (blood) of the head. we observed that these dyes lit up the eyes within a few minutes of injection. Specimens fixed and sectioned showed that dye is indeed present in the eye, concentrating particularly in the outermost optical layer, the cornea, which could only have reached by diffusing up from the base of the eye. We are currently setting up to check this, using electron-microscope tracers. Next, bugs were injected on a tilt stand (goniometer) mounted directly on the microscope, allowing fluorescence emission from part of the eye surface to be measured optically in real time with a sensit", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Neural Statistics, Human Failing, and th'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Animal behavior is something of a mobile projective test, no matter how objective we try\n         to be. What cues do we use, for example, to interpret the actions of other creatures? Part\n         of the answer depends upon our measurement systems: \"What you measure is what you\n         get!\" Of equal importance, measurements are inevitably incomplete and thereby can be\n         filled-in through often undefined expectations, biases, and the like. We have thus\n         launched a pilot project in which standardized behavior tapes and computer representations\n         of movement are presented to people under different settings. The results can be scary (as\n         in scare, not scar). It is clear that: a) cues can be used in an idosyncratic manner, b)\n         background events can change perceptions of behavior, and c) internal expectations of the\n         observer can dictate what is recorded, and how these recordings are interpreted. Certainly\n         the definition of objectivity must move beyond the position of shared bias. There may be a\n         rich field for cognitive psychologists as well as ethologists to explore here. Suggestions\n         are solicited.", "authors_raw": "Perceptions of movement\n         John Fentress", "abstract": "---------------------------------~----                                                                   - ----\n\n1997In-HouseConvention                                                                      7", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T9 at: 'Tl 0. Perceptions of movement'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Behavioral sequences in canids: a new perspective on the plasticity of action and movement patterns Simon Gadbois Important dimensions of behavioral patterns may have been overlooked in the past because of (1) the species chosen, (2) the action patterns investigated and (3) the methods of analysis selected. The issues of intentionality (control) and automaticity, plasticity and stereotypy, stochasticity and derterminism are reviewed in the light of new observations on caching sequences in canids. I will also discuss the pertinence of the concept of intensity patterns in behavioral sequences, which are often ignored to the profit of seguential patterns. An analogy with prosody in linguistics is suggested for the development of future models of temporal organization of behavior. Tl2.   Major urinary proteins of the strange male house mouse (Mus musculus) confer the specificity required to induce pregnancy block", "authors_raw": "Heather M. Schellinck 1 and E. Barry Keveme 2, 1Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University, 2Sub-Department of Animal", "abstract": "Behaviour, University of Cambridge The pregnancy of a female mouse (Mus musculus) is blocked by olfactory cues contained in the urine from a strange male but not in the urine from the stud male. We investigated the role of Major Urinary Proteins (MUPs) in determining these urinary cues by exposing pregnant female mice to one of the following: (A) urine from strange males; (B) chemically purified MUPs derived from strange male urine, with their ligands attached or (C) chemically purified MUPs derived from strange male urine, with their ligands removed via chemical extraction; (D) urine from stud males to which had been added chemically purified MUPs from strange males, with their ligands removed; (E) urine from stud males or (F) chemically purified MUPs from stud males with their ligands attached. (G) chemically prepared ligand, 2-(sec-butyl)thiazoline. Statistical analysis revealed that the exposure of pregnant females to (A) urine from strange males, (B) strange MUPs either with or (C) without the ligand attached or (D) combined with stud urine blocked significantly more pregnancies than exposure of female mice to (E) stud urine or (F) MUPs and ligand extracted from the urine of stud males or (G) chemically preapred ligand These results indicate not only that (1) the MUPs of male mice demonstrate pheromonal activity whearas the volatile ligands do not but also that (2) the MUPS of strange males confer the specificity required to induce pregnancy block in females. 8                                                          1997In-House Convention T13.   The Hebb-Williams Maze: Fifty years of research (1946-1996) Richard Brown & Lianne Stanford The Hehir Williams (H-W) maze was design", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T9 at: 'Tl 1. Behavioral sequences in canids:'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T29-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Effect of Male Removal on Gestation Length in Female California Mice (Peromyscus Calif ornicus)", "authors_raw": "A.W. Lee, D. Cantoni & R.E. Brown", "abstract": "California mice are a monogamous species that show biparental care. In mated pairs, the presence of the male facilitates reproductive success by increasing pup survival and reducing the female's gestation length. Under wheel running conditions for food, females living with their mate have a mean gestation length of 33 days. Females which have their mates removed 2 days postpartum, have a mean gestation length of 52.5 days, suggesting that these females had delayed implantation. The present study investigated the effect of male removal near the middle (Day 17) or end (Day 32) of the gestation period. Females living with their mate with ad lib food, have a mean gestation length of 34 days. Females which have their mates removed on Day 32 of gestation have a mean gestation length of 36 days. Females which have their mates removed in on Day 17 of gestation either have a mean gestation length of 36 days or fail to give birth. These results suggest that the presence of the male is important throughout the gestation period in maintaining a normal, gestation length in female California mice. Aspects of the male's behavior during parturition which may facilitate parturition will be discussed. 16                                                          1998 In-House Convention T31.   Copy Cat: Spatial Localization Deficits in Cats with Experimentally Induced Amblyopia are Identical to Those Experienced by Human Amblyopes Guy Gingras and Donald E. Mitchell, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University Although human amblyopia is defined as uncorrectable poor visual acuity, not all forms of acuity are affected equally. The worst deficits are observed on tasks that measure the ability to locate differences in the position of objects in space. This research had as its goal a comparison of the performance of normal cats and humans on the same localization task (a test of the ability to detect a misalignment between 3 Gaussian blobs) and to document the deficits on this task of cats with various forms of early visual deprivation (monocular deprivation or strabismus). Deprived cats demonstrated localization deficits that changed with spatial scale (blob size) in a manner identical to that observed in human amblyopes. Moreover, like human amblyopes, the spatial deficits on the alignment task were considerably larger than the deficits of grating acuity. The results justify the use of these animals models of human amblyopia. T32.   Instant identification of popular songs:          Insights into auditory memory representations E. Glenn Schellenberg 1, Paul Iverson 2 , Margaret C. McKinnon3 1Dalh", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T29 at: 'Effect of Male Removal on Gestation Leng'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T36-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Tim Bredy, Will Moger and Richard Brown", "authors_raw": "Behavioural Differences in MHC-Congenic Mice: The Step-Down Passive\n~       Avoidance Test", "abstract": "Although there are a multitude of physiological and pathological traits in which the major\n        histocompatibility complex (MHC) might influence behaviour (lvanyi, 1978, Proc. R. Soc.\n        Lond. B, 202, 117-158), MHC-congenic mice have primarily been tested for mate\n        selection and individual recognition by odour (Yamazaki et al., 1976, J. Exp. Med.,144,\n        1324-34; Manning et al., 1992, Nature, 360,581-583). The present experiment\n        investigated the possiblity that two strains of MHC congenic mice (C57Bl/6J vs. B6 H-2K)\n        would differ in their ability to learn and remember a passive avoidance task.\n        Glucocorticoids influence learning and memory (Smith, 1996, Beh. Brain Res., 78, 25-36)\n        and there are strain differences in hippocarnpal glucocorticoid binding capacity in mice\n        (Patacchioli et al., 1990, Beh. Brain Res., 37, 185-188). Plasma corticosterone\n        concentrations were therefore measured using radioirnrnunoassay following the passive\n        avoidance test. There was a significant strain difference in the ability of the no shock\n        control group to habituate to the step-down passive avoidance apparatus that can be\n        attributed to a strain difference in learning. The results indicated no strain differences in\n        retention. Corticosterone levels are presently being analyzed. Strain differences in passive\n        avoidance learning and in corticosterone levels may explain some of the MHC-related strain\n        differences in mate selection, intermale aggression and other behaviours.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T36 at: 'Behavioural Differences in MHC-Congenic '"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Symposium To Hebb and Beyond Donald Hebb was one of Canada's most famous and distinguished scientists, whose contributions were manifold and writings prolific. Hebb is widely recognized for his neo- connectionist assumption that correlated firing results in improved synaptic transmission (increase in connection weight) and his proposal of the cell assemblies. Hebb was a major advocate of psychology as a science and was a major force in directing its evolution in the 20th century. In order to examine Hebb and his work in a broader context, we will attempt to situate Hebb and his ideas within history, both in terms of the people who influenced him as well as in how his ideas shaped (or failed to shape) subsequent researchers. Some of the areas influenced by Hebb include LTP,kindling, neural networks, animal learning", "authors_raw": "and memory, mental imagery, stopped retinal image, pain, aging and the role of early", "abstract": "experience in cognitive and perceptual development. A life history of Hebb connecting significant life events to the various areas of interest integrates the diverse fields in which Hebb made a notable impact. For example, the publication of the Organization of Behavior ( 1949), which was influenced by the writings of William James and Santiago Ramon y Cajal, has exerted an ever-growing influence on those interested in mind, brain and how brains implement mind. 22                                                         1998 In-House Convention Posters", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Symposium To Hebb and Beyond'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "What does that robot want from me now? Young children's abilities to repair contingent queries.", "authors_raw": "Suzanne Ferrier", "abstract": "The ability of two-year-old's to respond differentially to specific and general contingent queries was examined with the use of an immobile robot as the conversation partner. Twenty-one 2;9-year-old and 21 2;3-year-old children were queried (5 specific and 5 general) immediately following 10 of their spontaneous utternaces in a free play session. The type of response strategy (repetition or specification) was coded for each queried utterance. Regardless of age, children tended to respond to a general query with an exact repetition of their original utterance. Age differences were found, however, in their replies to a specific query. The 2;9-year-olds most often replied with the specific information requested, whereas the 2;3-year-olds often repeated their original utterance, providing their partner with too much information. These findings suggest that it is not until 2;9 years of age that children efficiently satisfy their communicative partner's informational needs when conversational exchanges involve only linguistic cues.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'What does that robot want from me now?'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split3", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Temperature Selection and Use of Torpor by the Marsupial Sminthopsis Macroura", "authors_raw": "Xiaowei Song* and Fritz Geiser Department of Zoology, School of Biological Sciences, University of New England,", "abstract": "Australia *present address: Rusak Lab, Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University Many small mammals display daily torpor to minimize energy expenditure during the rest phase when faced with unfavorable environmental conditions. However, given a choice of thermal environments, it is not clear whether these daily heterotherms select ambient temperatures based on whether these minimize metabolic rates during torpor or during normothermia. It is also not clear whether they prefer being normothermic or torpid. In this study, we investigated temperature selection, activity patterns body temperature patterns, and the use of torpor in Sminthopsis macroura in a thermal gradient when food was freely available or restricted. Animals employed torpor regularly immediately after cessation of activity even when excess food was provided. Nevertheless, they selected high ambient temperature near the zone of thermoneutrality during both normothermia and torpor. Reduced food supply did not affect either temperature preference during torpor. Our study shows that S. macroura selected a high ambient temperature to reduce energy costs during normothermia. Nevertheless, daily torpor was frequently employed at the high temperature, especially when food was restricted. 1998 In-House Convention                                                                      23", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Temperature Selection and Use of Torpor'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split4", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Measurement of Pain in Non-verbal, Cognitively Impaired Individuals", "authors_raw": "Lynn Breau, Patrick J. McGrath, Carol Camfield, Christina Rosmus, G. Allen Finley", "abstract": "A preliminary investigation of the properties of the Non-communicating Children's Pain\n     Checklist was conducted. Caregivers of 38 individuals with Cerebral Palsy, Austism/PDD\n     or a neurological disorder completed the checklist at home: twice when that person was in\n     pain, once when they were in distress, and once when they were calm. Caregivers also\n     completed the Checklist concerning their participant's past pain behaviour in general.\n     Analyses were conducted to assess the Checklist's internal consistency, concurrent\n     validity, sensitivity, specificity, and reliability. The results indicate that, when used by\n     caregivers on actual events in a natural environment, the checklist can discriminate between\n     calm and pain, is reliable over time, correlates with a visual analogue measure of pain, and\n     is internally consistent. No differences were found between diagnostic groups, although\n     reported behaviour did vary as a function of the relationship of the caregiver to the\n     individual, and that individual's level of verbal comprehension.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Measurement of Pain in Non-verbal, Cogni'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split5", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Evidence Based Decision Making: Construct Validity of a Sodium Amobarbital Recognition Memory Protocol", "authors_raw": "McGlone, J., Black, S.E., Evans, J., Grantmyre, A., Moscovitch, M., Parkin, A., Sadler, M., Sita, A., Squires,E., Stuss, D., and Wilson, B.A.", "abstract": "Purpose: We tested whether the Intracarotid Arnobarbital Protocol had criterion and concurrent validity. It was hypothesized that a recognition memory test designed for intracarotid injections and used to predict the risk of global amnesia prior to an elective temporal lobectomy should identify persons who are severely amnesic due to other neurological causes. •Speech tasks would be unaffected by amnesia, but would identify aphasia. The impact of aphasia on memory outcome would be negligible. Methods: Fifteen persons with severe amnesia and one aphasic were administered a four- item yes/no recognition memory protocol and a speech protocol. No drug injection occurred. Standardized neuropsychological tests were used to divide the amnesic group into those with Global Amnesia (i.e., retain no ongoing memories), Dissociated Amnesia, and Amnesia plus other neuropsychological deficits (i.e., Non-Dissociated). Results: Two Global Amnesic persons obtained scores at or below chance (i.e., failed) on the memory protocol. Unexpectedly, the remaining 13 severely amnesic persons (Dissociated and Non-dissociated), obtained passing memory scores. Amnesia had no impact on the speech protocol. An aphasic individual passed the memory protocol and was impaired on the speech protocol. Conclusions: This IAP memory protocol showed good criterion validity in identifying Global Amnesia, but it was insensitive to other disabling, severe amnesic disorders. Discriminant validity was shown by amnesic persons perf orrning well on IAP speech tasks. These results suggest that this IAP protocol might have validity in predicting a post surgical Global Amnesic disorder, but it did not identify and therefore could not predict other severe amnesic disorders 24                                                        1998 In-House Convention", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Evidence Based Decision Making:'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split6", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Effects of Alcohol and Alcohol Expectancy on Responses to Hyperventilation in High Anxiety Sensitive Individuals", "authors_raw": "Alan MacDonald, Rochelle Hutson and Sherry Stewart", "abstract": "High anxiety sensitivity (AS) levels are significantly associated with increased beliefs about the tension-reduction properties of alcohol (Karp, 1993). The present study examined the effect that these alcohol expectancies might have on alcohol's reactivity dampening effects in high AS young adults (Baker, MacDonald, Stewart & Skinner, under review), in addition to alcohol's pharmacological anxiolytic effects. A three cell beverage condition design was used to assess the contributions of expectancy vs. expectancy plus pharmacology: told alcohol-given alcohol (A-A, pharmacology + expectancy); told alcohol- given placebo (A-P, expectancy only); and told placebo-given placebo (P-P, control). High AS student participants were randomly assigned to each condition. Following alcohol consumption and absorption, participants underwent a 3 minute voluntary hyperventilation challenge. Preliminary analyses indicate that A-A participants show greater reductions in affective, cognitive and somatic symptoms in response to challenge than A-P and P-P participants. However, A-P participants do not show reduced affective and cognitive symptoms to challenge compared to P-P participants. In fact, correlational analyses suggest a positive relationship between subjective intoxication measures and levels of affective reactivity within the the A-P group (a \"reverse expectancy\" effect), and a negative relationship between these measures in the A-A group. Implications of these results for prevention of alcohol abuse in high AS individuals are discussed.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'The Effects of Alcohol and Alcohol Expec'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split7", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Role of Sulfated Cholecystokinin Octapeptide (CCK-SS) in the Modulation of Separation-Induced Ultrasonic Vocalizations in 12 Day Old Rat Pups", "authors_raw": "Paul D. Mendella, Anna Maria Szczesniak, Richard E. Brown", "abstract": "Rat pups emit ultrasonic vocalizations (UV's) when separated from the dam and littermates. Anxiogenic drugs increase UV s, while anxiolytic drugs decerase UV s. The neuropeptide cholecystokinin (CCK) induces anxiety in health human volunteers and in individuals diagnosed with panic disorder. The purpose of the present investigation was to assess the effects of CCK-8S on UVs, locomotor activity, and body temperature in 12 day old rats pups, 15 or 30 minutes following drug treatment. Pups were injecteJ intraperitoneally with either vehicle or CCK-8S (0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0 µg/kg). After 15 minutes, male pups emitted more UVs and less turing behaviour than female pups. This is one of the few studies to find sex differences in rat pup UVs. After 30 minutes CCK-8S (4.0 mg/kg) significantly reduced line crossing frequency. In addition, male pups completed fewer head raises compared to female pups 30 minutes following drug treatment. Neither UV rate or body temperature was significantly altered by CCK-8S after 15 or 30 minutes. These findings suggest that CCK-8S is not directly involved in the modulation of anxiety-related behaviour in the separation-induced UV model of anxiety. 1998 In-House Convention                                                                25", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Role of Sulfated Cholecystokinin Octapep'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split8", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Saccharin must be added to the taste cue to condition robust taste preferences", "authors_raw": "Cathy Forestell and Vin LoLordo", "abstract": "A reverse-order differential conditioning procedure was employed to condition taste preference in rats. During training, one taste solution (CS+) was presented 3 min after a calorific reinforcer (glucose), and another taste solution (CS-) was presented 3 min after water. For half of the animals, both taste solutions always contained saccharin, whereas for the remaining animals, the tastes were mixed in water. Subsequently, two-bottle tests revealed a significant preference for the CS+ relative condition. These results suggest that without the presence of sacchrin in the CS solutions, conditioned preferences do not occur.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Saccharin must be added to the taste cue'"}
{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split9", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Simulating oculomotor behavior within a neural field model", "authors_raw": "S. D. Simpson, R. Klein, T. Trappenberg", "abstract": "Oculomotor programming can be viewed as the process of integrating exogenous\n     (environmental) and endogenous (intentional) signals into a unified motor goal. Just as\n     many experimental researchers recognize the importance of understanding both the bottom-\n     up and top-down influences on oculomotor programming, we believe it is important to\n     recognize that computational modeling of such systems should also be constrained by\n     multiple levels of analysis; specifically by behavioral and neurophysiological data obtained\n     from the area of interest. By extending and modifying a current neural field model of\n     oculomotor programming (Kopecz and Schoner, 1996) we have developed a computational\n     account of both behavioral and neurophysiological data from a variety of saccadic\n     paradigms including target location preparation (Munoz & Dorris, this meeting),\n     antisaccades (Everling et al, this meeting), and distractor manipulations. In the model,\n     environmental and endogenous signals are integrated within a buildup layer allowing for\n     competition among possible oculomotor programs. The activity of this buildup layer serves\n     as input to a burst layer whose activity represents a specific oculomotor command. This\n     poster will describe the model's architecture and demonstrate its ability to simulate saccadic\n     reaction time patterns and neuronal activity of buildup and burst neurons within the\n     Superior Colliculus. Possible enhancements to the model will also be discussed .", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'Simulating oculomotor behavior within a '"}
{"year": 1999, "entry_id": "T22-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "\\'   Dr. Peter Jusczyk", "authors_raw": "The Discovery of Spoken Language", "abstract": "To acquire a native language, a learner has to correctly identify the units (words, phrases, and clauses)\n       that are combined and manipulated in forming utterances in that language. A failure to identify the\n       appropriate units in the speech input would greatly complicate learning how sentences are structured in\n       the native language. There is considerable evidence that, during the second half of the first year, infants\n       rapidly converge on the specific properties that distinguish the sound organization of their native\n       language from other languages. Infants' developing sensitivity to native language sound structure not\n       only plays a role in helping to segment words from fluent speech, but has consequences for learning\n       about the language's grammatical organization. Thus from an early age, infants appear to use\n       information in the speech signal to group the input in a way that facilitates the discovery of the structure\n       of utterances. Findings from our laboratory show that infants detect cues to clausal and phrasal units in\n       utterances well before they actually begin producing and combining words. Furthermore, the groupings\n       that infants perceive in the input influence what information they encode and retain about speech. In\n       addition, there is evidence that infants are sensitive to the sequential order of elements in the information\n       that they retain. I will discuss some of these findings and their implications for understanding how\n       learners discover the organization of their native language.\n\nJusczyk, P. W. (1997). The discovery of spoken language. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.\n\n:.-\n                                                                                                  ,_ ....\n\n✓-- '._·-<.                     _J,;\\.ll....:~\n                                                      .••• ; ,..,(-~--)~ ......               / ,:__\n                                                                                                   .L ),\n\nT23.    An Investigation of Sentence Reading Using Event-related Functional Magnetic\n        Resonance Imaging (fMRI)\n   ,,\n   \\/ Ryan C.N. D'Arcy, John F. Connolly, Larry Gates, and Elisabet Service\n\nNeurophysiological studies of reading have successfully elucidated electrical and magnetic correlates of\n        cognitive processing, such as semantic analysis manifested by the N400. We used an established\n        paradigm from ERP/MEG research to study the neuranatomical regions of activation during sentence\n        reading. The participants read a series of sentences with terminal words that were either semantically\n        congruent or incongruent (e.g., The pizza was too hot to: eat/sing). In both condi", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T22 at: 'The Discovery of Spoken Language'"}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T14-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Effects of passive limb movement on the Visual Scanning abilities of Neglect subjects in Two\n        Coordinate Spaces", "authors_raw": "Beverly Butler.2, Gail Eskes 1.2,E. Harrison 1.2,& Alison MacDonald 2 , Dalhousie University 1 and Queen\n        Elizabeth II Health Sciences Centre2", "abstract": "Hemispatial neglect is a deficit in directing attention/movement toward the contralesional space.\n        Robertson (1995) reported that passive left limb movement did not improve visual scanning in a single\n        case of neglect, and suggested that active limb movement was required. Contrary to this finding, Ladavas\n        et al. (1997) and our own pilot study, showed that passive movement may improve visual scanning in\n        neglect patients in peripersonal space. The present study attempted to replicate and extend these passive\n        movement effects. Neglect subjects (n=6), right-hemisphere damaged non-neglect controls (n=6) and non-\n        brain-damaged controls (n=5) detected visual targets in peripersonal and extrapersonal space under\n        conditions of no movement and passive left limb movement (produced by functional electrical stimulation)\n        in left hemispace. We were unable to replicate the passive movement effects on visual scanning in this\n        group of neglect patients in peripersonal or extrapersonal space. However, the neglect group showed a\n        gradient of decreasing target detection from right to left, which was not evident in either of the control\n        groups (p<0.05).\n\nT16.    The Influences of Child Age and Parent Informant on the Associations Between Parenting\n        Practices and Child Behaviour Problems\n\nThis project investigated the influences of child age and parent informant (mother versus father report)\n        on the associations between parenting practices and conduct problem behaviour in a community sample\n        of children aged 5 to 12. Valid sample size for the computed regressions varied from 335 to 339.\n        Parenting practices were assessed using a modified version of the Alabama Parenting Questionnaire\n        (APQ; Frick, 1991). Conduct problems were defined by DSM-IV criteria for Oppositional Defiant\n        Disorder (ODD) and Conduct Disorder (CD), and assessed through the use of the Assessment of\n        Disruptive Symptoms, DSM-IV Version (ADS-IV; Pelham, Gnagy, Greenslade, & Milich, 1992). Both\n        mothers and fathers acted as informants for the two questionnaires. Preliminary analyses suggest that\n        the parenting practices of maternal involvement, poor monitoring and supervision of children's\n        activities, as well as inconsistent discipline, are significantly associated with number of CD and number\n        of ODD symptoms in children. The magnitud", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T14 at: 'Effects of passive limb movement on the '"}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T16-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Time Course of Linguistic Processing as indexed by Event-Related Brain Potentials (ERPs)", "authors_raw": "Randy Lynn Newman and John F. Connolly", "abstract": "While most theories of visual word recognition agree that access to meaning is meditated by phonology,\n        some theories contend that words can access their meaning directly, without phonological mediation.\n        ERPs, unlike behavioral measures of word recognition, provide an on-line measure of cognitive\n        processing without requiring overt behavioral responses. Indeed, a number of ERP components have\n        been found to be sensitive to orthographic, phonological, and semantic information. The goals of the\n        present study were to disentangle orthographic and semantic processing, and to define phonology's role\n        on route to accessing semantic information. ERPs were recorded to the terminal words of visually\n        presented sentences. Phonological/ orthographic and/or semantic characteristics of terminal words were\n        manipulated in 4 conditions in which: (1) the terminal word was the highest cloze probability ending\n        (e.g. Larry writes with his left hand.) (congruent); (2) the terminal word was orthographically\n        inappropriate, but was phonologically identical to the highest cloze probability ending (e.g. The game\n        was called off when it started to rayne. [rain]) (Pseudofoil); (3) the terminal word was orthographically\n        appropriate, but was semantically incongruent to the sentence context (e.g. The pizza was too hot to\n        sing.[eat]) (incongruent); or (4) the terminal word was orthographically inappropriate and was\n        phonologically distinct from the anticipated highest cloze probability ending (e.g. The teacher wrote the\n        problem on the heet. [board]) (incongruent-nonword). A negative peak was observed in the 250-300\n        msec range (the N270) in three conditions in which the orthography was unexpected. That is, even if the\n        orthography was corrent, as in the congruent condition, it was orthographically distinct from the highest\n        cloze probability ending for that sentence. A second, left tempro-parietally distributed negative peak in\n        the 350-450 range (the N400), was observed in both congruent conditions. Interestingly, the N400 was\n        absent in the WR condition, suggesting that phonology plays an important role in mediating access to\n        semantic information. Overall, these findings demonstrate the ability of ERPs to measure subtle aspects\n        of linguistic processing.\n\nT18.   Transcallosal While Matter Activation Revealed by Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging\n       During Reading\n\nRyan C.N. D'Arcy!, John F. Connollyl,2, Frank P. MacMaster2, Robert Vandorpe3, Larry Gates3,\n       Sultan Darvesh4, and Matthias Schrrtidt5 I. Cognitive/Clinical Neuroscience Unit, Department of\n       Psychology, Dalhousie University; 2. Department of Psychiatry, Dalhousie University; 3. Depa", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16 at: 'Time Course of Linguistic'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Will Brown and Chris Moore", "authors_raw": "Good genes, fluctuating asymmetry and human jealousy", "abstract": "Ancestrally extrapair copulations (EPC) likely exerted adaptive pressures on hominids. One adaptive\n           solution to reducing the probability of EPC is jealous emotions. Jealousy may be an adaptive strategy\n           designed to retain one's mate. If jealousy was an ancestral mate retention tactic, then individuals more\n           likely to be philandered upon should be more jealous. A predictor of likelihood to be philandered upon\n           may be developmental instability. Developmental stability (DS) is a heritable indicator of an organism's\n           ability to buffer environmental and genetic perturbances. DS is measured indirectly via fluctuating\n          asymmetry (FA). FA is the deviation from perfect bilateral symmetry in normally bilateral traits. The\n           less deviation from perfect symmetry is believed to be an intrinsically unfalsifiable indicator of 'good\n          genes.' As predicted, more asymmetric individuals (as measured by digital calipers with .0lmm\n          accuracy) were more jealous. FA accounted for substantial proportion of variance in self-reported\n          jealousy. Findings are consistent with jealousy being a condition-dependent mate retention tactic in\n          humans.\n\n-----       -     ---\n\n13\n\nTl 7.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15 at: 'Good genes, fluctuating asymmetry and hu'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Listening for chaos amid order, or order amid chaos", "authors_raw": "Susan Boehnke, Susan Hall, Torsten Marquardt, Dennis Phillips", "abstract": "The listening brain generates auditory images with a location by examining the correlation between the\n        sound waveforms that reach the two ears. If the sounds reaching the two ears are perfectly correlated\n        (+ORDER) we perceive a compact sound image with a distinct location. If the two ears receive\n        independent uncorrelated sounds (CHAOS), the perception is spatially diffuse and has no \"location\",\n        like the noise of wind rustling leaves in a forest. We can digitally generate another, unnatural, type of\n        perfectly correlated signal in which the signal phase at one ear is perfectly opposite to that of the signal\n        reaching the other ear (-ORDER). This is perceptually somewhat compact, but doesn't have an easily\n        specifiable \"location\". We have been examining the shortest detectable duration of each of these sounds\n        when they occur between markers of another type: What is the shortest duration of ORDER you can\n        detect in an ongoing stream of CHAOS, or of CHAOS in ORDER. It is much easier to detect the latter.\n\nTl 8.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15 at: 'Listening for chaos amid order, or order'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Dieting and body dissatisfaction: An epidemiological survey of health behaviours in Canadian\n        adolescents", "authors_raw": "Frank Elgar, Christine Clancy, Alan J.C. King", "abstract": "Identifying socio-demographic trends and psychological and behavioural correlates of dieting and body\n        dissatisfaction (BD) in adolescents helps to identify those at greater risk of developing eating disorders.\n        Analyses were performed on data collected from the Health Behaviours in School-Aged Children study\n        in which 11,272 Canadian adolescents from grades 6 through 10 participated. Both BD and dieting were\n        most prevalent among older and female adolescents, and BD increased the likelihood of dieting\n        threefold. Other factors that increased the likelihood of dieting were depressed mood and low self-\n        confidence. Adolescents who socialized more with peers, smoked more and consumed more alcohol\n        were more likely to be dieting, suggesting peer influences on eating behaviours are pervasive during\n        adolescence. Also, breakfast skipping was more closely related to BD and dieting than to family\n        income, suggesting school lunch programs targeted to adolescents from low-income families should\n        inform all adolescents about the risks associated with unnecessary dieting.\n\nT19.   \"Matt Stone looks just ravishing in his pink dress\" Irony in computer-mediated conversations.\n\nJeff Hancock and Philip Dunham\n\nThe text-based conversations that occur in email and internet chat environments eliminate many of the\n       non-verbal signals, such as facial expressions and tone of voice, that we rely on to interpret a speaker's\n       intent. The present study assessed the impact of computer-mediated communication (CMC) on the use\n       of ironic forms (e.g., irony, hyperbole, understatement, rhetorical questions) in conversations between\n       strangers. Given the reduction in the cues available in CMC to signal irony, we expected less use of\n       irony in this impoverished environment than in face-to-face conversations. Comparison of 40\n       conversations across these two communicative environments indicated that, contrary to initial\n       expectations, substantially more ironic language was produced in the CMC condition. This general\n       finding has several implications for current theoretical accounts of the comprehension and production of\n       verbal irony.\n\nT20.   Neurobiology of sleep deprivation effects on mood in major depressive disorder\n\nDenise Bernier\n\nThe goal of this pilot study is to assess the neurotransmitter changes in the brain that correlate with the\n       improvement of mood in depression. Sleep deprivation therapy has consistently shown an acute,\n       although transient, improvement of depressive symptoms in more than half of patients suffer", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15 at: 'Dieting and body dissatisfaction: An epi'"}
{"year": 2002, "entry_id": "P10-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "poster", "title": "Effect of Methylphenidate Hydrochloride (Ritalin) Administration on Locomtor Activity, Emotional Behaviour and Spatial Learning in C3H/HeSnJ Mice", "authors_raw": "Tera M.Mosher & Richard E. Brown", "abstract": "Attention Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a neuropsychological disorder prevalent in 3-5% of children. The three major characteristics of ADHD are hyperactivity, impulsivity and inattention. Currently, ADHD is treated through a variety of methods, including the use of psychostimulants. Ritalin is the treatment used by the majority of those diagnosed with ADHD because it decreases hyperactivity allowing subjects to concentrate more effectively. There are, however, few animal studies concerned with the effects of Ritalin on behaviour. In particular, it is important to ensure that drugs which alter hyperactivity do not impair cognitive function (e.g. Learning and Memory). The focus of the present study is to determine the effects of Ritalin vs. saline injections on locomotor activity, emotional behaviour and spatial learning in C3H/HeSnJ mice, which are not hyperactive. These mice were tested in the elevated plus maze, open field and Morris water maze. In the elevated plus maze the Ritalin-treated mice spent more time in the open arms than saline-treated mice. In the open field, mice treated with Ritalin were significantly more active than those treated with saline. In the Morris water maze there was no effect of Ritalin treatment on the latency to reach the platform. From these results we conclude that Ritalin increases locomotor activity, and decreases emotionality, but does not effect spatial learning and memory. Our next experiment will compare the effects of MPH on the hyperactive coloboma mouse with those of the control mice. We expect that MPH will reduce locomotor activity in these mice.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from P10 at: 'Effect of Methylphenidate Hydrochloride'"}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T16-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Confocal Microscopic Analysis of the Colocalization of Vesicular Glutamate Transporters in Cholinergic Neurons of the Rat Basal Forebrain: Do cholinergic neurons release glutamate?", "authors_raw": "Amanda Poulin and Kazue Semba", "abstract": "In addition to its well known role in cognition, the basal forebrain (BF) is implicated in the regulation of behavioural state. Neurochemically, these functions have been attributed primarily to the cholinergic, and to some extent, the GABAergic neurons in this brain region. Recent evidence also suggests the involvement of a glutamatergic system within the BF. Glutamate may act as a major transmitter in the BF, and may also be co-released from a subpopulation of cholinergic BF neurons. We examined the possibility of glutamate colocalization in BF cholinergic neurons by using antibodies to vesicular acetylcholine transporter and vesicular glutamate transporters (VGluT)-1/2/3, three recently identified transporters responsible for glutamate uptake into synaptic vesicles. Confocal microscopy was used to examine coimmunofluorescence for VAChT and VGluT 1/2/3 in the cell bodies of BF cholinergic neurons and their terminals in selected target areas. In the BF, scattered neurons in the horizontal limb of the diagonal band, ventral pallidum, substantia innominata, and globus pallidus were immunoreactive (ir) for both VAChT and VGluT3; however, no cell bodies in the BF were double-labeled for VGluTl/2 and VAChT. No fibers or terminals in the motor, somatosensory, piriform and entorhinal cortices were coimmunoreactive for VGluTl/2/3 and VAChT; similarly, VAChT-ir terminals within the BF were not VGluTl/2/3-ir. The reticular nucleus of the thalamus, which receives cholinergic projections from the BF, was also devoid of coimmunofluorescence for VAChT and VGluTl/2/3. In some of the above areas with cholinergic innervation, VGluTl/2/3-ir and VAChT-ir terminals were segregated in distinct patterns, whereas in others they were intermixed. These results suggest that VGluT3 is present in a small population of cholinergic BF neurons. The presence of VGluT3 in a subpopulation of BF cholinergic neurons suggests that terminals of some BF cholinergic neurons might release both acetylcholine and glutamate. Tl8)   Mothers' Views about Stress and Depression Marie-josee Lefaivre Despite the fact that depression is a prevalent mental health problem in women, very little is actually known about women's views and opinions regarding stress and maternal depression. A few qualitative studies suggest that women in rural communities tend to normalize their depressive experiences by seeing it as part of their lives as mothers and housewives. Other studies indicate that these women are more likely to present somatic symptoms associated with depression or distress. Previous research also suggests that individuals often characterize their depression", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16 at: 'Confocal Microscopic Analysis of the Col'"}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T19-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "How do different mouse strains differ on measures of locomotion,\n       exploration, anxiety, learning and memory?", "authors_raw": "Dirk Luchtman and Richard Brown", "abstract": "Transgenic mouse models of human diseases provide an animal model for understanding\nthe underlying mechanisms of these diseases. It is hoped that, eventually, these models\nwill translate into new treatments of human (neurological) diseases. Researchers are\nassembling test batteries in order to compare behavioral expressions of transgenic and\nmutant mice. The data that is produced in these experiments can be used to build up\nelectronic databases, like the Mouse Phenome Database of the Jackson Laboratory.\n    As part of the Phenome Project, we are investigating the behavioral differences in 5\nstrains of mice: SPRET/Ei, MOLF/Ei, C3H/HeJ, SJL/J and A/J. We are testing these\nmice for anxiety-like behaviors on the elevated plus maze, and light-dark box;\nlocomotion and exploration in the open field; motor learning on the rotarod; and spatial\nlearning in the Barnes maze and Morris water maze. We are also testing these mice for\nolfactory discrimination learning and visual acuity. Our poster compares the 5 strains of\nmice on these behaviors and examines the influence of body weight, anxiety, exploratory\nbehavior and visual acuity on performance in tests of learning en memory.\n\nPsychology Department In-House Conference May 2003                                   3\n\nThursday, Mayl, 2003\n              Room 4258, Life Sciences Centre\n\n9: 15         Introduction and brief history of convention (Vin LoLordo)\n\n9:30-10:30    Session 1.\n\nT 1) Jason Ivanoff\n                            T2) Troy Harker\n                            T3) Elizabeth Service\n                            T4) Kristie Dukewich\n\n10:30-10:45   Coffee Break\n\n10:45-12:00   Session 2.\n\nTS) John Barresi\n                            T6) Stephen Lewis\n                            T7) Sandra Reyno\n                            T8) Kimberly Good\n                            T9)\n\n12:00-2:00    Lunch Break and Posters (Psychology 2nd Floor Lounge)\n\nP 1) Lisa Currie\n                            P2) Beverly Butler\n                            P3) Slobodan Mirkovic\n                            P4) Crystal Lowe-Pearce\n                            PS) Lianne Stanford\n                            P9) Mohammad Inanlou\n\n2:00-3:30     Session 3.\n\nTlO) Eric Morris\n                            T 11) Amanda Wintink\n                            T12) Rebecca Douglas\n                            T 13) Kathleen Hourihan\n                            T14) Tracy Taylor\n                            T15) Megan Therrien\n\nFriday, May 2, 2003\nRoom 4258, Life Sciences Ce", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T19 at: 'How do different mouse strains'"}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T20-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Behavioral assessment of visual discrimination, pattern discrimination and\n            visual acuity in seven strains of mice", "authors_raw": "Aimee A. Wong and Richard E. Brown", "abstract": "Previous research has demonstrated that mice are capable of brightness discrimination and visual\npattern discrimination and that it is possible to quantitatively determine the visual acuity of the\nmouse. Based on the procedure of Glen Prusky (Prusky et al., 2000, Vision Research, 40, 2201-\n2209), we have developed a protocol using a computer-based, two-alternative swim task that\nevaluates visual discrimination, pattern discrimination and visual acuity in one apparatus. Seven\nstrains of mice (BALB/cByJ, C3H/HeSnJ, C57BL/6J, Coloboma, DBA/2J, FVB/NJ and\nMOLF/Ei) were tested on 8 trials/day for 8 days on each of the three tests. There was a\nsignificant strain difference in visual ability in all three tests. Mice with normal vision\n(C57BL/6J and DBA/2J) performed very well in these tasks. Mice with poor vision\n(BALB/cByJ) took longer to learn the tasks than mice with normal vision and mice with retinal\ndegeneration (C3H/HeSnJ, Coloboma, FVB/NJ, MOLF/Ei) performed only at chance levels.\nBecause measures of leaning and memory on visuo-spatial tasks may be affected by visual\nability, we correlated performance in the Morris Water Maze with the visual acuity of each\nstrain. We found that visual acuity was significantly correlated (r = -0.998) with the latency to\nfind the platform in the Morris Water Maze. This suggests that the visual ability of each strain is\na confounding variable in visuo-spatial learning and that visual acuity, rather than spatial\nmemory capability, may account for some of the strain differences in mice in the Morris Water\nMaze.\n\nT22)        Investigating Spatial Biases in Face Perception\n\nJamesie Coolican, BSc. and Gail Eskes, Ph.D\n\nWe were interested in the reported left-sided perceptual bias in interpreting facial emotion and in\nfacial recognition. Our purpose was to replicate the reported bias in normal subjects and to\nexamine whether this phenomenon was related to global/holistic face processing per se. Twenty-\none undergraduate students participated in the study. In Study 1, subjects were shown chimeric\nfaces created by combining half of a smiling face and half of a neutral face. They were asked to\njudge which of two faces (smile on left vs smile on right side of the face) was \"happier\". Results\nshowed a strong bias for judging the face with the left-sided smile as happier. In a second\ncondition, the chimeric faces were inverted. The left-sided bias in emotion judgement remained,\nsuggesting this judgement was not based on global face processing. In Study 2, composite faces\nfrom the left or right side of a neutral face were created and the subjects were asked to identify\nwhich composite most nearly matched the original face. In this case, a significant (but smaller)\nleft-sided bias for matching a composite was seen. In addition, top faces were s", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T20 at: 'Behavioral assessment of visual discrimi'"}
{"year": 2010, "entry_id": "T24-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Halifax is now home to Canada's most advanced magnetoencephalogrphy (MEG) brain imaging system. MEG is a noninvasive tool that offers the temporal resolution of EEG/ERP and spatial resolution than can rival fMRI. However, compared to those techniques it is faster to set up, less affected by head movements, more comfortable for the subject/patient, silent, and does not involve large magnets. This makes it an ideal tool for use with children and various patient populations. Through a partnership between the IWK Health Centre and the National Research Council Institute for Biodiagnostics, Elekta Neuromag OY has installed a 306 channel MEG imaging system and will be situated their North American R&D Headquarters at the IWK Health Centre. This presents a fantastic opportunity for researchers to do cutting-edge work with first-class support. However, as with any technique MEG is not exactly \"plug 'n play\" and requires some understanding to get up and running. In this talk I will briefly describe what MEG is and how it works, and then walk the audience through the process of designing a MEG study, moving a project through the approval process at IWK/NRC, implementing the study, and analyzing the data.", "authors_raw": "What is MEG and How Can I Use It? \n\t\tAaron Newman", "abstract": "Friday, April 30th\n\n8:30-10:00\tSession 5 Chair: Megan McLarnon\n\nT25)\tAnxiety Sensitivity and Negative Interpretation Biases: Implications for Anxiety Symptoms\n\tJanine Olthuis, Sherry Stewart, Margo Watt, & Brigitte Sabourin\n\nAnxiety sensitivity (AS) is an established cognitive risk factor for anxiety disorders. The present study explored whether individuals high in AS display a similar negative interpretation bias as that identified in those with anxiety disorders. Furthermore, we investigated whether the association between AS and both panic and generalized anxiety symptoms could be accounted for by negative interpretation biases of ambiguous panic-related body sensations, general events, social events, and/or other body symptoms. Eighty-nine female undergraduates (44 low AS; 45 high AS) completed self-report measures of AS, negative interpretation bias, and panic and generalized anxiety symptoms. Findings showed that women high in AS had significantly greater negative interpretation biases. In addition, negative interpretations of ambiguous panic-related body sensations partially mediated the association between AS and panic symptoms while negative interpretations of ambiguous general and social events partially mediated the association between AS and generalized anxiety symptoms. Clinical implications are discussed.\n\nT26)\tThe Effects of Maternal Care on Offspring Fitness in the Zebra Finch (Taeniopygia guttata)\n\tHeather Phelan & Leslie Phillmore\n\nVariations in maternal care can cause adverse effects later in life for humans and rats (Liu et al. 1997). This study examined the role of maternal care on offspring fitness in the zebra finch (Taeniopygia guttata), a species that provides biparental care to", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T24 at: 'What is MEG and How Can I Use It?'"}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The world of publishing, both within academia and more broadly, has been revolutionized by digital technology. With the technology necessary to distribute one's work available to virutally everyone, it is clear that the old paradigms cannot be maintained. At the same time, scientific publishing has a long and proud tradition of curation through rigourous peer review. While few would argue that peer review is a bad thing, we are also aware that peer review has a dark side: irrational reviewers (positive or negative, though we focus more on the latter); coldly rational reviewers who deliberately sabatoge manuscripts to prevent being scoped; editors who lack the expertise to evaluate arguments properly; and the fact that journals deliberately restrict themselves to the publication of the \"best\" papers in order to improve their reputations, rather than because all rejected papers are \"bad\" science. As well, in moves reminiscent of the music industry over the last 15 years, we have witnessed academic publishers take coprporate and legislative steps to protect their profit margins at the expense of academic freedom, for instance by requiring libaries to purchase \"bundles\" of journals at great expense, including journals that the libraries do not want, as well as publishers' support of recent legislative moves in Canada and the US to radically strengthen copyright protection at the expense of academic freedom. Against this draconian landscape, however, academics are faced with the reality that our careers, including hiring, promotion, and funding decisions, hinge not only on how much we publish, but where. In this debate, one side will argue in favour of open publishing and highlight current best practices, while the other side will argue in favour of a relatively unchanged status quo. Arguments and rebuttals will be followed by an open discussion with the audience.", "authors_raw": "DEBATE: Open vs traditional peer-reviewed publishing in science\nAaron Newman, Jon Fawcett, Mike Lawrence, Heath Matheson, and more", "abstract": "T46)\tSeeing the forest on the left and the trees on the right\n\tJohn Christie\n\nUsing a novel method that could be applied quite broadly to both normal and neurologically damaged subjects we assess right and left biases in global stimuli across hemifields.  In the same experiment, without changes in instruction, we also assess local laterality effects across hemifields and across objects within a hemifield.  Findings are as expected in normal participants but with larger effect sizes than previously found in similar studies.  A lone neurological patient is presented who shows a unique laterality difference from the healthy controls for local items.\n\nT47)\tPicking a flavor: Do perceptual processing strategies drown out motoric IOR effects?\n\tGreg MacLean, Matt Hilchey, & Ray Klein\n\nAt short cue-target onset asynchronies, irrelevant cues can “capture” attention, resulting in a response benefit when they cue the location of a upcoming target, and incurring a respo", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44 at: 'DEBATE: Open vs traditional peer-reviewe'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "and neuroscience have traditionally been dominated by the \"null hypothesis significance testing\" (NHST) philosophy of statistics, recent advances in computing have permitted alternative approaches, most notably Bayesian methods. This talk will briefly distinguish the philosophical backgound of NHST and Bayesian methods followed by a walk-through of a simple Bayesian analysis. The talk will conclude with discussion of the power of Bayesian methods to address more advanced analyses.", "authors_raw": "Final Symposium\nPsychology and Neuroscience: Why our name without \"and neuroscience\" would not smell as sweet", "abstract": "Descartes made a sharp distinction between conscious processes of the mind or rational soul and mechanical material processes of the body. This distinction was effective and had long-term consequences that included separating the disciplines of psychology and neurobiology.  Why this happened and why we are now able to reintegrate psychology and neuroscience is the subject of this symposium.\n\nWhy psychology and neuroscience separated as sciences\nJohn Barresi\n\nFor Aristotle psychology was an integral part of the biology of animate beings. But, with the rise of Christianity and its emphasis on Plato’s earlier idea of the immortality of the rational human soul, Western thinkers were ready for Descartes’ revolutionary theory, which distinguished sharply between the conscious rational soul of humans and body-machines. While subsequent thinkers rejected Descartes’ idea that all other animals were mere automata, without conscious minds, the majority of 18th and 19th century scientists continued to distinguish conscious processes of minds and purely material processes of animate bodies, including the brain. A consequence of this historical development has been that psychology and neurobiology have been separate disciplines until quite recently.\n\nHow Donald Hebb brought psychology and neuroscience back together\nRichard Brown\n\nIn the 1940's, there were many \"Schools\" of psychology, such as Gestalt Psychology, Structuralism, Functionalism, Behaviourism, etc., each of which looked at behaviour in a different way. There were also a plethora of \"physiological\" theories of behaviour proposed by Pavlov, Lashley, Morgan, and others.  Each theory focused on a different aspect of behaviour: learning, memory, development, motivation, emotion and clinical problems.  What Hebb did, with two simple concepts, the modifiable synapse and the cell assembly, was to provide a neural mechanism which could account for all of the different categories of behaviour that psychologists were struggling to explain with their separate theories. The result was to change Psychological theory and reintroduce the idea that a neural mechanism was the basis for all behaviour, normal and abnormal and that one of the aims of Psychology was to understand that physiological mechanism. Hebb's aim was to show that the psychological study of the \"mind\" required a biological approach.\n\nA neo-Hebbian blueprint", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50 at: 'and neuroscience'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "For Aristotle psychology was an integral part of the biology of animate beings. But, with the rise of Christianity and its emphasis on Plato’s earlier idea of the immortality of the rational human soul, Western thinkers were ready for Descartes’ revolutionary theory, which distinguished sharply between the conscious rational soul of humans and body-machines. While subsequent thinkers rejected Descartes’ idea that all other animals were mere automata, without conscious minds, the majority of 18th and 19th century scientists continued to distinguish conscious processes of minds and purely material processes of animate bodies, including the brain. A consequence of this historical development has been that psychology and neurobiology have been separate disciplines until quite recently.", "authors_raw": "Why psychology and neuroscience separated as sciences\nJohn Barresi", "abstract": "", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50 at: 'Why psychology and neuroscience separate'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split3", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "In the 1940's, there were many \"Schools\" of psychology, such as Gestalt Psychology, Structuralism, Functionalism, Behaviourism, etc., each of which looked at behaviour in a different way. There were also a plethora of \"physiological\" theories of behaviour proposed by Pavlov, Lashley, Morgan, and others.  Each theory focused on a different aspect of behaviour: learning, memory, development, motivation, emotion and clinical problems.  What Hebb did, with two simple concepts, the modifiable synapse and the cell assembly, was to provide a neural mechanism which could account for all of the different categories of behaviour that psychologists were struggling to explain with their separate theories. The result was to change Psychological theory and reintroduce the idea that a neural mechanism was the basis for all behaviour, normal and abnormal and that one of the aims of Psychology was to understand that physiological mechanism. Hebb's aim was to show that the psychological study of the \"mind\" required a biological approach.", "authors_raw": "How Donald Hebb brought psychology and neuroscience back together\nRichard Brown", "abstract": "", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50 at: 'How Donald Hebb brought psychology and n'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split4", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "A neo-Hebbian blueprint for the integration of neuro-psychological science and the mission of our Department", "authors_raw": "Raymond M. Klein", "abstract": "With Hebb's ideas providing a backdrop, the recent history of our discipline will be related to a (somewhat) personalized history of the department. Divisions based on workplace (laboratory versus clinic), type of work (studies of brain versus behavior; animals versus humans), sub-discipline (development, perception, personality, learning, etc.) and favorite causal mechanism (nature vs nurture) characterize these histories. Importantly, conceptual, methodological and technological innovations have made it possible for us to implement Hebb's neuropsychological vision of the discipline through an integrated effort to understand how nature and nurture shape the neural networks that underlie the organization of our overt and covert behaviors.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50 at: 'A neo-Hebbian blueprint for the integrat'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split5", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Our increasing ability to see into the mind has helped scientists adapt theory to match the computations that are actually performed within the brain. For example, rational choice theory would posit that when faced with a decision, one should always choose the response option with the highest utility, or value. However, that is not always the case. When humans play the “ultimatum game” frequently people make irrational decisions – they reject proffered money in the name of “fairness”. Functional imaging has given us insight into why this occurs, and has forced a reconciliation of rational choice theory with psychological theory. As we head into the future, technological advances in human neuroimaging will only allow us to see further into the processes of the mind and explain other phenomenon. For instance, recent advances in neuroimaging have taken us into the realm of mind reading – a technology that knows what we are thinking as we are thinking it. Not only does research like this give us better insight into why we do and say the things we do, but it also puts us right in front of Pandora’s Box – forcing to us to an understanding that we might not want to have.", "authors_raw": "The future of psychology and neuroscience \nOlav Krigolson", "abstract": "POSTERS\n\nThursday’s Posters\n\nP1) \tIs Perfectionism a Vulnerability Factor for Depression After Controlling for Neuroticism?\nTara M. Gralnick and Simon Sherry\n\nExtensive evidence suggests neuroticism (i.e., a dispositional tendency to experience negative emotional states) is a higher order personality trait that shares substantial variance with perfectionism dimensions and depressive symptoms (Graham et al., 2010; Sherry et al., 2012). Such evidence raises an important question: are perfectionism dimensions vulnerability factors for depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism? The present meta-analysis examined the existing evidence testing if perfectionism dimensions (i.e., self-oriented perfectionism, socially prescribed perfectionism, concern over mistakes, doubts about actions, and perfectionistic attitudes) predict changes in depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism. A comprehensive meta-analysis of 10 longitudinal studies involving 1858 participants from undergraduate, community, and psychiatric samples indicated all five perfectionism dimensions significantly predicted changes in depressive symptoms after neuroticism was taken into account. Perfectionism dimensions consistently predicted changes in depressive symptoms across a wide range of samples, methods, and measures. Observed effect sizes were small to moderate in magnitude. Results lend credence to and bring coherence to theoretical accounts, case histories, and empirical studies suggesting perfectionism dimensions are part of the premorbid personality of people vulnerable to depressive symptoms. Results also suggest perfectionism dimensions are unique lower order personality traits that add incrementally to understanding of depressive sy", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50 at: 'The future of psychology and neuroscienc'"}
{"year": 2024, "entry_id": "P44-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "poster", "title": "Sst-Cre; Ai40D transgenic mice performing a psychophysical size discrimination task do not show sex- or cohort-related differences in task accuracy.", "authors_raw": "Singh, P.K., Michaud, N.M., ten Haaf, M.R., Nadeau, E., Atwell, I., Dang, L.T., Adesalu, K., Crowder, N.A.", "abstract": "Mice serve as an important animal model in neuroscience because of their compatibility with various genetic techniques. Our research program investigates links between neural circuits in primary visual cortex (V1) and perception in transgenic mice using optogenetic tools, which modify the activity of specific neuron subtypes using light. We are evaluating size perception in mice using a two-alternative-forced-choice size discrimination task where mice turn a steering wheel to bring the larger of the two stimuli towards to centerline for a reward. During certain trails, we illuminated V1 bilaterally with yellow light to suppress Archaerhodopsin expressing somatostatin-positive interneurons. Our present analysis of the psychophysical data focused on possible sex and cohort differences, accounting for other factors beyond optogenetic manipulation that could affect task performance.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from P44 at: 'Singh, Prem'"}

