{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9-split2", "patch": {"title": "Behavioral sequences in canids: a new perspective on the plasticity of action and movement patterns", "abstract": "The pregnancy of a female mouse (Mus musculus) is blocked by olfactory cues contained in the urine from a strange male but not in the urine from the stud male. We investigated the role of Major Urinary Proteins (MUPs) in determining these urinary cues by exposing pregnant female mice to one of the following: (A) urine from strange males; (B) chemically purified MUPs derived from strange male urine, with their ligands attached or (C) chemically purified MUPs derived from strange male urine, with their ligands removed via chemical extraction; (D) urine from stud males to which had been added chemically purified MUPs from strange males, with their ligands removed; (E) urine from stud males or (F) chemically purified MUPs from stud males with their ligands attached. (G) chemically prepared ligand, 2-(sec-butyl)thiazoline. Statistical analysis revealed that the exposure of pregnant females to (A) urine from strange males, (B) strange MUPs either with or (C) without the ligand attached or (D) combined with stud urine blocked significantly more pregnancies than exposure of female mice to (E) stud urine or (F) MUPs and ligand extracted from the urine of stud males or (G) chemically preapred ligand These results indicate not only that (1) the MUPs of male mice demonstrate pheromonal activity whearas the volatile ligands do not but also that (2) the MUPS of strange males confer the specificity required to induce pregnancy block in females. 8 1997In-House Convention T13. The Hebb-Williams Maze: Fifty years of research (1946-1996) Richard Brown & Lianne Stanford The Hehir Williams (H-W) maze was design"}}
