{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Bloom·_ Neonatal Assessment as a Model for Medical/Social Change.", "authors_raw": "K", "abstract": "Neonatal assessment is a structured        procedure in which\n      defined behaviors are observed and elicited.           This process yields\n      not only an objective description       of the newborn's medical and\n      behavioral   status, but also a generalized       affect upon the quality\n      of the observer's    subjective    judgments.    In the former and traditional\n      way, the assessment procedure is used as a dependent variable.             In\n      the latter way, assessment is viewed as an independent variable or\n      treatment of the adult (e.g., pediatrician,          parent, child-care\n      specialist).     The value of structured      behavioral assessment for\n      teaching, primary medical care and research will be illustrated            with\n      examples from pediatrics,       developmental and clinical    psychology.\n\n9.\n\n28.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25-split1 at: 'K. Bloom'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Power of Learning Theories.", "authors_raw": "T. Whalen", "abstract": "The nature of a theory of learning may be determined using\n      theoretical   machines called finite automata.   There is some finite\n      automaton which will behave in the same way as any organism.        As an\n      organism learns, however, it changes its behaviour.      Therefore, there\n      will be a way to change a finite automaton so that it also behaves in\n      this new way: A description     of these changes will be equivalent to a\n      theory of learning.    If it can be shown that a particular    process is\n      required to alter a finite automaton so that it learns appropriate\n      behaviour, a theory of learning must also incorporate     this process.\n      For example, if it can be shown that something more than stimulus-\n      response associations   are required for a \"naive\" finite automaton\n      to learn some behaviour, then S-R theories will not be sufficient       to\n      account for this learning.\n\n29.   J. Barresi   &D. Dalzell     - The Abstraction   of Spatio-T~mporal    ~}~5!~re.\n\nA chain of 80 dot patterns was constructed by recursively\n      applying a distortion      rule to the pattern constructed         from the pre-\n      vious application     of the rule.   When these patterns        are presented\n      visually    for 300 msec each in their \"natural\"        order, they appear as\n      a continuously changing shape.        Surprisingly,     subjects'     ability to\n      identify patterns     from the sequence is no better when the patterns\n      are presented in their \"natural\"       order than when the sequence of 80\n      is presented randomly.       However, both of these conditions yield much\n      better performance than does a sequence of 80 entirely              random\n      patterns.     These and other results suggest that resemblance rather\n      than continguity    is the first associative       principle.\n\n30.   J. Willner   - Constraints    on Learning:   A Re-evaluation.\n\nAlthough rats preferentially       condition to gustatory cues when\n      illness  is the reinforcer,     the argument that this reflects     a specific\n      learning ability    selected for by evolution is not especially       compell-\n      ing. Data from experiments on blocking and second-order conditioning\n      which employed nongustatory       CS's will be described which suggest\n      that the constraint     is on the expression of learning,     rather than on\n      the learning i tse If.     The relevance of these findings to general\n      theories of learning will be discussed.\n\n31.   J. Raymond - Visual Sensitization       with a Large, Flashed Annulus.\n\nThe addition of light to the visual system usually acts to\n      desensitize     detection mechanisms.    In this experiment, specific\n      stimulus conditions are defined that make an exception to this general\n      rule.    The results show that the addit", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25-split1 at: 'T. Whalen'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "6-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Remembering Processes in the Pigeon.", "authors_raw": "T. Whalen", "abstract": "Depending on the requirements of the situation,                           it is\n                                            believed that an organism, such as a pigeon, can either remember a\n                                            stimulus or a future behaviour required by the present stimulus.                                      Honig\n                                            has shown that in situations                in which a pigeon is only required to\n                                            remember whether to peck or not, remembering occurs over longer inter-\n                                            vals than are normally found with procedures which require the recall\n                                            of a stimulus.    The present research uses a procedure which also requires\n                                            only that the pigeon remember whether to respond or not,                               It is simpler\n                                            than those that have been used previously.                        Since this seems to produce\n                                             as much recall in pigeons as Honig's procedure, this hypothesis is\n                                            supported.            ·.         .                             ·..       . _,,--.~ _,,-. _..,,,.--\n                                                                                                                                            _,,..,,...\n                                                                                                                                                  __,,,----\n           ,,.1,J~,,...__/--~,_,,,,_,,,...._~.               ~ ____,,,\n                                                                   ,./,._,,. _ ~- •. - ---•./. /. ~ /   ./ • ./ - _/\n\nVO\"r2_<._                 9.     B. Tansley & M. Regan - Estimation of the Sensitivity                                      of FM Channels\n               ~ ..1                                        in the Human Auditory S~tem.\n           \\)~--;:~cJ\n\n~+~~t\n                                                Because of the high sensitivity  of auditory mechanisms to\n                                    amplitude changes associated with frequency variations        of an acoustic\n                                    stimulus, the estimation of frequency-modulation      sensitivity   via a\n    ~},~                            threshold method is often contaminated with input from channels selec-\n ~\\'·                   /           tively sensitive     to changing amplitude.  We propose a method whereby it\n~ v .-\\,1                           appears possible to estimate the sensitivity     of FM channels by\n_•;.,---trr                         \"titrating    off'' the", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 6-split1 at: 'T. Whalen'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Induced Anisocoria.", "authors_raw": "J. Gardner", "abstract": "Kittens raised with a dimming filter     over one eye show long-\n                                    lasting changes in the pupilary light reflex.        The deprived eye\n                                    becomes more sensitive    to light, and when the filter      is removed, that\n                                    pupil is consistently    smaller.    The anisocoria   lasts for weeks. We\n                                    suspect that this plasticity      is due to a cerebellar    mechanism and are\n                                    now testing normal and lesioned adult cats. - -----------------------------------\n\n4.\n12.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split2 at: 'J. Gardner'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Resolution of Ambiguity irt the PerceFtion of\n                                     Motion in Depth.", "authors_raw": "D. Regan &K. Beverley", "abstract": "Increasing or decreasing retinal      image size is an ambiguous\n       visual cue because it can mean either that an object's          size is chang-\n        ing or that the object is moving in depth.         How does the visual system\n       resolve this ambiguity so as to provide an unequivocal basis for\n        action?    We will present evidence that there are separate information-\n       processing channels for changing size and for motion in depth, and\n      ·that the visual system contains a biassing mechanism that is capable\n       of suppressing the activity       of one or other channel.    One trigger\n       that activates      this biassing mechanism is the relationship     between\n       the speeds of the horizontal       and vertical   edges:  if the object's\n       shape is constant,       then the changing-size   channel is rendered less\n       effective.\n\n13.   G. Tower &J. Barresi        - The Effects of a Third Choice on Cooperation\n                                   • in a Mixed-Motive Game.\n\nThe generally low amount of cooperative       (30%) as opposed to\n      competitive   (70%) responding in the two-choice, prisoner's         dilemma\n      game may be due to the meanings attached to the restricted           choices\n      provided by the game. In the present study a third choice was added\n      whose mere presence changed the \"meaning\" of the cooperative and\n      competitive choices.      Three \"meanings\" of the cooperative choice·were\n      compared - sharing, self-interest,       and altruism.    The sharing condi-\n      tion produced the most cooperative responding (sharing=           56%, self-\n      interest   = 33%, altruism=     36%). The self-interest     condition pro-\n      duced the most competitive responding (sharing=          25%, self-interest\n      = 43%, altruism=      35%). Finally,   the altruism condition produced\n      the most third (contract)      choice responding (sharing=     19%, self-\n      interest   = 24%, altruism=     29%).\n\n14.   R. Baxter   &J.   Barresi    - The Effects of Three Preprograrnm!d Strategies\n                                     on Cooperative responding in a Three-Choice\n                                     Mixed-Motive Game.\n\nCooperative responding in the prisoner's        dilennna game has\n      been increased from a free play 30% to 80% when a preprogrammed tit-\n      for-tat    strategy is used by the \"partner\".        This strategy involves\n      responding on each trial with the real subject's          previous response.\n      Thus, the subject is rewarded for a cooperative response (i.e.,            with\n      cooperation)      and punished for a competitive response (i.e.,      with\n      competition).       The effectiveness    of this and two other preprogrammed\n      strategies     w", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split2 at: 'D. Regan &K. Beverley'"}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "11-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Hemispheric Asymmetry in Part-Whole Judgements.", "authors_raw": "B. L. Smith", "abstract": "The work presented here is an attempt to obtain a test sensitive       to\n      right hemisphere processes.   Experiments with stick figures,     extracted   from the\n      16 segments obtained from a 3 x 3 matrix, appear promising.       A three-segment\n      part, either contained within a foveally-presented   six-segment figure or not,\n      was briefly exposed in the left or right visual field.      Decisions (part\n\n4.\n\nincluded in the figure or not) were made quicker for \"easy\" parts (e.g.\n     triangles)   in the right visual field,    and for \"difficult\"  parts (unconnected\n     and scattered)   in the left.    These data suggest?- method for evaluating\n     perceptual   and memory representations    in the two hemispheres.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 11-split1 at: 'B. L. Smith'"}
