{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "11-split1-split3", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Abnormal Grating Adaptation in Multiple Sclerosis.", "authors_raw": "D. J. Raymond", "abstract": "Reduced contrast    sensitivity      is often found in individuals        with\n     multiple sclerosis     (MS). I investigated         this abnormality of contrast       vision\n     by measuring changes in contrast        sensitivity      after adaptation    to a high\n     contrast  sine wave grating pattern in MS patients             and normal control subjects.\n     I found that after viewing a 70 90 contrast          adapting pattern     for 1 minute, 15 out\n     of 17 MS patients    showed contrast     sensitivity      changes, or adaptation     effects,\n     smaller than 2. 0 standard deviations        below the mean adaptation        effect for the\n     normal group with at least one eye.          In normals, the size of the adaptation\n     effect increases    both as the contrast       of the adapting pattern is increased           and\n     as the duration of exposure to the adapting pattern is increased.                  Although\n     these relationships     also hold for the MS patients          studied,   the shapes of both\n     the contrast    and duration functions are different           for the MS group.\n\nWhen the contrast     of the adapting pattern is low but still         visible\n     to the subject     (less than 1.0 l.u. greater than the unadapted log contrast\n     threshold),   an adaptation    effect can always be observed in normal subjects.\n     However, in some MS patients       adapting patterns      of m1,lchhigher contrasts\n     (up to 1. 0 1. u greater than the log unadapted contrast            threshold)  are\n     insufficient    to induce adaptation     effects.     Similarly,    20 to 60 seconds of\n     exposure to a 70% contn:.st adapting pattern are enough to produce near-maximum\n     adaptation   effects    in normal subjects.     MS patients    require exposures of 180\n     to 300 seconds before adaptation        effects   similar in size to those found in\n     normals can be observed.\n\nThese differences  between MS patients   and normal subjects   cannot\n     be explained by reduced contrast     sensitivity  and indicate   that the neural,\n     probably cortical,    mechanisms mediating visual contrast     adaptation may be\n     considerably   altered by MS.\n\nE.   I.   Meinertzhagen   and A. Frtlhlich.     Synaptogenesis    in the Fly's       Visual   System.\n\nThe ultrastructure      and composition of fly photoreceptor       synapse\n     populations   has been examined by serial       electron microscopy of developing\n     animals.    Adult synapses are tetrads with four postsynaptic          elements.    At\n     younger stages dyad and triad synapses (with nrn and three postsynaptic\n     elements, respectively)       coexist alongside tetrads,      those of older animals\n     having an average more postsynaptic        processes per synapse.      It is sug", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 11-split1 at: 'D. J. Raymond'"}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "8-split4-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Aspects of Dominance Behavior in Groups of Sibling Coyotes.", "authors_raw": "J. Ryon", "abstract": "Two unrelated    groups of sexually mature sibling coyotes with three\n                     males and two fema]es each were observed when each group was a) housed\n                     together,    b) divided by sex into four groups and c) reunited after three\n                     months.    T\\vo dominance hierarchies        (male and female) in each group were\n                     determi1:ed by social display.         TI1e effect of opposite-sex      animals on\n                     1) prosocial    and 2) agonistic      interactions,     3) scent-marking,     4) some aspects\n                     of howling and S) spatial        containment of lo1v-ranking animals was studied.\n                     Same-sex aggression       was higher in females than in males.          The presence of\n                     males correlated      with a striking     increase in levels of aggression between\n                     females.     TI1e rate of scent-marking        and howling was greater     for the dominant\n                     females than for any other individual            of either group.     TI1e only incident\n                     of spatial    containment occurred among females.\n\n13.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split4 at: 'J. Ryon'"}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "8-split4-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "From Percept to Concept: Parsing Prj..nciples\n                                                              for Perceptual Categories.", "authors_raw": "J. Barresi and B. MacCallum", "abstract": "When subjects     are asked to partition       random 9-dot patterns       into\n                     their \"natural\"     parts,  most of the subjects'      partitions     for a particular\n                     pattern can be fit into a single nested hierarchy              of parts.   Such hierarchies\n                     often differ even among quite \"similar\"         patterns.       How then do \\ve form abstract\n                     concepts to represent      a category of such related patterns?           Perhaps, with\n                     experience,   related patterns     assimilate   to a single nested hierarchy          of parts\n                     which comes to define the concept.          Evidence will be presented which supports\n                     this hypothesis.\n\n14.   W. J. Jacobs,      J. Hill-Flewelling,       and V. LoLordo.     More Quantitative      Properties\n                                                                                      of Anxiety.\n\nThree expei'iments investigated      the effects     of a CER procedure\n                     (Estes and Skinner, 1941) upon appetitively-motivated             wheel rwming.       Rats\n                     received the onset of a tone as a conditional          stimulus and the presentation\n                     of a brief electric        shock as the unconditional    stimulus.      Experiment 1 found\n       <0            that, unlike the 1,·ell-documented suppression        of an appetitively-motiv2ted\n       ~             lever-press    response,     the current preparation   produced acceleration       of\n                     appetitively-motivated        wheel running in the presence of the conditioned\n                     stimulus.     Facilitation      was not observed in the Random CS or No CS control\n                     conditions.      Experiment 2 demonstrated that conditioned          facilitation   is a - -------                                                                                                   ---------·· - 6.\n      function of the intensity  of the UCS: the more intense the UCS, the greater\n      the facilitation.   In Experiment 3, each rat was trained both to run in a wheel\n      and to press a lever for food reinforcement.       It was found that the rats\n      increased their rate of wheel running, but suppressed their rate of lever\n      pressing in the presence of the conditional     stimulus.   The results are discussed\n      in the context of Dickinson and Pearce's    recent (1977) model of conditioned\n      suppression.\n\n15.   J.   ~!ates and P. Paton.    The Malheur Swallows:", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split4 at: 'J. Barresi and B. MacCallum'"}
{"year": 1984, "entry_id": "5-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Dead or Alive:        When Motion Becomes Intention. ------ A single      object    moved on a Apple-controlled           monitor     according     to a quantifiable      rule.    Human observers      were asked to evaluate       its motion on six Likert Scales:         Mechanical,    Random, Purposive,       Intelligent,       Alive, and Human. The proportion              of foreward   versus    27° turns of the object affected     judgements on some of these scales.            Whether or not the object occasionally        stopped and changed direction          also affected        judgements. However, complex interactions              involving   sex of subject        and stimulus appearance argue against any simple interpretation               of these results.", "authors_raw": "J. Barresi     & E. Wyatt", "abstract": "2", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 5-split1 at: 'J. Barresi & E. Wyatt'"}
{"year": 1987, "entry_id": "23-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Subjects      viewed adaptation          stimuli       for l minute.        Then two rival       test\n    gratings,      differing    in orientation         from each other by 90 , were presented\n    one to each eye, for l minute and subjects                 recorded binocular       rivalry.     When\n    one eye was adapted,          rivalry     alternations      were briefer      for adaptation       and\n    test    gratings       of similar      orientation,        especially       in the adapted        eye.\n    However, when both eyes were adapted                    by rival   gratings,     the duration       of\n    rivalry    alternations     increased       in both eyes equally,         to produce symmetrical\n    U-shaped orientation            functions,         This implies       that rivalry      adaptation\n    affects    only binocular      units in the human visual system,·", "authors_raw": "Orientation          tuning   and binocularity         of binocular-rivalry   adaptation    in human\n    vision", "abstract": "26,", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 23-split1 at: 'Orientation'"}
{"year": 1987, "entry_id": "23-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Individual          Differences      in Attention:           Type~     and Type Band      Cognitive\n     Failure", "authors_raw": "M, Brennan", "abstract": "A significant       negative    correlation        was found between         two self-report\n     measures:      the JAS (Jenkins Activity          Survey) and the CFQ (Cognitive         Failure\n     Questionnaire).         The JAS is used to distinguish                  Type A from Type B\n     individuals.       The CFQ assesses       a person's      absent-mindedness      and everyday\n     errors,      Thus, the correlation         showed that Type A's reported           low CFQ and\n     Type B's reported      high CFQ, Previous          literature      has shown that ( 1) Type A\n     and Type B individuals       differ    in their attentional          mechanisms, and (2) high\n     CFQ and low CFQ differ       in attention,         My research      will involve    looking at\n     whether or not these attentional           differences       really exist,", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 23-split1 at: 'M, Brennan'"}
{"year": 1988, "entry_id": "5-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Mother      Care     and    Other       Care:     Some Differences             in Mother-Infant        Social Structure:----", "authors_raw": "P. Dunham,         F, Dunham and          c. Davis", "abstract": "While studying       the structure      of mother-infant       social                   interactions,         we\n                  encountered     some unexpected      and interesting     differences                       when comparing\n                  mothers     employed   outside    the home and mothers       who care                    for their    infants\n                  full-time     in the home.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 5-split1 at: 'P. Dunham'"}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "28-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Bringing home the bacon: food provisioning within a captive pack of coyotes (Canis latrans)", "authors_raw": "Jenny Ryon, Richard Brown, and John Fentress", "abstract": "Social behaviour in a pack of coyotes was observed for six years. This report concerns pup and\n       related feeding by adults. All adult members of coyote packs feed young. Some members also feed\n       pregnant and lactating females and yearlings. In our study, feeding began just before the birth of\n       pups and continued for about 24 weeks. One adult male (Obie) was the only individual to feed the\n       mother as well as the pups in the two years pups were born. The mother, another adult male and\n       adult female also.fed the pups in these two years. Obie and the mother but not the other adults also\n       fed the yearlings. All males were vasectomized before the mating season of the third year, thus no\n       further pups were born. Obie continued to feed his mate (the mother in past years) at the appropriate\n       time of year (i.e., just before the expected time of birth, as measured from the time of mating). He\n       also fed his \"pups\" from previous years. He continued this pattern of feeding for four years\n       (until his death) despite the fact that one of the male \"pups\" he fed had become dominant to him and\n       one of the female \"pups\" had become dominate to his mate. The mother also continued to feed\n       older off spring in the absence of new pups. We present data for six years and discuss these with\n       respect to the stimuli which activate food provisioning within coyote packs.\n\n------------------------•---~                                               --     --   .\n\n31.    April D'Aloisio and Ray Klein\n\nAgin~ andAttention\n\nThis study examined age differences in attention and the relationship among different tasks previously\n       used to measure attention. Sixteen community-dwelling older adults (X age= 61.1) and 16 young\n       undergraduates (X age= 19.4) were tested on three attention tasks: Treisman's serial search task,\n       Eriksen's distractor task and LaBerge's attentional range tasks. For all tasks, stimuli were arranged\n       on an imaginary circle in order to eliminate any effects of retinal eccentricity. In Treisman's task the\n       old showed slower search rates than young which suggests that the old were slower to shift their\n       attention than the young. Both the amount of interference and the shape of the interference function in\n       the Eriksen task was similar for both young and old indicating that there was no age difference in the\n       size of the attentional 'beam'; the probe data from the LaBerge narrow task also support this\n       conclusion. In sum, the results show that older subjects are able to control the size of the attentional\n\n~-\n       'beam' as well as young subjects, but they may not be as efficient at shifting their 'beam' as the\n       young. •", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28-split1 at: 'Jenny Ryon'"}
{"year": 1989, "entry_id": "32-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "\"Great Expectations\" and other tales of attention and set.", "authors_raw": "Alan Kingstone", "abstract": "Delayed crossing the Atlantic Ocean", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 32-split1 at: 'Alan Kingstone'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "19-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Ears on insect knees Crickets carry a pair of directionally-selectivehearing organs on their forelegs, which they use to home in on the calling songs of potential mates. They are distantly related to cockroaches, which have a simpler organ that until recently was believed to respond only to vibration, but which we showed last year also responds sensitively to sound. The roach subgenual (\"below the knee\") organ is particularly interesting in that it forms a conceptual bridge to explain the evolution of the more elaborate, pure auditory cricket's ear from an ancestral pure vibration receptor. We have found, unexpectedly, that the roach ear is also strongly directional. According to the standard physical theory applied to insect hearing organs, possession of directionality implies the presence of two sound input pathways to the organ. In crickets, the two entry points are an external tympanum on the leg, and internal air tubes (tracheae) connected to openings (spiracles) on the sides of the body. Only the tracheal pathway is obvious in roaches, with no evident tympanum. Attempts to pinpoint how and where sound gets into the knee will be described, along with tests that demonstrate that roaches can respond to sound, albeit feebly, given an appropriate behavioral assay.", "authors_raw": "Steve Shaw, Kathy Kokic and Don MacIntosh", "abstract": "22.   Jeffrey Hamm and Paddy McMullen\n      Identification, starting at the top\n             Viewing the same object from different angles results in different retinal images. We are\n             able to recognize these different visual inputs as the same object This is known as\n             object constancy. When line drawings of familiar objects are presented to subjects, the\n             time to name the object increases linearly for objects rotated up to 120 degrees from the\n             vertical. This function suggests that during object identification, the input is being\n             normalized to the upright, until a match is found in memory. Biederman (1989) has\n             suggested that the effects of orientation are due to finding the top of the object In order\n             to test this hypothesis, valid and invalid precues of object orientation will be presented\n             prior to the display of the object to be named. If the effect of orientation is in finding the\n             top, as Biederman has suggested then the valid cue condition should show less of an effect\n             of orientation than the invalid cue.\n\n23.   Dennis Phillips and Paula Tallal\n      Temporal auditory processing deficits in developmental dysphasia\n             The most comprehensive, if somewhat controversial, account of developmental dysphasia\n             is Tallal's. Briefly, she argues that the speech reception deficit is due to an auditory", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 19-split1 at: '21. Steve Shaw'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Neuropsychological assessment of subcortical dementia in Huntington's Disease Individuals with Huntington's Disease and Dementia of Alzheimer's Type (DAT) were examined on a neuropsychological battery designed to assess frontal, memory, and language abilities. The purpose of testing both DAT and HD subjects was to examine the distinctiveness of cortical and subcortical dementias and, by doing so, clarify the possible role that the basal ganglia pathology has in the mediation diverse set of cognitive proc~.      This comparison is especially important in light of the lackof direct comparisons made between HD and DAT. It was hypothesized that deficits in HD would be characterized by focal frontal deficits and subtle declines in memory while DAT would be madced by language difficulties coupled with generafu.edmemory deficits. Preliminary analysis indicates the existence of qualitative differences between HD and DAT which appear to reflect divergent pathological processes. It is proposed that cognitive changes in • HD and DAT support the position that dementia may be differentiated in terms of a cortical/subcorticaldimension.", "authors_raw": "David Colquhoun", "abstract": "3 1.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28-split1 at: 'David Colquhoun'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "What does the shape of neurons tell you about what neurons do?: Morphology of cholinergic and non-cholinergic cortically projecting neurons in the rat basal fore brain Neurons appear in different shapes. Whatever factors might be involved for these various shapes to form during development and then change during normal aging (as well as in pathological conditions), neuronal morphology often provides interesting insights as to functions of individual neurons. Previously we have shown that there are two physiological subtypes of cortically projecting neurons in the basal forebrain, and that these are also morphologically distinct, and have hypothesized that one subgroup is cholinergic and the other non-cholinergic. In the present study, we test the morphological aspect of this hypothesis, using retrograde tracing, single cell injections, and irnmunohistochemistry.", "authors_raw": "Kazue Semba", "abstract": "32.    P.D. Cole\n       Pigeon umwelt: Is a picture worth a thousand words?\n             Operant chamber techniques have yielded a diversity of information regarding various\n             facets of pigeon vision. More recently complex photographic material in the form of\n             slides, depicting sundry categories such as trees, cats, cars and people, has been employed\n             in category discrimination tasks. In such studies the assumption is presumably made that\n             the photographs are perceived by the Pigeons as representative of the three-dimensional\n             objects or scenes that they depict Are there enough salient dimensions present in a slide\n             photograph to allow it to function as a suitable representation of the Pigeons\n             environment and, if so, could it be used to explore the complexity of the Pigeon Umvelt?\n             Some recent work in this area will be presented.\n\n- 14 -\n\n3 3.   Elzbieta Pyza\n\nThe effect of quipazine • a serotonin agonist, on the circadian rhythm\n       of locomotor activity and the serotonin level in the brain of the house\n       cricket (Acheta domesticus L.)\n             The rhythm of locomotor activity in insects results from the function of an endogenous\n             pacemaker system and entrainment of this system by environmental factors (light)\n             changing during the 24 hour period. The aim of this study was to examine the role of\n             serotonin (5-HT) in the regulation of circadian rhythms. Results obtained indicated that\n             the circadian system controlling locomotor acitvity rhythms in the house cricket is\n             composed of two oscillators which act jointly (in DD - constant dark),or separately (in\n             LL constant light) and that 5-HT takes part in the regulation of overt rhythmicity. In LL,\n             injections of quipazine affected the phase of two c", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28-split1 at: 'Kazue Semba'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The secret to creating life Do humans equate spontaneous movement with being alive and having internal states? Do children think the same way as adults on these issues? Recently, researchers have been grappling with the effects of movement patterns on animacy and intentionality attributions. Unfortunately, most of these researchers have used objects familiar to the subject and hence they are subject to biases associated with previous experience. In the present study, we examine the role of endogenous movement in the attribution of animacy, motivation and internal states to unfamiliar objects. Subjects in grades 1, 4 and 7 and university were asked to respond to the following statement \"Tell me a story about what you have just seen\", after viewing a computer generated display consisting of two circular stimuli exhibiting three types of movement Results indicate that age, gender, as well as movement patterns all contribute to differences in these attributions.", "authors_raw": "Valerie Bolivar and John Barresi", "abstract": "37.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 34-split1 at: 'Valerie Bolivar'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The effect of regional compactness upon region discrimination time is modulated by oculomotor programming Podgomy & Shepard (1983) demonstrated that reaction time to determine if a target is on or off an attended region decreased with increasing compacbless of that region. Six experiments explored the nature of this compacbless effect and its relationship to visual attention. Subjects viewed a 3 x 3 grid in which there were shaded and unshaded regions. In four experiments their task was to determine a) if a target letter appearing in the shaded or unshaded region was a Tor L, orb) if a target stimulus was presented in the shaded or unshaded region. Eye position monitoring was used to ensure that subjects were not shifting gaze to inspect the display. The compacbless effect was not obtained in any of these experiments. In two further experiments eye position monitoring was NOT employed and the pattern reported by Podgomy & Shepard • a negative correlation between RT and compacbless • was observed. The RT/compactness relationship discovered by Podgomy & Shepard appears to be mediated by the programming of the oculomotor system and does not reflect the distribution of endogenously conttolled attention.", "authors_raw": "Mark Farrell and Raymond M. Klein", "abstract": "38.   Natasha Harvey\n      Integration of kinematic information in emotional judgments\n            Adults rated the happiness/sadness of 36 short film excerpts of a person whose facial and\n            body movements varied from excerpt to excerpt. There were three different facial\n            expression (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by mouth position and eye focus) and three\n            different body movement patterns (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by position and rate\n            of limb movement) combined factorially. The influence of both sources of information\n            on ratings was highly significant and in the manner predicted. Thus, emotional meaning\n            can be communicated by multidimensional kinematic information. Results are compared\n            with those from preschool children.\n\n• 16-\n\n39.   Heather Schellinck and Richard E. Brown\n      Discrimination of human male odours by rats is not influenced by the\n      relatedness of the urine donors\n            Rats can be trained in an olfactometer to discriminate between the urine odours of MHC\n            congenic rats and mice. They learn these discriminations quickly and remember the\n            information from one daily session to another. Such results indicate that constant odour\n            cues are used to discriminate between these urines (Schellinck, Brown and Slotnick,\n            Anim,Learn,Behay,.      in press). To determine if rats can discriminate between human\n            urines, we tested fiv", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 34-split1 at: 'Mark Farrell'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Imagination and social understanding It has been claimed that social understanding is achieved not so much through the development and application of a \"theory of mind\" but through the ability to pretend or imagine self in situations appropriate to another time or person. In this paper, I discuss recent work of ours on social reasoning tasks, in which children's judgements have to be made either from a third-person perspective or from an imagined first-person perspective. Initial results seem to support the idea that imagined or pretend contexts facilitate social reasoning.", "authors_raw": "Chris Moore", "abstract": ",---··\n\n- 18 -\n\n-   -   -·-------                 -~--------                                                                                     --~-   -----   ---\n\n45.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 42-split1 at: 'Chris Moore'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The dynamic properties of synapses in the fly's lamina In the first optic neuropile, or lamina. beneath the fly's (Musca domestica L.) compound eye photoreceptor terminals (Rl-R6) and intemeurons are reciprocally connected. At each afferent synaptic sites a presynaptic ribbon in R-R6 abuts a postsynaptic tetrad containing processes of two monopolar cells, Ll & L2. L2 in tum provides feedback input to Rl- R6 at a synaptic dyad. We have examined both afferent and feedback synapses, in each case following the loss of their main target cells. When R 1-R6 degenerated by photoablation, presynaptic ribbons of feedback synapses separated from teh presynaptic membrane and soon appeared free floating in L2's cytoplasm. Despite the presence of floating ribbons the number of L2 synapses increased twofold during an overlapping period of reactive synaptogenesis. When L1 and U degenerated by lesioning, presynaptic ribbons of afferent synapses were only mod~tely affected with slight decreases in their frequency. Thus many presynaptic ribbons in Rl-R6 outlive their postsynaptic partners. This difference in the reaction of photoreceptor and monopolar cells following the loss of postsynaptic partners, reflects a greater dependence of monopolar cells upon their targets, Rl-R6, than of Rl-R6 upon their targets, L2 and Ll.", "authors_raw": "J.H. Brandstatter,H.S. Seyan and I.A. Meinertzhagen", "abstract": "46.   John McNulty\n\nPsychological sequelae of carbon monoxide poisoning and their\n      treatment with hyperbaric oxygen\n            One of the most frequently observed symptoms of carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning is\n            \"mental\" or \"cognitive\" impairment. These symptoms often persist even when other\n            medical and neurological symptoms have disappeared. The standard treatment for\n            coexposure is hyperbaric oxygen. If symptoms are minor, or exposure time is short,\n            patients are sometimes treated only with oxygen at normal atmospheric pressure or are\n            not treated at all. There are, however, \"hints\" that failure to treat even mild cases may\n            result in relatively permanent neuropsychological deficits. Some preliminary data and\n            suggestions for research on the problem will be presented.\n\n47.   BrunoJ. Losier and KazueSemba\n      Cholinergic and aminergic inputs from the mesopontine area to the\n      basal forebrain and thalamus: A hypothesis for brainstem\n      involvement in cortical arousal\n            Researchers of behavioral states have investigated the role of specific direct and indirect\n            cholinergic inputs of the basal forebrain and mesopontine tegmental cholinergic areas in\n            the regulation of waking and sleep. This study examines the contribution of tegmental\n            cholinergic, serotonergic and dopaminergic c", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 42-split1 at: 'J.H. Brandstatter'"}
{"year": 1994, "entry_id": "T11-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Getting a GRiP on GRouP GRoPe in the Light", "authors_raw": "Michael Antle, Hugh Piggins, & Benjamin Rusak", "abstract": "In rodents, the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus is the\n                  circadian pacemaker. The SCN contains various substances which may be\n                  involved in photic entrainment of the pacemaker. The bombesin like peptide,\n                  gastrin-releasing peptide (GRP) is one such substance. The present study was\n                  designed to determine if GRP would phase shift hamsters housed in continuous\n                  illumination. GRP was found to produce \"light pulse-like\" shifts when injected to\n                  the SCN. These results suggest that GRP may be involved in photic entrainment.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T11-split1 at: 'Michael Antle'"}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Conflicting Desire And The Child's Theory Of Mind", "authors_raw": "Chris Moore", "abstract": "We contrast the standard representational theory of mind approach to the understanding\n                     of mental states with an alternative view which has it that theory of mind tasks require\n                     executive functioning or the inhibition of more 'cognitively salient' information. In the\n                     first experiment 3-5-year-olds were tested on their understanding of desire in others\n                     either when they themselves held a strong and conflicting desire or when they had no\n                     strong desire. Results showed that under the condition of having a strong and\n                     conflicting desire, only 5-year-olds were able to recognize that another person might\n                     desire something different In contrast when the children themselves held no strong\n                     desire, even 3-year-olds were able to judge another's desire correctly. The second\n                     experiment compared 3-year-olds' performance on a standard false belief task with that\n                     on an equivalently structured desire task in which subjects had again to inhibit their\n                     own strong and conflicting desire. Results showed similar performance on the\n                     traditional false belief task and the new conflicting desire task.\n          T19.    Beyond Immediate Self-Interest: Or, What Good Comes From Having A\n                  Theory of Mind?\n                  John Barresi, Carol Selig and Chris Moore\n\nThe purpose of this research was to investigate the early development of prudence\n                     and altruism involving future situations. The study tested the hypothesis that these\n                     are interrelated phenomena and that both should develop at approximately four years\n                     of age. Using a modified delay of gratification paradigm, 3- to 5-year-olds were\n                     tested on their ability to forgo a current desire for some stickers in order to further\n                     their own future interests or the current or future interests of a research assistant.\n                     Results showed that in current situations, altruism was unrelated to age. However,\n                     prudence and altruism involving the future situations were correlated with one another\n                     and with age. Children under four years of age performed significantly less well than\n                     the older children on the prudence task (F(l, 49) = 15.75; p<.001) and on the\n                     altruism task involving future situations, (F(l, 49) = 33.24; p<.001). Between three\n                     and five years, prudence and altruism showed a similar developmental pattern with\n                     performance increasing at age four.\n                   In Defense of Defenses: A User's Guide to the", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split1 at: \"Conflicting Desire And The Child's Theor\""}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T1-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Influence of the Male California Mouse (Peromyscus californicus) on", "authors_raw": "Pup Survival and Female Reproductive Success Richard E. Brown and Debora Cantoni", "abstract": "The California mouse is a monogamous rodent in which the male shows a high level of parental care. In our experiments, these mice were required to \"forage\" for food by running in a wheel. Male-female pairs could rear larger litters of pups to weaning than females alone and the pups with both parents grew faster. Single females who reared their pups to weaning had a longer inter-birth-interval than paired females. Our presentation will discuss the behaviour of the male which increases pup survival and facilitates implantation in the female.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T1-split1 at: 'The Influence of the Male California Mou'"}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T1-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Sexual and Maternal Behavior Correlates of Neuroanatomical Differences Between Inbred Mouse Strains", "authors_raw": "Kara Firth, Paul Neumann and Richard Brown", "abstract": "In rodents, the preoptic area (POA) of the hypothalamus has been demonstrated to have critical involvement in sexual and maternal physiology and behaviors. Structural differences in the POA have been found between two inbred mouse strains, DBN2J (02) and C57BU6J (B6) (Robinson et al, 1985). The B6 strain lacks a densely packed neuronal cluster (termed 'medioventral pars compacta') that is found in the D2 strain in the POA, on either side of the third ventricle; this compact nucleus may be homologous to The sexually dimorphic nucleus (SON) in rats. Preliminary results (Mathieson and Neumann, unpublished) suggest that this hypothalamic structural variant is an X-linked trait. These strains also show differences on sexual behavior measures such as male sexual performance (McGill and Manning, 1976) and maternal behavior measures such as infanticide (Svare and Broida, 1982; Svare et al, 1984). It is therefore possible that the structural variation between the two strains is responsible for the observed behavioral differences. Specific aims of this project are 1) to find experimental protocols that will reproduce published strain differences in sexual and maternal behaviors between D2 and B6 mice, and/or establish new ones, 2) to determine the mode of inheritance of these differences in classical crosses, and 3) to correlate variation in these behaviors with inheritance of the hypothalamic variant Therefore, this project provides a unique opportunity to consider a model system involving genetic variation and the resulting structural differences between mouse strains, and the postulated behavioral manifestations of these differences. 1996 In-House Convention                                                                      5 T5.       Roles of Tastes and Odours in Flavour Preference Conditioning Cathy Forestall In flavor aversion conditioning, tastes tend to facilitate or potentiate conditioning to odors when both stimuli are presented simultaneously. In the study to be discussed, the roles of tastes and odors in flavor preference conditioning were investigated using a reverse order reinforcement procedure. In the Experimental Condition, animals were exposed to an 8% sucrose solution followed after 5 minutes by either a citric acid solution (Taste Group) or an almond solution (Odor Group). The Taste and Odor Groups in the Control Condition received sucrose followed by either citric acid or almond solutions after 1 hour. During the test phase, there was a trend for animals in the Experimental Condi", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T1-split1 at: 'Sexual and Maternal Behavior Correlates'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "A translation of borderline and histronic personality disorders", "authors_raw": "Michael MacGregor, Karina Davidson and Stephanie Gustys", "abstract": "This paper addresses the translation of Borderline and Histrionic personality disorders into\n        the language of the Five-Factor model of personality. Based on theoretical expectations,\n        we investigated the empirical relationship between the Five-Factors of personality and these\n        two personality disorders in a non-clinical sample. As expected, the personality disorders\n        were characterized by high levels of Neuroticism. For Borderline personality disorder, our\n        expectations regarding Agreeableness were confirmed, however, those for Extraversion\n        were not As well, additional relationships were found between both Openness and\n        Conscientiousness and Borderline personality disorder. For Histrionic personality\n        disorder, our expectations for Extraversion were confirmed, however, those for Openness\n        were not Additionally, both Agreeableness and Conscientiousness demonstrated and\n        unexpected relationship with Histrionic personality disorder. While some of the expected\n        relationships between the Five-Factors and Borderline and Histrionic personality were\n        confirmed. others were not It appears that theoretical or clinical expectations are not\n        necessarily confirmed by empirical findings in a non-clinical sample. Results are discussed\n        in terms of the utility of the Five-Factor model in describing personality disorders.\n\nT20.    Becoming conscious of 'consciousness':               Notes for a history of an\n        important psychological concept\n        John Barresi\n\nDuring the 17th century the term of 'consciousness' suddenly appeared as a psychological\n        concept. Since then this concept has become increasingly important both in the foundations\n        and later developments of 'mental philosophy' and scientific psychology. Although during\n        the heyday of behaviourism it diminished in importance, interest in consciousness has been\n        revived again toward the end of this century. In the present talk I will look at the origins of\n        the use of this term, its ancient sources in Greek and Latin, its major 'discovery' in\n        Descartes, and its later development in the works of Cudworth, Locke, Leibniz, Hume,\n        and others in the late 17th and early 18th century.\n\n1997 In-House Convention                                                                    11\n\nT21. Attention (to the moving line): \"Where you lead, I will follow\".\n      Raymond M. Klein & Jeff P. Hamm\n\nWhen a line is presented in the vicinity of a recent luminance change (peripheral cue) it is\n      perceived to be drawn over time away from its \"cued\" end even though the line is actually\n      presented all at once. This study was designed to determine if attention, exogenously\n      attracted to the cue, would come under the", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split2 at: 'A translation of borderline'"}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T14-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Influences of Child Age and Parent Informant on the Associations Between Parenting", "authors_raw": "Practices and Child Behaviour Problems", "abstract": "This project investigated the influences of child age and parent informant (mother versus father report)\n        on the associations between parenting practices and conduct problem behaviour in a community sample\n        of children aged 5 to 12. Valid sample size for the computed regressions varied from 335 to 339.\n        Parenting practices were assessed using a modified version of the Alabama Parenting Questionnaire\n        (APQ; Frick, 1991). Conduct problems were defined by DSM-IV criteria for Oppositional Defiant\n        Disorder (ODD) and Conduct Disorder (CD), and assessed through the use of the Assessment of\n        Disruptive Symptoms, DSM-IV Version (ADS-IV; Pelham, Gnagy, Greenslade, & Milich, 1992). Both\n        mothers and fathers acted as informants for the two questionnaires. Preliminary analyses suggest that\n        the parenting practices of maternal involvement, poor monitoring and supervision of children's\n        activities, as well as inconsistent discipline, are significantly associated with number of CD and number\n        of ODD symptoms in children. The magnitude of these associations varied according to whether it was\n        the mothers or the fathers who reported the practices. In contrast with previous research in a clinical\n        sample, results did not show a significant child age trend in the associations. This project has significant\n        implications for the parent training component of the psychosocial interventions that are currently used\n        for CD and ODD.\n\nTl 7.   Time Course of Linguistic Processing as indexed by Event-Related Brain Potentials (ERPs)\n\nRandy Lynn Newman and John F. Connolly\n\nWhile most theories of visual word recognition agree that access to meaning is meditated by phonology,\n        some theories contend that words can access their meaning directly, without phonological mediation.\n        ERPs, unlike behavioral measures of word recognition, provide an on-line measure of cognitive\n        processing without requiring overt behavioral responses. Indeed, a number of ERP components have\n        been found to be sensitive to orthographic, phonological, and semantic information. The goals of the\n        present study were to disentangle orthographic and semantic processing, and to define phonology's role\n        on route to accessing semantic information. ERPs were recorded to the terminal words of visually\n        presented sentences. Phonological/ orthographic and/or semantic characteristics of terminal words were\n        manipulated in 4 conditions in which: (1) the terminal word was the highest cloze probability ending\n        (e.g. Larry writes with his left hand.) (congruent); (2) the terminal word was orthographically\n        inappropriate, but was phonologically identical to the highest cloze probability ending (e.g. T", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T14-split1 at: 'The Influences of Child Age'"}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Ryan C.N. D'Arcy!, John F. Connollyl,2, Frank P. MacMaster2, Robert Vandorpe3, Larry Gates3,\n       Sultan Darvesh4, and Matthias Schrrtidt5 I. Cognitive/Clinical Neuroscience Unit, Department of\n       Psychology, Dalhousie University; 2. Department of Psychiatry, Dalhousie University; 3. Department\n       of Radiology, Dalhousie University; 4. Department of Medicine (Neurology and Geriatric Medicine),\n       Dalhousie University; and 5. Department of Diagnostic Imaging, The Hospital for Sick Children,\n       Toronto", "authors_raw": "Transcallosal While Matter Activation Revealed by Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging\n       During Reading", "abstract": "Functional :MRI has been used to demonstrate gray matter activation associated with sensory and\n       cognitive functions. We provide the first evidence of f:MRI activation in ~'.h_i!e_~aJJer(1.5T). This\n       activation was observed in comrrtissural fiber tracts passing through the splenium of the corpus callosum\n       during sentence reading. The time course data from white matter voxels revealed that, like gray matter\n       activation, the responses were time-locked to the stimulus presentation. However, as expected, the white\n       matter peak amplitudes were markedly attenuated relative to the responses in the visual cortex.\n       Reliability of the white matter activation was established by replicating fully the effect in a participant\n       following a six-month interval. The active white matter regions localized the comrrtissural fibers that\n       connect functionally specialized visual word form areas. These findings provide the first noninvasive\n       identification of the neural architecture involved in sentence reading.\n\nT19.   An investigation of the phonological processing in Chinese language with ERPs\n\nJingtian Wang and John Connolly\n\nTwo unique features of Chinese language draw much attention and interest in psycholinguistics. The\n       first is that Chinese written language is pictographic. There is an opaque relationship between the\n       pronunciation and physical appearance of a Chinese character. For example, homophones have the exact\n       same pronunciation but completely different script feature and meaning. This opacity of the script-to-\n       sound relationship has led to a widespread assumption that readers of Chinese can arrive at the mental\n       lexicon by identifying a whole character visually, without any involvement with phonological coding.\n       The issue of whether there is phonological code involved in Chinese reading was investigated with the\n       recording of ERPs. The other specific feature of Chinese language is that it is a tone language. Most\n       Chinese characters consist of monosyllables with an affiliated lexical tone and the tonality of a\n       monosyllable is lexically meaningful. Though the perception of tone plays a major role in Chinese\n       speech comprehension, little is known about its underlying electrophysiological b", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split1 at: 'Transcallosal While Matter Activation'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Matt Stone looks just ravishing in his pink dress\" Irony in computer-mediated conversations.", "authors_raw": "Jeff Hancock and Philip Dunham", "abstract": "The text-based conversations that occur in email and internet chat environments eliminate many of the\n       non-verbal signals, such as facial expressions and tone of voice, that we rely on to interpret a speaker's\n       intent. The present study assessed the impact of computer-mediated communication (CMC) on the use\n       of ironic forms (e.g., irony, hyperbole, understatement, rhetorical questions) in conversations between\n       strangers. Given the reduction in the cues available in CMC to signal irony, we expected less use of\n       irony in this impoverished environment than in face-to-face conversations. Comparison of 40\n       conversations across these two communicative environments indicated that, contrary to initial\n       expectations, substantially more ironic language was produced in the CMC condition. This general\n       finding has several implications for current theoretical accounts of the comprehension and production of\n       verbal irony.\n\nT20.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15-split3 at: 'Matt Stone looks just ravishing'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Neurobiology of sleep deprivation effects on mood in major depressive disorder", "authors_raw": "Denise Bernier", "abstract": "The goal of this pilot study is to assess the neurotransmitter changes in the brain that correlate with the\n       improvement of mood in depression. Sleep deprivation therapy has consistently shown an acute,\n       although transient, improvement of depressive symptoms in more than half of patients suffering from\n       major depression. A test-retest magnetic resonance spectroscopy will be performed before and after half\n       a night of sleep deprivation in a sample of female patients (n=12) in their twenties, suffering from major\n       unipolar depression. We will investigate the medial prefrontal cortex, which was already identified by\n       brain imaging studies as showing metabolic differences before and after sleep deprivation in responders,\n       and the limbic structures, which have been shown to be involved in emotional expression. We expect the\n       glutamatergic peak on the MRS spectra to change in association with changes in mood.\n\nT21.   Using Taste Reactivity to Measure Shifts in the Palatability of Conditioned Taste Cues\n\nCatherine A. Forestell and Vincent M. LoLordo\n\nTastes become more preferred after they have been paired with sugar reinforcement in a classical\n       conditioning paradigm. The mechanism involved in the formation of conditioned taste preferences is\n       not clear. It is possible that conditioned preferences occur because animals learn to expect calories upon\n       consumption of the taste cue. Alternatively, the conditioning procedure may produce an increase in the\n       palatability of the taste cue. Typically the taste reactivity test is used to assess the palatability of tastes.\n       This test involves measuring a rat's hedonic and aversive affective responses to oral infusions of taste\n       solutions. In this talk I will describe some of the taste reactivity experiments currently being conducted\n       in our laboratory to assess palatability shifts in conditioned taste cues.\n\nT22.   Challenges of running research in a large laboratory class: An animal experiment where the\n       researchers outnumber the animals by 30 to 1\n\nHeather Schellinck(l), Ron Hoffman(!) and John MacDonald(2). (1) Department of Psychology\n       (2) Academic Computing Services\n\nAs part of the continuing evolution of the introductory psychology class (P 1001) into a laboratory class,\n       this past year an animal research project was incorporated into the curriculum. Eighteen mice were\n       assigned to either of two groups. Mice in the experimental group received caffeine in their drinking\n       water. The mice were then observed in an open field apparatus, and experimenters recorded several\n       behaviours. With over 600 potential experimenters, the logistics were challenging. In this talk, we\n       describe how live observations were combined with additional observat", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15-split3 at: 'Neurobiology of sleep deprivation'"}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Using a novel method that could be applied quite broadly to both normal and neurologically damaged subjects we assess right and left biases in global stimuli across hemifields.  In the same experiment, without changes in instruction, we also assess local laterality effects across hemifields and across objects within a hemifield.  Findings are as expected in normal participants but with larger effect sizes than previously found in similar studies.  A lone neurological patient is presented who shows a unique laterality difference from the healthy controls for local items.", "authors_raw": "Seeing the forest on the left and the trees on the right\n\tJohn Christie", "abstract": "T47)", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44-split1 at: 'Seeing the forest on'"}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Picking a flavor: Do perceptual processing strategies drown out motoric IOR effects?", "authors_raw": "Greg MacLean, Matt Hilchey, & Ray Klein", "abstract": "At short cue-target onset asynchronies, irrelevant cues can “capture” attention, resulting in a response benefit when they cue the location of a upcoming target, and incurring a response cost when they do not. However, participants can selectively filter task irrelevant cues if they differ predictably from task-relevant stimuli on some salient dimension such as color (Folk, Remington & Johnston, 1992) or spatial location (Ishigami, Klein, & Christie, 2009). This selective filter, termed an “attentional control setting”, has been shown to modulate the early facilitative effects of cueing, but not the inhibitory aftereffects (Often referred to as Inhibition of Return or “IOR”; Pratt & McAuliffe, 2002). In the present study, a manipulation similar to that of Ishigami et al (2009) was used in order to induce a spatial ACS in participants, and responses to central arrow targets were used to measure the cueing effects of irrelevant non-informative cues. Evidence also suggests that IOR can be separated into two semi-distinct “flavors”; one perceptual and the other motoric (Taylor & Klein, 2000) but activation of the motor system does not seem to affect expression of the perceptual flavor (Chica, Taylor, Lupianez & Klein, 2010). By mixing saccadic and manual target trials within blocks and varying the relative probability of those trials it was expected that participants might invoke their perceptual flavor of processing, shutting down the oculomotor system and eliminating saccade-measured IOR. Results are discussed with focus on implications for spatial attentional control and the divergent typologies of IOR.\n\nT48)\tPreliminary findings on the anti-epileptic and anti-anxiety effects of leaf-extracts of Chinese lantern tree (dichrostachys glomerata) in albino mice\n\tSunday A. Bisong & E. E. Osim\n\nThe leaves of the Chinese lantern tree (Dichrostachys  glomerata) are used as a spice and for medicinal purposes in Africa. The use of the leaf-extracts of this plant as an anti-epileptic drug in traditional medicine has left more questions than answers. The aim of this study was to test the anti-epileptic and anti-anxiety effects of the ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata in mice. Ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata (DG) were phytochemically analyzed and lethality studies done.  The phytochemical constituents of ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata included 10.60% alkaloids, 0.02% saponins, 2.55% tannins, 4.2% flavonoids, 2.16% cardiac glycosides, traces of moisture, ash, protein and some other reducing compounds and its LD50 was 13.5mg/kg, from which an ED50 of 4.5 mg/kg was calculated. To test anti-epileptic effect of the extract, seizures were induced in 20 mice using 80 mg/kg of penthylene tetrazol (PTZ).  Ten mice were given PTZ alone (80mg/kg, i.p.) and the other 10 mice given PTZ 30 minutes after pre-treatment with ethanol lea", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44-split1 at: 'Picking a flavor:'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "For Aristotle psychology was an integral part of the biology of animate beings. But, with the rise of Christianity and its emphasis on Plato’s earlier idea of the immortality of the rational human soul, Western thinkers were ready for Descartes’ revolutionary theory, which distinguished sharply between the conscious rational soul of humans and body-machines. While subsequent thinkers rejected Descartes’ idea that all other animals were mere automata, without conscious minds, the majority of 18th and 19th century scientists continued to distinguish conscious processes of minds and purely material processes of animate bodies, including the brain. A consequence of this historical development has been that psychology and neurobiology have been separate disciplines until quite recently.", "authors_raw": "Why psychology and neuroscience separated as sciences\nJohn Barresi", "abstract": "", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50-split1 at: 'Why psychology and neuroscience separate'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "In the 1940's, there were many \"Schools\" of psychology, such as Gestalt Psychology, Structuralism, Functionalism, Behaviourism, etc., each of which looked at behaviour in a different way. There were also a plethora of \"physiological\" theories of behaviour proposed by Pavlov, Lashley, Morgan, and others.  Each theory focused on a different aspect of behaviour: learning, memory, development, motivation, emotion and clinical problems.  What Hebb did, with two simple concepts, the modifiable synapse and the cell assembly, was to provide a neural mechanism which could account for all of the different categories of behaviour that psychologists were struggling to explain with their separate theories. The result was to change Psychological theory and reintroduce the idea that a neural mechanism was the basis for all behaviour, normal and abnormal and that one of the aims of Psychology was to understand that physiological mechanism. Hebb's aim was to show that the psychological study of the \"mind\" required a biological approach.", "authors_raw": "How Donald Hebb brought psychology and neuroscience back together\nRichard Brown", "abstract": "A neo-Hebbian blueprint for the integration of neuro-psychological science and the mission of our Department\nRaymond M. Klein\n\nWith Hebb's ideas providing a backdrop, the recent history of our discipline will be related to a (somewhat) personalized history of the department. Divisions based on workplace (laboratory versus clinic), type of work (studies of brain versus behavior; animals versus humans), sub-discipline (development, perception, personality, learning, etc.) and favorite causal mechanism (nature vs nurture) characterize these histories. Importantly, conceptual, methodological and technological innovations have made it possible for us to implement Hebb's neuropsychological vision of the discipline through an integrated effort to understand how nature and nurture shape the neural networks that underlie the organization of our overt and covert behaviors.\n\nThe future of psychology and neuroscience \nOlav Krigolson\n\nOur increasing ability to see into the mind has helped scientists adapt theory to match the computations that are actually performed within the brain. For example, rational choice theory would posit that when faced with a decision, one should always choose the response option with the highest utility, or value. However, that is not always the case. When humans play the “ultimatum game” frequently people make irrational decisions – they reject proffered money in the name of “fairness”. Functional imaging has given us insight into why this occurs, and has forced a reconciliation of rational choice theory with psychological theory. As we head into the future, technological advances in human neuroimaging will only allow us to see further into the processes of the mind and explain other phenomenon. For instance, recent advances in neuroimaging have taken us into the realm of mind reading – a technology that knows what we are thinking", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50-split1 at: 'How Donald Hebb brought psychology and n'"}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split5-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Extensive evidence suggests neuroticism (i.e., a dispositional tendency to experience negative emotional states) is a higher order personality trait that shares substantial variance with perfectionism dimensions and depressive symptoms (Graham et al., 2010; Sherry et al., 2012). Such evidence raises an important question: are perfectionism dimensions vulnerability factors for depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism? The present meta-analysis examined the existing evidence testing if perfectionism dimensions (i.e., self-oriented perfectionism, socially prescribed perfectionism, concern over mistakes, doubts about actions, and perfectionistic attitudes) predict changes in depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism. A comprehensive meta-analysis of 10 longitudinal studies involving 1858 participants from undergraduate, community, and psychiatric samples indicated all five perfectionism dimensions significantly predicted changes in depressive symptoms after neuroticism was taken into account. Perfectionism dimensions consistently predicted changes in depressive symptoms across a wide range of samples, methods, and measures. Observed effect sizes were small to moderate in magnitude. Results lend credence to and bring coherence to theoretical accounts, case histories, and empirical studies suggesting perfectionism dimensions are part of the premorbid personality of people vulnerable to depressive symptoms. Results also suggest perfectionism dimensions are unique lower order personality traits that add incrementally to understanding of depressive symptoms above and beyond neuroticism. Perfectionism dimensions appear neither redundant with nor captured by neuroticism. Findings from the present meta-analysis are incongruent with a view of self-oriented perfectionism as an adaptive personality trait associated with positive outcomes. In contrast, results indicate self-oriented perfectionism may represent a form of counterproductive overstriving that confers vulnerability to depressive symptoms. Although self-oriented perfectionism is often labeled as adaptive, such assertions appear premature.", "authors_raw": "Is Perfectionism a Vulnerability Factor for Depression After Controlling for Neuroticism?\nTara M. Gralnick and Simon Sherry", "abstract": "P2) \tAddictive Personalities \nSari McLin and Mairi Keay\n\nResearch has discovered that there are four personality risk factors, as well as other factors such as resilience, that affect how individuals are susceptible to addictions. Addictions, being harmful and dangerous for those affected, are very difficult to treat and yet it is very important to do so. The purpose of this experiment is to determine how individuals with different risk and protection factors respond to a quitting smoking program. Smoking habit and risk factor surveys, as well as piCO measurements, were completed by a sample population of adolescents. The data was then evaluated for correlation values and p-values using statistic software. It was disco", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T50-split5 at: 'Is Perfectionism'"}

