{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "6-split1-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "Depending on the requirements of the situation, it is\n believed that an organism, such as a pigeon, can either remember a\n stimulus or a future behaviour required by the present stimulus. Honig\n has shown that in situations in which a pigeon is only required to\n remember whether to peck or not, remembering occurs over longer inter-\n vals than are normally found with procedures which require the recall\n of a stimulus. The present research uses a procedure which also requires\n only that the pigeon remember whether to respond or not, It is simpler\n than those that have been used previously. Since this seems to produce\n as much recall in pigeons as Honig's procedure, this hypothesis is"}}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "19-split1-split1", "patch": {"title": "Ears on insect knees", "abstract": "22. Jeffrey Hamm and Paddy McMullen\n Identification, starting at the top\n Viewing the same object from different angles results in different retinal images. We are\n able to recognize these different visual inputs as the same object This is known as\n object constancy. When line drawings of familiar objects are presented to subjects, the\n time to name the object increases linearly for objects rotated up to 120 degrees from the\n vertical. This function suggests that during object identification, the input is being\n normalized to the upright, until a match is found in memory. Biederman (1989) has\n suggested that the effects of orientation are due to finding the top of the object In order\n to test this hypothesis, valid and invalid precues of object orientation will be presented\n prior to the display of the object to be named. If the effect of orientation is in finding the\n top, as Biederman has suggested then the valid cue condition should show less of an effect\n of orientation than the invalid cue."}}
{"year": 1996, "entry_id": "T1-split1", "patch": {"title": "The Cannabinoid Agonist CPSS, 940 Reduces Ultrasonic Vocalizations of\n       Infant Rats", "authors_raw": "Brown, Richard amd  Dastur, Farhard and  McLennan, Ashley and McGregor, Iain"}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T37-split1", "patch": {"authors_raw": "Patrick J. McGrath, Christina Romos, Carol Camfield, Mary Ann Campbell, Allan Hennigar", "abstract": "Primary caregivers of 20 children (age=14.5 years and recruited, language level=lO months) were and pain, interviewed to recall 2 instances of short sharp and pain, 2 of longer-lasting and reviewed, describe their child's behaviour. Transcribed interviews were and sets of non-overlapping items were developed. Thirty one behaviours were extracted from the interviews. The specific behaviors were often different from one child to another but the classes of behaviors (Vocal, Eating/Sleeping, Socia1/Personality, Facial Expression, Activity, Body and Limbs and validity, Physiological) were common. Relibility of using the checklist on interviews was good (kappa=.77). The checklist has excellent content and will be useful for caregivers of cognitively-impaired, non-communicating children to report on pain behaviors"}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T9-split1", "patch": {"title": "Perceptions of movement", "authors_raw": "Fentress, John"}}
