{"year": 1998, "entry_id": "T44-split1", "patch": {"title": "Symposium To Hebb and Beyond", "authors_raw": "", "abstract": "Donald Hebb was one of Canada's most famous and distinguished scientists, whose contributions were manifold and writings prolific. Hebb is widely recognized for his neoconnectionist assumption that correlated firing results in improved synaptic transmission (increase in connection weight) and his proposal of the cell assemblies. Hebb was a major advocate of psychology as a science and was a major force in directing its evolution in the 20th century. In order to examine Hebb and his work in a broader context, we will attempt to situate Hebb and his ideas within history, both in terms of the people who influenced him as well as in how his ideas shaped (or failed to shape) subsequent researchers. Some of the areas influenced by Hebb include LTP,kindling, neural networks, animal learning and memory, mental imagery, stopped retinal image, pain, aging and the role of early experience in cognitive and perceptual development. A life history of Hebb connecting significant life events to the various areas of interest integrates the diverse fields in which Hebb made a notable impact. For example, the publication of the Organization of Behavior ( 1949), which was influenced by the writings of William James and Santiago Ramon y Cajal, has exerted an ever-growing influence on those interested in mind, brain and how brains implement mind."}}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T14-split1-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "This project investigated the influences of child age and parent informant (mother versus father report)\n on the associations between parenting practices and conduct problem behaviour in a community sample\n of children aged 5 to 12. Valid sample size for the computed regressions varied from 335 to 339.\n Parenting practices were assessed using a modified version of the Alabama Parenting Questionnaire\n (APQ; Frick, 1991). Conduct problems were defined by DSM-IV criteria for Oppositional Defiant\n Disorder (ODD) and Conduct Disorder (CD), and assessed through the use of the Assessment of\n Disruptive Symptoms, DSM-IV Version (ADS-IV; Pelham, Gnagy, Greenslade, & Milich, 1992). Both\n mothers and fathers acted as informants for the two questionnaires. Preliminary analyses suggest that\n the parenting practices of maternal involvement, poor monitoring and supervision of children's\n activities, as well as inconsistent discipline, are significantly associated with number of CD and number\n of ODD symptoms in children. The magnitude of these associations varied according to whether it was\n the mothers or the fathers who reported the practices. In contrast with previous research in a clinical\n sample, results did not show a significant child age trend in the associations. This project has significant\n implications for the parent training component of the psychosocial interventions that are currently used\n for CD and ODD."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1", "patch": {"title": "Bayes in brief: philosophy and application", "authors_raw": "Lawrence, Mike", "abstract": "While quantitative methods in psychology and neuroscience have traditionally been dominated by the \"null hypothesis significance testing\" (NHST) philosophy of statistics, recent advances in computing have permitted alternative approaches, most notably Bayesian methods. This talk will briefly distinguish the philosophical backgound of NHST and Bayesian methods followed by a walk-through of a simple Bayesian analysis. The talk will conclude with discussion of the power of Bayesian methods to address more advanced analyses."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1-split1", "patch": {"title": "Why psychology and neuroscience separated as sciences", "authors_raw": "Barresi, John", "abstract": "For Aristotle psychology was an integral part of the biology of animate beings. But, with the rise of Christianity and its emphasis on Plato’s earlier idea of the immortality of the rational human soul, Western thinkers were ready for Descartes’ revolutionary theory, which distinguished sharply between the conscious rational soul of humans and body-machines. While subsequent thinkers rejected Descartes’ idea that all other animals were mere automata, without conscious minds, the majority of 18th and 19th century scientists continued to distinguish conscious processes of minds and purely material processes of animate bodies, including the brain. A consequence of this historical development has been that psychology and neurobiology have been separate disciplines until quite recently."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split1-split2", "patch": {"title": "How Donald Hebb brought psychology and neuroscience back together", "authors_raw": "Brown, Richard", "abstract": "In the 1940's, there were many \"Schools\" of psychology, such as Gestalt Psychology, Structuralism, Functionalism, Behaviourism, etc., each of which looked at behaviour in a different way. There were also a plethora of \"physiological\" theories of behaviour proposed by Pavlov, Lashley, Morgan, and others.  Each theory focused on a different aspect of behaviour: learning, memory, development, motivation, emotion and clinical problems.  What Hebb did, with two simple concepts, the modifiable synapse and the cell assembly, was to provide a neural mechanism which could account for all of the different categories of behaviour that psychologists were struggling to explain with their separate theories. The result was to change Psychological theory and reintroduce the idea that a neural mechanism was the basis for all behaviour, normal and abnormal and that one of the aims of Psychology was to understand that physiological mechanism. Hebb's aim was to show that the psychological study of the \"mind\" required a biological approach."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split5", "patch": {"title": "The future of psychology and neuroscience", "authors_raw": "Krigolson, Olav", "abstract": "Our increasing ability to see into the mind has helped scientists adapt theory to match the computations that are actually performed within the brain. For example, rational choice theory would posit that when faced with a decision, one should always choose the response option with the highest utility, or value. However, that is not always the case. When humans play the “ultimatum game” frequently people make irrational decisions - they reject proffered money in the name of “fairness”. Functional imaging has given us insight into why this occurs, and has forced a reconciliation of rational choice theory with psychological theory. As we head into the future, technological advances in human neuroimaging will only allow us to see further into the processes of the mind and explain other phenomenon. For instance, recent advances in neuroimaging have taken us into the realm of mind reading - a technology that knows what we are thinking as we are thinking it. Not only does research like this give us better insight into why we do and say the things we do, but it also puts us right in front of Pandora's Box - forcing to us to an understanding that we might not want to have."}}
{"year": 2013, "entry_id": "T50-split5-split1", "patch": {"title": "Is Perfectionism a Vulnerability Factor for Depression After Controlling for Neuroticism?", "authors_raw": "Gralnick,  Tara M. and Sherry, Simon", "abstract": "Extensive evidence suggests neuroticism (i.e., a dispositional tendency to experience negative emotional states) is a higher order personality trait that shares substantial variance with perfectionism dimensions and depressive symptoms (Graham et al., 2010; Sherry et al., 2012). Such evidence raises an important question: are perfectionism dimensions vulnerability factors for depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism? The present meta-analysis examined the existing evidence testing if perfectionism dimensions (i.e., self-oriented perfectionism, socially prescribed perfectionism, concern over mistakes, doubts about actions, and perfectionistic attitudes) predict changes in depressive symptoms after controlling for neuroticism. A comprehensive meta-analysis of 10 longitudinal studies involving 1858 participants from undergraduate, community, and psychiatric samples indicated all five perfectionism dimensions significantly predicted changes in depressive symptoms after neuroticism was taken into account. Perfectionism dimensions consistently predicted changes in depressive symptoms across a wide range of samples, methods, and measures. Observed effect sizes were small to moderate in magnitude. Results lend credence to and bring coherence to theoretical accounts, case histories, and empirical studies suggesting perfectionism dimensions are part of the premorbid personality of people vulnerable to depressive symptoms. Results also suggest perfectionism dimensions are unique lower order personality traits that add incrementally to understanding of depressive symptoms above and beyond neuroticism. Perfectionism dimensions appear neither redundant with nor captured by neuroticism. Findings from the present meta-analysis are incongruent with a view of self-oriented perfectionism as an adaptive personality trait associated with positive outcomes. In contrast, results indicate self-oriented perfectionism may represent a form of counterproductive overstriving that confers vulnerability to depressive symptoms. Although self-oriented perfectionism is often labeled as adaptive, such assertions appear premature."}}
{"year": 2014, "entry_id": "T50", "patch": {"title": "Integrating methods from neuroscience, experimental psychology, and computer science in the study of cognitive science", "authors_raw": "Satel, Jason", "abstract": "Cognitive science is widely considered to be the last frontier of scientific inquiry. In order to adequately investigate difficult questions in cognitive science, we must begin integrating techniques from multiple disciplines. Although my work so far has focused primarily on the study of visual attention, I am interested in using multiple interdisciplinary methods to investigate questions in cognitive science pertaining to many different topics, including, for example, attention, learning, memory, language, and disorders associated with such functions. In this talk, I will demonstrate how I have integrated methods from neuroscience, psychology, and computer science to investigate a cognitive phenomenon, termed inhibition of return, as an example of how such techniques can be combined to provide insight on difficult topics. I believe this work can be used as a model for the integration of multiple techniques throughout cognitive science and revolutionize the field."}}
{"year": 2023, "entry_id": "T5", "patch": {"abstract": "Children in French immersion (FI) experience a lag in English literacy skills through the early grades of\nelementary school, until English instruction is introduced into the curriculum. Here we recruited third grade English and\nFI students to complete a novel-word learning paradigm, and a lexical decision task during EEGrecording, to compare\nN170 print and lexical tuning effects between the two groups. The N170 print and lexical tuning effects are measured\nusing event-related brain potentials (ERPs) and have been shown to relate to behavioural measures of reading\ndevelopment. We hypothesized FI students would demonstrate bilateral N170 print tuning and no lexical tuning, while\nEnglish students would demonstrate more left-lateralized print and lexical tuning of the N170, and higher reading\nproficiency. Findings demonstrated English and FI students performed similarly on behavioural assessments of reading.\nHowever, while both groups demonstrated print tuning effects, lexical tuning was only observed for English students.\nThese findings demonstrate measurable differences in neural activity during reading between English and FI students, that\ndo not necessarily indicate a lag in reading skill for FI students."}}
