{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "We contrast the standard representational theory of mind approach to the understanding\n                     of mental states with an alternative view which has it that theory of mind tasks require\n                     executive functioning or the inhibition of more 'cognitively salient' information. In the\n                     first experiment 3-5-year-olds were tested on their understanding of desire in others\n                     either when they themselves held a strong and conflicting desire or when they had no\n                     strong desire. Results showed that under the condition of having a strong and\n                     conflicting desire, only 5-year-olds were able to recognize that another person might\n                     desire something different In contrast when the children themselves held no strong\n                     desire, even 3-year-olds were able to judge another's desire correctly. The second\n                     experiment compared 3-year-olds' performance on a standard false belief task with that\n                     on an equivalently structured desire task in which subjects had again to inhibit their\n                     own strong and conflicting desire. Results showed similar performance on the\n                     traditional false belief task and the new conflicting desire task."}}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split2-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "This paper addresses the translation of Borderline and Histrionic personality disorders into\n        the language of the Five-Factor model of personality. Based on theoretical expectations,\n        we investigated the empirical relationship between the Five-Factors of personality and these\n        two personality disorders in a non-clinical sample. As expected, the personality disorders\n        were characterized by high levels of Neuroticism. For Borderline personality disorder, our\n        expectations regarding Agreeableness were confirmed, however, those for Extraversion\n        were not As well, additional relationships were found between both Openness and\n        Conscientiousness and Borderline personality disorder. For Histrionic personality\n        disorder, our expectations for Extraversion were confirmed, however, those for Openness\n        were not Additionally, both Agreeableness and Conscientiousness demonstrated and\n        unexpected relationship with Histrionic personality disorder. While some of the expected\n        relationships between the Five-Factors and Borderline and Histrionic personality were\n        confirmed. others were not It appears that theoretical or clinical expectations are not\n        necessarily confirmed by empirical findings in a non-clinical sample. Results are discussed\n        in terms of the utility of the Five-Factor model in describing personality disorders."}}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "Functional :MRI has been used to demonstrate gray matter activation associated with sensory and\n       cognitive functions. We provide the first evidence of f:MRI activation in ~'.h_i!e_~aJJer(1.5T). This\n       activation was observed in comrrtissural fiber tracts passing through the splenium of the corpus callosum\n       during sentence reading. The time course data from white matter voxels revealed that, like gray matter\n       activation, the responses were time-locked to the stimulus presentation. However, as expected, the white\n       matter peak amplitudes were markedly attenuated relative to the responses in the visual cortex.\n       Reliability of the white matter activation was established by replicating fully the effect in a participant\n       following a six-month interval. The active white matter regions localized the comrrtissural fibers that\n       connect functionally specialized visual word form areas. These findings provide the first noninvasive\n       identification of the neural architecture involved in sentence reading."}}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3-split2", "patch": {"abstract": "The goal of this pilot study is to assess the neurotransmitter changes in the brain that correlate with the\n       improvement of mood in depression. Sleep deprivation therapy has consistently shown an acute,\n       although transient, improvement of depressive symptoms in more than half of patients suffering from\n       major depression. A test-retest magnetic resonance spectroscopy will be performed before and after half\n       a night of sleep deprivation in a sample of female patients (n=12) in their twenties, suffering from major\n       unipolar depression. We will investigate the medial prefrontal cortex, which was already identified by\n       brain imaging studies as showing metabolic differences before and after sleep deprivation in responders,\n       and the limbic structures, which have been shown to be involved in emotional expression. We expect the\n       glutamatergic peak on the MRS spectra to change in association with changes in mood."}}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T20-split1", "patch": {"abstract": "Previous research has demonstrated that mice are capable of brightness discrimination and visual\npattern discrimination and that it is possible to quantitatively determine the visual acuity of the\nmouse. Based on the procedure of Glen Prusky (Prusky et al., 2000, Vision Research, 40, 2201-\n2209), we have developed a protocol using a computer-based, two-alternative swim task that\nevaluates visual discrimination, pattern discrimination and visual acuity in one apparatus. Seven\nstrains of mice (BALB/cByJ, C3H/HeSnJ, C57BL/6J, Coloboma, DBA/2J, FVB/NJ and\nMOLF/Ei) were tested on 8 trials/day for 8 days on each of the three tests. There was a\nsignificant strain difference in visual ability in all three tests. Mice with normal vision\n(C57BL/6J and DBA/2J) performed very well in these tasks. Mice with poor vision\n(BALB/cByJ) took longer to learn the tasks than mice with normal vision and mice with retinal\ndegeneration (C3H/HeSnJ, Coloboma, FVB/NJ, MOLF/Ei) performed only at chance levels.\nBecause measures of leaning and memory on visuo-spatial tasks may be affected by visual\nability, we correlated performance in the Morris Water Maze with the visual acuity of each\nstrain. We found that visual acuity was significantly correlated (r = -0.998) with the latency to\nfind the platform in the Morris Water Maze. This suggests that the visual ability of each strain is\na confounding variable in visuo-spatial learning and that visual acuity, rather than spatial\nmemory capability, may account for some of the strain differences in mice in the Morris Water\nMaze."}}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44-split1-split2", "patch": {"abstract": "At short cue-target onset asynchronies, irrelevant cues can “capture” attention, resulting in a response benefit when they cue the location of a upcoming target, and incurring a response cost when they do not. However, participants can selectively filter task irrelevant cues if they differ predictably from task-relevant stimuli on some salient dimension such as color (Folk, Remington & Johnston, 1992) or spatial location (Ishigami, Klein, & Christie, 2009). This selective filter, termed an “attentional control setting”, has been shown to modulate the early facilitative effects of cueing, but not the inhibitory aftereffects (Often referred to as Inhibition of Return or “IOR”; Pratt & McAuliffe, 2002). In the present study, a manipulation similar to that of Ishigami et al (2009) was used in order to induce a spatial ACS in participants, and responses to central arrow targets were used to measure the cueing effects of irrelevant non-informative cues. Evidence also suggests that IOR can be separated into two semi-distinct “flavors”; one perceptual and the other motoric (Taylor & Klein, 2000) but activation of the motor system does not seem to affect expression of the perceptual flavor (Chica, Taylor, Lupianez & Klein, 2010). By mixing saccadic and manual target trials within blocks and varying the relative probability of those trials it was expected that participants might invoke their perceptual flavor of processing, shutting down the oculomotor system and eliminating saccade-measured IOR. Results are discussed with focus on implications for spatial attentional control and the divergent typologies of IOR."}}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "17-split3-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Hypothalamic Lesions Block the Arttigortadal Action of\n                                          Melatonin.", "authors_raw": "B. Rusak", "abstract": "In hamsters an intact pineal gland is necessary for the anti-\n                               gonadal effect of exposure to short photoperiods.             The pineal product,\n                               melatonin,has     been shown to produce gonadal regression          in short\n                               photoperiods     and to block gonadal regrowth in long photoperiods;           it\n                               is presumed that melatonin is a prime pineal antigonadotrophin.\n                               Lesions of the suprachiasmatic        nuclei (SCN) of the hypothalamus\n                               eliminate many circadian rhythms including that of pineal melatonin\n                               formation; these same lesions prevent testicular           regression    in short\n                               photoperiods.      I have suggested four possibilities         for the mechanism\n                               of this effect;     the simplest of these states that SCN destruction\n                               prevents pineal melatonin formation, thereby lowering circulating\n                               melatonin levels and permitting        the testes to remain functional.          On\n                               this hypothesis,      replacement of melatonin in SCN-lesioned hamsters\n                               should exert an antigonadal       action.     This hypothesis was tested by\n                               regressing    the testes of hamsters in short photoperiods           and using\n                               melatonin to block regrowth when returned to a long photoperiod.\n                               Melatonin blocked regrowth in intact hamsters but had no effect on\n                               SCN-lesioned hamsters.        This hypothesis is therefore       ruled out,\n                               leaving three choices:        i) The critical     factor is not the level of\n                               melatonin but the rhythm of melatonin.            ii) The lesions increase\n                               gonadotropin levels independently of the pineal.             iii) The lesions\n                               destroy the site of melatonin uptake so that it cannot influence\n                               pituitary    function.\n\n24.     A. Randich - The Role of the Pituitary-Adrenal           Axis in the lJCS\n                                            Pre-exposure Phenomenon.\n\nExperiments tested the hypothesis that the pituitary-adrenal\n       \\lff\\V\n            _x.A\n                       1\n                        •\n                           /\n                               system mediates the decremental effect of prior exposure to an aver-", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 17-split3-split1 at: '23. B. Rusak'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Abstraction of Spatio-T~mporal ~}~5!~re.", "authors_raw": "J. Barresi &D. Dalzell", "abstract": "A chain of 80 dot patterns was constructed by recursively\n      applying a distortion      rule to the pattern constructed         from the pre-\n      vious application     of the rule.   When these patterns        are presented\n      visually    for 300 msec each in their \"natural\"        order, they appear as\n      a continuously changing shape.        Surprisingly,     subjects'     ability to\n      identify patterns     from the sequence is no better when the patterns\n      are presented in their \"natural\"       order than when the sequence of 80\n      is presented randomly.       However, both of these conditions yield much\n      better performance than does a sequence of 80 entirely              random\n      patterns.     These and other results suggest that resemblance rather\n      than continguity    is the first associative       principle.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25-split1-split2 at: '29. J. Barresi &D. Dalzell'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Constraints on Learning: A Re-evaluation.", "authors_raw": "J. Willner", "abstract": "Although rats preferentially       condition to gustatory cues when\n      illness  is the reinforcer,     the argument that this reflects     a specific\n      learning ability    selected for by evolution is not especially       compell-\n      ing. Data from experiments on blocking and second-order conditioning\n      which employed nongustatory       CS's will be described which suggest\n      that the constraint     is on the expression of learning,     rather than on\n      the learning i tse If.     The relevance of these findings to general\n      theories of learning will be discussed.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25-split1-split2 at: '30. J. Willner'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "25-split1-split2-split3", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Visual Sensitization with a Large, Flashed Annulus.", "authors_raw": "J. Raymond", "abstract": "The addition of light to the visual system usually acts to\n      desensitize     detection mechanisms.    In this experiment, specific\n      stimulus conditions are defined that make an exception to this general\n      rule.    The results show that the addition of a large, flashed annulus\n      leads to greater sensitivity      in detecting a central test spot than\n      when the annulus is not presented.        The characteristics  of this sensi-\n      tization    effect suggest that different     neural mechanisms are involved\n      than those thought to be mediating Westheimer spatial sensitization\n      effects.\n\n10.\n\n32.   R. Klein,    J. Day, &R. Armitage - Cognitive and Rhythmic Control\n                                          of Hemisphere Activation.\n\nThe two cerebral hemispheres of the human brain are special-\n      ized for the performance of different      cognitive processes.    Meta-\n      control refers to mechanisms that influence which hemisphere is\n      activated and therefore     likely to take control of processing in a\n      given situation.     Two types of metacontrol are distinguished:       one\n      is transient   and cognitive,    the other is rhythmic and automatic.\n      Cognitive metacontrol has been demonstrated in split-brain        subjects,\n      but its elicitation    in normal subjects has been unclear.      Rhythmic\n      metacontrol has been hypothesized but not clearly demonstrated.          We\n      will present clear-cut     evidence for both types of metacontrol pro-\n      cesses in the normal intact brain.\n33.   N. Bennett    - Some Aspects of Communal Pup-Rearing     i~the   Timber Wolf.\n\nCommunal pup-rearing   is a major co-operative  feature of pack\n      social behavior in the timber wolf (Canis lupus) which has not yet\n      been studied in detail.       It is known that in the pack,adults   assist\n      both mothers and pups in a variety of ways. The present study exam-\n      ined some aspects of pup-rearing      in a pack of 12 captive timber\n      wolves and found that assistance      to mothers was rendered in a highly\n      selective    manner whereas all pups were cared for equally and without\n      distinction.     In addition an analysis of the social relationship\n      between pairs of pack members suggests that little       aggression occurs\n      during the breeding season between future mothers and their helpers.\n\n34.   R. Sutherland    - Epithalamic Reinforcement   System:    Why is the\n                         Habenular Complex?\n\nThe reinforcing   consequences of electrical   stimulation   at\n      sites in the habenular complex and adjacent structures        were inves-\n      tigated in 44 rats.     Electrode locations in the stria medullaris,\n      habenular nuclei and", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 25-split1-split2 at: '31. J. Raymond'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8-split2-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Effects of a Third Choice on Cooperation\n                                   • in a Mixed-Motive Game.", "authors_raw": "G. Tower &J. Barresi", "abstract": "The generally low amount of cooperative       (30%) as opposed to\n      competitive   (70%) responding in the two-choice, prisoner's         dilemma\n      game may be due to the meanings attached to the restricted           choices\n      provided by the game. In the present study a third choice was added\n      whose mere presence changed the \"meaning\" of the cooperative and\n      competitive choices.      Three \"meanings\" of the cooperative choice·were\n      compared - sharing, self-interest,       and altruism.    The sharing condi-\n      tion produced the most cooperative responding (sharing=           56%, self-\n      interest   = 33%, altruism=     36%). The self-interest     condition pro-\n      duced the most competitive responding (sharing=          25%, self-interest\n      = 43%, altruism=      35%). Finally,   the altruism condition produced\n      the most third (contract)      choice responding (sharing=     19%, self-\n      interest   = 24%, altruism=     29%).\n\n14.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split2-split2 at: 'G. Tower'"}
{"year": 1978, "entry_id": "8-split2-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Effects of Three Preprograrnm!d Strategies\n                                     on Cooperative responding in a Three-Choice\n                                     Mixed-Motive Game.", "authors_raw": "R. Baxter &J. Barresi", "abstract": "Cooperative responding in the prisoner's        dilennna game has\n      been increased from a free play 30% to 80% when a preprogrammed tit-\n      for-tat    strategy is used by the \"partner\".        This strategy involves\n      responding on each trial with the real subject's          previous response.\n      Thus, the subject is rewarded for a cooperative response (i.e.,            with\n      cooperation)      and punished for a competitive response (i.e.,      with\n      competition).       The effectiveness    of this and two other preprogrammed\n      strategies     were compared in a three-choice      mixed-motive game. The\n      results    of the experiment suggest that the reward and punish strategy\n      of tit-for-tat      is more effective    in producing cooperation than other\n      more \"altruistic\"      strategies.     Furthermore, in the three-choice\n      game this strategy elicited         95% cooperation in the last 30 of the 120\n      trials.\n\n5.\n\n15.        P. Nau - The Investigation      of Objects           by Rats Placed          in a Novel\n                                           Environment.\n\nAn exploring rat spends a great deal of time examining the\n                                  objects it encounters.    Each object is visited       repeatedly and con-\n                                  tacted with the snout until,      after several such visits,      the rat will\n                                  have had experience with its entire surface.         Evidence will be pre-\n                                  sented to show that the location of these contacts,           and hence this\n                                  progression   across the object's     surface, is highly systematic,\n                                  depending both on the object's       physical characteristics     and on the\n                                  location of previous contacts.\n\n16.        C. Barnes - Spatial     Memory Deficits        in Senescent          Rats.\n\nMiddle-aged and senescent rats' ability      to acquire and retain a\n                                  task which forced the use -of a spatial    strategy for its solution was\n                                  examined. Although both groups improved the accuracy with which they\n                                  located the goal tunnel, the older rats never attained the same level\n                                  of proficiency   as their young counterparts.      Furthermore, when given", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split2-split2 at: 'R. Baxter'"}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "8-split4-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "More Quantitative Properties\n                                                                                      of Anxiety.", "authors_raw": "W. J. Jacobs, J. Hill-Flewelling, and V. LoLordo", "abstract": "Three expei'iments investigated      the effects     of a CER procedure\n                     (Estes and Skinner, 1941) upon appetitively-motivated             wheel rwming.       Rats\n                     received the onset of a tone as a conditional          stimulus and the presentation\n                     of a brief electric        shock as the unconditional    stimulus.      Experiment 1 found\n       <0            that, unlike the 1,·ell-documented suppression        of an appetitively-motiv2ted\n       ~             lever-press    response,     the current preparation   produced acceleration       of\n                     appetitively-motivated        wheel running in the presence of the conditioned\n                     stimulus.     Facilitation      was not observed in the Random CS or No CS control\n                     conditions.      Experiment 2 demonstrated that conditioned          facilitation   is a - -------                                                                                                   ---------·· - 6.\n      function of the intensity  of the UCS: the more intense the UCS, the greater\n      the facilitation.   In Experiment 3, each rat was trained both to run in a wheel\n      and to press a lever for food reinforcement.       It was found that the rats\n      increased their rate of wheel running, but suppressed their rate of lever\n      pressing in the presence of the conditional     stimulus.   The results are discussed\n      in the context of Dickinson and Pearce's    recent (1977) model of conditioned\n      suppression.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split4-split2 at: '14. W. J. Jacobs'"}
{"year": 1980, "entry_id": "8-split4-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The Malheur Swallows: A Simple Field Experiment\n                                   Relatedtoflight    ~-lechanisms.", "authors_raw": "J. ~!ates and P. Paton", "abstract": "Lifting the wings of captive Cliff Swallows, Petrochelidon\n      pyrrhonota,   we triggered  a fluttering  of the body and tail.     Onset and\n      termi11ation of the flutter   occurred at fixed wing angles.      Autonomous action\n      of mechanisms underlying the flutter     may drive the fluttering    of birds\n      voluntarily   holding their wings up and back from their bodies.\n\n16.   P. Dodd.    The Response-Reinforcer       Relation:     A Pigeon's   Eye View.\n\nEach presentation     of a red response key ended with a food\n      presentation   either following t1,o responses separated by at least 10 sec\n      (a DRL schedule) or folJowing a 10sec response-free        period (a DROschedule).\n      A white side key was shown next and ended with response-dependent        food\n      folloHing one schedule and a timeout following the other.         Three pigeons\n      responded differentially      following the DRL and DROschedules,    but not simply\n      according to the schedule duration,       numbers of responses or even the time\n      between a response and its consequence.\n\n17.   G. Eskes.    Func;tio~w.l Aspects an<l Neural Control        of Daily Cycles of Male\n                   Sexual Performance.\n\nThe circadian    and neural mechanisms important for the functional\n      organization    of reproductive     behavior in the male golden hamster were examined.\n      It was found that males shoh' a diurnal rhythm of sexual behavior;                 latencies   to\n      copulate and ejaculate       were shorter in the dark phase, a time that coincides\n      with the female period of sexual receptivity.             The integrity     of the supra-\n      chiastmatic    nuclei of the anterior       hypothalamus appears necessary for this\n      rhythm.     SCN lesions eliminated      the rhyt~n in performance without interferring\n      with the ability      of the w1imal to copulate.        In contrast,     the medial preoptic\n      area (MPOA)is essential        for normal copulatory performance;           in those animals\n      that continued to copulate,        after MPOAlesions the circadian           modulation of\n      sexual behavior remained intact.           The regulation    of sexual behavior by these\n      structures    cons ti tut.es a useful model for the interaction         of circadian    and other\n      neural systems in the control of behavioral            expression.\n\nThe significance     of this rhythm is being tested by examrnrng the\n      ability  of arrhythmic SD-lesioned          males or males in different   circadian\n      phases to copulate in a mating situation          in which they must compete for\n      access to a single receptive        female.    If the rhythm of copulatory", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 8-split4-split2 at: '15. J. ~!ates and P. Paton'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "19-split1-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Identification, starting at the top Viewing the same object from different angles results in different retinal images. We are able to recognize these different visual inputs as the same object This is known as object constancy. When line drawings of familiar objects are presented to subjects, the time to name the object increases linearly for objects rotated up to 120 degrees from the vertical. This function suggests that during object identification, the input is being normalized to the upright, until a match is found in memory. Biederman (1989) has suggested that the effects of orientation are due to finding the top of the object In order to test this hypothesis, valid and invalid precues of object orientation will be presented prior to the display of the object to be named. If the effect of orientation is in finding the top, as Biederman has suggested then the valid cue condition should show less of an effect of orientation than the invalid cue.", "authors_raw": "Jeffrey Hamm and Paddy McMullen", "abstract": "23.   Dennis Phillips and Paula Tallal\n      Temporal auditory processing deficits in developmental dysphasia\n             The most comprehensive, if somewhat controversial, account of developmental dysphasia\n             is Tallal's. Briefly, she argues that the speech reception deficit is due to an auditory\n             temporal processing disorder: the disordered mechanism is thought to be cortical in locus,\n             and to affect the perception of both linguistic and nonlinguistic sounds. The most\n             compelling demonstration of the impairment lies in the inability of these children to\n             discriminate the order of two brief (75 ms) tone pulses if the duration of the silent period\n             between them is less than 100 to 300 ms, a task which normals perform with near-perfect\n             accuracy for inter-stimulus intervals as small as O ms. The intended connotation of the\n             term \"temporal processing\" is, however, far from clear in Tallal's published work. By the\n             same token, nothing is known about the generality of any deficit across auditory\n             perceptual dimensions that have their origins in different forms of time-related or time-\n             dependent sound processing. In this talk, I will present sketches of two of a long series\n             of experiments, based on modem auditory neuroscience, that we have planned to address\n             these lacunae.\n\n- 11 -\n\n24.   A.I. Cohen, D. Dunphy, M. Lamoureux and B. Frankland\n      Battery includes music\n            Musical stimuli engage a variety of sensory, perceptual and cognitive processes. Yet,\n            none of the numerous neuropsychological tests in existence examines these processes.\n            Drawing upon tasks used in research in the psy", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 19-split1-split1 at: '22. Jeffrey Hamm'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28-split1-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Pigeon umwelt: Is a picture worth a thousand words? Operant chamber techniques have yielded a diversity of information regarding various facets of pigeon vision. More recently complex photographic material in the form of slides, depicting sundry categories such as trees, cats, cars and people, has been employed in category discrimination tasks. In such studies the assumption is presumably made that the photographs are perceived by the Pigeons as representative of the three-dimensional objects or scenes that they depict Are there enough salient dimensions present in a slide photograph to allow it to function as a suitable representation of the Pigeons environment and, if so, could it be used to explore the complexity of the Pigeon Umvelt? Some recent work in this area will be presented.", "authors_raw": "P.D. Cole", "abstract": "- 14 -", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28-split1-split2 at: '32. P.D. Cole'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "28-split1-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "The effect of quipazine • a serotonin agonist, on the circadian rhythm\n       of locomotor activity and the serotonin level in the brain of the house\n       cricket (Acheta domesticus L.)\n             The rhythm of locomotor activity in insects results from the function of an endogenous\n             pacemaker system and entrainment of this system by environmental factors (light)\n             changing during the 24 hour period. The aim of this study was to examine the role of\n             serotonin (5-HT) in the regulation of circadian rhythms. Results obtained indicated that\n             the circadian system controlling locomotor acitvity rhythms in the house cricket is\n             composed of two oscillators which act jointly (in DD - constant dark),or separately (in\n             LL constant light) and that 5-HT takes part in the regulation of overt rhythmicity. In LL,\n             injections of quipazine affected the phase of two components of the rhythm or changed\n             one of the components present in activity into the second one (changes of the rhythm\n             period). In DD, quipazine administrations caused only phase shifts of the rhythm which\n             were phase-dependent Quizapine injections decreased also the 5-HT concentration in the\n             cricket brain which may be a result of a negative feedback process triggered by direct or\n             indirect activation of 5-HT receptors.", "authors_raw": "Elzbieta Pyza", "abstract": "34.    Patricia A. McMullen\n       Symmetry and orientation normalization in the recognition of\n       naturalistic stimuli\n             Tarr and Pinker (Psychological Science, 1990) showed that mental rotation is used in\n             recognizing misoriented assymetrical patterns, but not symmetrical patterns, using novel\n             stimuli. They inferred that object-centered representations code spatial relations among\n             features on one dimension only. The generality of this finding was assessed by\n             retrospectively analysing three experiments' worth of latencies to name misoriented\n             drawings of common objects. For the first block of trials, symmetrical and asymmetrical\n             objects showed equivalent effects of orientation between upright and 120°. In contrast,\n             effects of orientation were significantly greater for asymmetrical than symmetrical objects\n             over three subsequent blocks of trials. These results are consistent with the hypothesis\n             that object-centered representations code object features along a single dimension.\n\nNameera Akhtar and Philip J. Dunham\n       Comprehension strategies of young children\n             Previous research (Shatz, 1978) has indicated that young children are biased to respond to\n             language with action. This study attempted to replicate this finding in a group of 64 24\n             month olds. These children heard 30 prerecorded sentences differing in syntax presented", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 28-split1-split2 at: '3 3. Elzbieta Pyza'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34-split1-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Integration of kinematic information in emotional judgments Adults rated the happiness/sadness of 36 short film excerpts of a person whose facial and body movements varied from excerpt to excerpt. There were three different facial expression (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by mouth position and eye focus) and three different body movement patterns (sad, neutral and happy as reflected by position and rate of limb movement) combined factorially. The influence of both sources of information on ratings was highly significant and in the manner predicted. Thus, emotional meaning can be communicated by multidimensional kinematic information. Results are compared with those from preschool children.", "authors_raw": "Natasha Harvey", "abstract": "• 16-", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 34-split1-split2 at: '38. Natasha Harvey'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "34-split1-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Discrimination of human male odours by rats is not influenced by the relatedness of the urine donors Rats can be trained in an olfactometer to discriminate between the urine odours of MHC congenic rats and mice. They learn these discriminations quickly and remember the information from one daily session to another. Such results indicate that constant odour cues are used to discriminate between these urines (Schellinck, Brown and Slotnick, Anim,Learn,Behay,.      in press). To determine if rats can discriminate between human urines, we tested five Long-Evans rats in a go/no discrimination in an olfactometer. Discriminable differences were present in urines from monozyotic twins, dizogotic twins, siblings and unrelated males. Analysis of the erros to criterion over eight 200 trial sessions indicated that the four human urine odour discriminations were equally difficult to learn. Although all test rats were able to discriminate the urine pairs to a criterion of 90% correct within one or more of the eight sessions, only one of the rats was able to maintain this level of performance from session to session. The other four subjects either relearned the discrimination within a session or performed at chance levels on subsequent sessions. When the ability of rats to learn to discriminate between the urine odours of rats, mice and humans is compared, it appears that constant cues are being used to discriminate between the urine odours of rats and mice whereas this is not the case for hwnan urine odours.", "authors_raw": "Heather Schellinck and Richard E. Brown", "abstract": "40.   Maria Patriquin\n      The effects of play structures on infant initiated imitative play\n            Nonverbal social exchanges or interactions are crucial steps in infants becoming full\n            partners in a social communicative context. Studies in the area have shown that\n            imitation is a key element in the development of coordinated joint attention. It is argued\n            that the period in which infants are sensitive to the imitative structures is at 24 month of\n            age. The present study observed 30 nine month olds to investigate whether infants are\n            sensitive to the imitative structures of play at this age. Subjects were randomly assigned\n            to three treatment groups, Synchronous-Contingent, Asynchronous-Contingent and\n            Noncontingent. Infants in the Synchronous-Contingent group engaged in more imitative\n            play while the infants in the other two treatment groups engaged in more parallel play.\n            Being imitated actually encouraged the infants to engage in more reciprical imitative play.\n            Although not statistically different, the Noncontingent infants displayed a tendency to\n            engage in less of bo", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 34-split1-split2 at: '39. Heather Schellinck and Richard E. Br'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42-split1-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Psychological sequelae of carbon monoxide poisoning and their", "authors_raw": "John McNulty", "abstract": "treatment with hyperbaric oxygen One of the most frequently observed symptoms of carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning is \"mental\" or \"cognitive\" impairment. These symptoms often persist even when other medical and neurological symptoms have disappeared. The standard treatment for coexposure is hyperbaric oxygen. If symptoms are minor, or exposure time is short, patients are sometimes treated only with oxygen at normal atmospheric pressure or are not treated at all. There are, however, \"hints\" that failure to treat even mild cases may result in relatively permanent neuropsychological deficits. Some preliminary data and suggestions for research on the problem will be presented.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 42-split1-split2 at: '46. John McNulty'"}
{"year": 1991, "entry_id": "42-split1-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Cholinergic and aminergic inputs from the mesopontine area to the basal forebrain and thalamus: A hypothesis for brainstem involvement in cortical arousal Researchers of behavioral states have investigated the role of specific direct and indirect cholinergic inputs of the basal forebrain and mesopontine tegmental cholinergic areas in the regulation of waking and sleep. This study examines the contribution of tegmental cholinergic, serotonergic and dopaminergic cell groups in modulating the activity of both thalamic and basal forebrain neurons in cortical arousal. Following multiple injections of both FITC beads into the basal forebrain, and Fluorogold into the thalamus, alternate sections from the forebrain and brainstem were processed for immunohistochemistry with antibodies to visualire cholinergic and aminergic neurons. Injection sites were plotted and alternate brainstem sections were surveyed for the presence of triple labeled neurons.", "authors_raw": "BrunoJ. Losier and KazueSemba", "abstract": "- 19 -\n\n48.        B.W. Frankland\n           Non-temporal and temporal effects on the perception of pattern in\n           sequential stimuli\n                 The analysis of the perception and/or cognition of pattern in sequentially presented\n                 stimuli is constrained by non-temporal and temporal factors that limit the number and\n                 type of possible temporal patterns. This work will discuss the effects of such constraints\n                 on the perception of pattern in the contour (the pattern of up and down) in sequentially\n                 presented tones. In particular, a brief review of the role of tonality (essentially, a non-\n                 temporal constraint) and the role of short term memory (essentially a temporal constraint)\n                 on the perception of pattern in contour will be presented.\n--------\n49.        Marcia Ozier and Andrea Blumenthal\n           Mood and memory: Open your Ears and close your eyes\n                 Usually we remember better if given a category cue to the meaning of the word we are\n                 seeking in memory than if we are given an alphabetic one. That finding reverses if we are\n                 induced into depression before trying to remember. Induced depression results in a\n                 dramatic decrease in the potency of category cues to meaningful words. Previous reports\n                 have been based upon an experimental design in which words were presented visually and\n                 test cues presented visually. The current experiment asked whether the decrease in potency\n                 of category cues under induced depression would occur if presentation and test were\n                 auditory rather than visual. The loss of meaning as a function of induced depression\n                 seems to be spec", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from 42-split1-split2 at: '47. BrunoJ. Losier and KazueSemba'"}
{"year": 1995, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Beyond Immediate Self-Interest: Or, What Good Comes From Having A Theory of Mind?", "authors_raw": "John Barresi, Carol Selig and Chris Moore", "abstract": "The purpose of this research was to investigate the early development of prudence and altruism involving future situations. The study tested the hypothesis that these are interrelated phenomena and that both should develop at approximately four years of age. Using a modified delay of gratification paradigm, 3- to 5-year-olds were tested on their ability to forgo a current desire for some stickers in order to further their own future interests or the current or future interests of a research assistant. Results showed that in current situations, altruism was unrelated to age. However, prudence and altruism involving the future situations were correlated with one another and with age. Children under four years of age performed significantly less well than the older children on the prudence task (F(l, 49) = 15.75; p<.001) and on the altruism task involving future situations, (F(l, 49) = 33.24; p<.001). Between three and five years, prudence and altruism showed a similar developmental pattern with performance increasing at age four. In Defense of Defenses: A User's Guide to the Psyche '            'FW. '(L7 Michael Wm. MacGregor and Karina Davidson U_;-1ll)\"1, \"\"1;fJ &.lkt             Two studies were conducted to determine coder reliability and the reliability of 2_j_ defense mechanisms assessed using the Defense-Q, an idiographic ecsort measure. In ~~ The first, study 30 subjects who had undergone an interpersonallysiressful structured interview were rated by ten trained coders for the use of 25 defense mechanism. Study ~~                two was similar to study one except that a new set of thirty interviews were rated by ten newly trained coders. The average coder reliability was .64 in study one (range .53 to .67) and .75 in study two (range .63 to .76) across all 25 defense mechanisms. il~~t;,__         Reliability coefficients for each defense mechanism ranged from .15 (reaction formation and displacement) to .87 (humour and acting out) in study one, and from .28 (undoing) ~r- f-','4-¼X,~ to .92 (humour) in study two. These results indicate that defense mechanisms can be reliably assessed using a standardized clinician-guided q-sort technique. The applications of these results to the assessment of normal and abnormal personality will", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split1-split1 at: 'T19. Beyond Immediate Self-Interest: Or,'"}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split2-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Becoming conscious of 'consciousness':               Notes for a history of an important psychological concept", "authors_raw": "John Barresi", "abstract": "During the 17th century the term of 'consciousness' suddenly appeared as a psychological concept. Since then this concept has become increasingly important both in the foundations and later developments of 'mental philosophy' and scientific psychology. Although during the heyday of behaviourism it diminished in importance, interest in consciousness has been revived again toward the end of this century. In the present talk I will look at the origins of the use of this term, its ancient sources in Greek and Latin, its major 'discovery' in Descartes, and its later development in the works of Cudworth, Locke, Leibniz, Hume, and others in the late 17th and early 18th century. 1997 In-House Convention                                                                    11", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split2-split1 at: \"T20. Becoming conscious of 'consciousnes\""}
{"year": 1997, "entry_id": "T16-split2-split1-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Attention (to the moving line): \"Where you lead, I will follow\".", "authors_raw": "Raymond M. Klein & Jeff P. Hamm", "abstract": "When a line is presented in the vicinity of a recent luminance change (peripheral cue) it is\n      perceived to be drawn over time away from its \"cued\" end even though the line is actually\n      presented all at once. This study was designed to determine if attention, exogenously\n      attracted to the cue, would come under the exogenous control of this illusory motion and\n      follow the drawn line from its cued end to its terminus. Each trial began with the display of\n      4 small squares at the corners of an imaginary square centered about fixation. After 750 ms\n      one of the 4 squares brightened briefly (50ms) in the cued conditions. Simultaneous with\n      the offset of the cue a horizontal line was presented joining the upper or lower boxes.\n      After 100 ms one of the 4 squares was transformed into a horizontal or vertical rectangle\n      for 150 ms. The subject's task was to make a horizontal/ vertical decision as rapidly as\n      possible. The different events (cues, lines and targets) were combined factorially so that\n      neither cues nor lines were informative about target location. Responses to targets at an\n      uncued location that was at the end of an illusorilly drawn line were as fast as to targets in\n      the neutral and \"valid\" conditions, and much faster than the remaining invalid conditions,\n      strongly suggesting that attention follows the motion in the \"shooting line\" illusion.\n\nT22. Integration of Environmental and Intentional Information within the\n     Saccadic Programming System: A Computational Perspective.\n      Sol Simpson, Thomas Trappenberg, & Raymond Klein\n\nSaccadic reaction time (SRT) is influenced by both the observer's environment (exogenous\n      factors) and intentions (endogenous factors). To investigate these two SRT contributions,\n      the time interval between the removal of a fixation point and the presentation of a peripheral\n      target (the Gap Paradigm) as well as the probability of a target appearing at a given location\n      were varied. It was hypothesized that if endogenous information affects SRT within the\n      same functional layer of the saccadic programming system that is responsible for\n      exogenous control (the superior colliculus), the effect of target location information would\n      be significantly larger in conditions where the fixation stimulus was removed prior to target\n      presentation than in conditions where the fixation stimulus remained present following\n      target onset. This interaction was obtained with saccadic but not manual RTs, suggesting\n      that the lateral inhibition of fixation cells in the rostral pole (RP) of the superior colliculus\n      (SC) onto the saccade related cells of the SC may memate the effects of both exogenous\n      and endogenous inputs on SRT. This presentation will attempt to explain this interaction", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split2-split1 at: 'T21. Attention (to the moving line): \"Wh'"}
{"year": 2000, "entry_id": "T16-split1-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "An investigation of the phonological processing in Chinese language with ERPs", "authors_raw": "Jingtian Wang and John Connolly", "abstract": "Two unique features of Chinese language draw much attention and interest in psycholinguistics. The\n       first is that Chinese written language is pictographic. There is an opaque relationship between the\n       pronunciation and physical appearance of a Chinese character. For example, homophones have the exact\n       same pronunciation but completely different script feature and meaning. This opacity of the script-to-\n       sound relationship has led to a widespread assumption that readers of Chinese can arrive at the mental\n       lexicon by identifying a whole character visually, without any involvement with phonological coding.\n       The issue of whether there is phonological code involved in Chinese reading was investigated with the\n       recording of ERPs. The other specific feature of Chinese language is that it is a tone language. Most\n       Chinese characters consist of monosyllables with an affiliated lexical tone and the tonality of a\n       monosyllable is lexically meaningful. Though the perception of tone plays a major role in Chinese\n       speech comprehension, little is known about its underlying electrophysiological basis. What's more, in\n       behavioral studies, there is a major issue of whether tone perception is of importance in Chinese reading\n       comprehension since there are more errors in tone discrimination tasks during Chinese reading. My\n       future experiments will mainly focus on the above issues with the recording of ERPs, the measurement\n       of brain electrical activity that is time-locked to the underlying linguistic processing.\n\nT20.    Magnetic Resonance in Psychiatry\n\nFrank P MacMaster, Shakeela Khan, Vivek Kusumakar\n\nIn reference to the invention of the stethoscope, P.A. Piorry remarked \"If this method had only a quarter\n        of the utility attributed to it. . .it would still be one of the most precious discoveries of medicine\". The\n        same can be said of magnetic resonance (MR). MR technology offers exciting insight into neurobiology,\n        and the main modalities and their application will be reviewed here. MR is based on the application of a\n        magnetic field and its modulation with a radio-frequency pulse. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)\n        offers insight into regional morphology. Magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS) offers a non-invasive\n        brain biopsy of neurochemistry. Functional MRI (fMRI) offers a window into brain function via\n        regional brain activation and oxyhemoglobin and deoxyhemoglobin exchange. Diffusion tensor imaging\n        (DTI) tracts white matter coherence and will be especially use", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T16-split1-split1 at: 'T19. An investigation of the phonologica'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Using Taste Reactivity to Measure Shifts in the Palatability of Conditioned Taste Cues", "authors_raw": "Catherine A. Forestell and Vincent M. LoLordo", "abstract": "Tastes become more preferred after they have been paired with sugar reinforcement in a classical\n       conditioning paradigm. The mechanism involved in the formation of conditioned taste preferences is\n       not clear. It is possible that conditioned preferences occur because animals learn to expect calories upon\n       consumption of the taste cue. Alternatively, the conditioning procedure may produce an increase in the\n       palatability of the taste cue. Typically the taste reactivity test is used to assess the palatability of tastes.\n       This test involves measuring a rat's hedonic and aversive affective responses to oral infusions of taste\n       solutions. In this talk I will describe some of the taste reactivity experiments currently being conducted\n       in our laboratory to assess palatability shifts in conditioned taste cues.", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15-split3-split2 at: 'T21. Using Taste Reactivity to Measure S'"}
{"year": 2001, "entry_id": "T15-split3-split2-split2", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Challenges of running research in a large laboratory class: An animal experiment where the\n       researchers outnumber the animals by 30 to 1", "authors_raw": "Heather Schellinck(l), Ron Hoffman(!) and John MacDonald(2). (1) Department of Psychology\n       (2) Academic Computing Services", "abstract": "As part of the continuing evolution of the introductory psychology class (P 1001) into a laboratory class,\n       this past year an animal research project was incorporated into the curriculum. Eighteen mice were\n       assigned to either of two groups. Mice in the experimental group received caffeine in their drinking\n       water. The mice were then observed in an open field apparatus, and experimenters recorded several\n       behaviours. With over 600 potential experimenters, the logistics were challenging. In this talk, we\n       describe how live observations were combined with additional observations recorded on digital video\n       and presented over the internet. The preparations were not trivial, but the outcome was a success in\n       several ways.\n               'i\";,_.J_   ~\\,_ •. ,.......,,\n                                            \\\n\nT23.   Construction and Initial Validation of a Daily Version of the Fatigue Impact Scale (D-FIS)\n\nJohn Fisk and Susan Doble\n\nIntroduction: The Fatigue Impact Scale (FIS) has been developed as a symptom-specific profile\n       measure of health-related quality of life (HRQoL). Its item content reflects subjects' attribution of\n       problems to fatigue in the areas of physicaCcognftive, and psychosocial functioning. The FIS was\n       initially developed for cross-sectional studies of medical conditions in which fatigue is a chronic\n       symptom. Thus, it had not been designed to be a responsive measure of daily changes in fatigue. The\n       present study describes the development and initial validation study of an adaptation of the FIS for use\n       in conditions in which fatigue symptoms are of acute onset or have significant daily variation.\n       Methods: Items for the Daily F_MigueImpact Scale (D-FIS) were selected from the pool of original FIS\n       items with the aid of Rasclianalyses of existing data. The reduced, 18-item FIS was administered to a\n       sample of 93 subjects with flu-like illness, some of whom were followed for a 21-day period. Rasch\n       analyses were used to further reduce the scale to a minimum number of items that represented a\n       unidimensional measure of self-reported fatigue impact.\n       Results: The resulting 8-item D-FIS demonstrated good relations to ratings of other flu symptoms and\n       to general ratings of HRQoL. It also proved to be a responsive measure, demonstrating significant\n       reduction in fatigue impact for those subjects that were followed longitudinally. Moreover, subjective\n       ratings of fatigue impact were associated with work hours lost and estimated work productivity for those\n       subjects who did work for pay during", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T15-split3-split2 at: 'T22. Challenges of running research in a'"}
{"year": 2003, "entry_id": "T20-split1-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Investigating Spatial Biases in Face Perception", "authors_raw": "Jamesie Coolican, BSc. and Gail Eskes, Ph.D", "abstract": "We were interested in the reported left-sided perceptual bias in interpreting facial emotion and in\nfacial recognition. Our purpose was to replicate the reported bias in normal subjects and to\nexamine whether this phenomenon was related to global/holistic face processing per se. Twenty-\none undergraduate students participated in the study. In Study 1, subjects were shown chimeric\nfaces created by combining half of a smiling face and half of a neutral face. They were asked to\njudge which of two faces (smile on left vs smile on right side of the face) was \"happier\". Results\nshowed a strong bias for judging the face with the left-sided smile as happier. In a second\ncondition, the chimeric faces were inverted. The left-sided bias in emotion judgement remained,\nsuggesting this judgement was not based on global face processing. In Study 2, composite faces\nfrom the left or right side of a neutral face were created and the subjects were asked to identify\nwhich composite most nearly matched the original face. In this case, a significant (but smaller)\nleft-sided bias for matching a composite was seen. In addition, top faces were significantly more\nlikely to be judged as more similar to the original than bottom faces, suggesting the recognition\nprocess was related to vertical spatial position of the face as well. When the faces were inverted,\n\nvertical spatial position ceased to affect judgements, while the left-sided bias remained.\nImplications of these findings for neurocognitive models of face processing will be offered for\ndiscussion.\n\nT23)   How to Grow up and be normal: Lessons from the visual system and accenture. It\n       is not the variety or amount of early experience you have, it's the proportion that is\n       normal that makes good things happen.\n\nDonald Mitchell and Marc Jones\n\nAlthough a number of key features of the anatomical and physiological organization of the\ncentral visual pathways of higher mammals can be remarkably well developed at birth, others\nachieve their adult status more gradually. Nevertheless, even those characteristics that appear\nremarkably mature at birth, such as the segregated pattern of ocular dominance observed in the\ngranular layer of the visual cortex (area 17) of monkeys, as well as those that appear less\ndeveloped, can change in a dramatic fashion in response to abnormal visual input imposed\nduring documented sensitive periods in early postnatal life. The cortical changes induced by such\nselected early visual exposure can be accompanied by profound and long-standing visual\ndeficits. In this study we demonstrate that with respect to form vision, normal visual input is\nweighted far more strongly during development than is biased visual exposure such that 2 hours\nof normal visual exposure each day", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T20-split1 at: 'T22) Investigating Spatial Biases in Fac'"}
{"year": 2012, "entry_id": "T44-split1-split2-split1", "add": true, "presentation_type": "talk", "title": "Preliminary findings on the anti-epileptic and anti-anxiety effects of leaf-extracts of Chinese lantern tree (dichrostachys glomerata) in albino mice", "authors_raw": "Sunday A. Bisong & E. E. Osim", "abstract": "The leaves of the Chinese lantern tree (Dichrostachys  glomerata) are used as a spice and for medicinal purposes in Africa. The use of the leaf-extracts of this plant as an anti-epileptic drug in traditional medicine has left more questions than answers. The aim of this study was to test the anti-epileptic and anti-anxiety effects of the ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata in mice. Ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata (DG) were phytochemically analyzed and lethality studies done.  The phytochemical constituents of ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata included 10.60% alkaloids, 0.02% saponins, 2.55% tannins, 4.2% flavonoids, 2.16% cardiac glycosides, traces of moisture, ash, protein and some other reducing compounds and its LD50 was 13.5mg/kg, from which an ED50 of 4.5 mg/kg was calculated. To test anti-epileptic effect of the extract, seizures were induced in 20 mice using 80 mg/kg of penthylene tetrazol (PTZ).  Ten mice were given PTZ alone (80mg/kg, i.p.) and the other 10 mice given PTZ 30 minutes after pre-treatment with ethanol leaf-extract of D. glomerata (4.5mg/kg i.p.). The latency to onset of seizures was significantly longer and the duration of seizures was significantly shorter for mice treated with ethanol leaf-extract of D. glomerata + PTZ when compared to the PTZ alone group (p<0.001). The effect of the ethanol leaf-extract of D. glomerata on anxiety-like behaviour associated with epilepsy was studied in another 40 male albino mice, divided into four groups. Mice were either given 0.9% normal saline (0.1ml/10g body weight, i.p. - control), saline + PTZ , ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata (4.5mg/kg i.p.) alone or ethanol leaf-extracts of D. glomerata extract 30 minutes before giving PTZ. Anxiety-like behaviours were scored in the elevated plus maze (EPM), light/dark box (LD) and open field (OF) tests within 1 hour after drug treatment. The percentage time in the open arm of the EPM differed between drug treatments (F(3,36) = 3.872; p<0.05). It was lower in the PTZ treated mice (P< 0.05) than controls, but did not differ in the other groups of mice. The frequency of stretch attend postures (SAP) in the EPM test also differed between treatment groups (F(3,36) = 9.032; p< 0.001). SAPs were higher in the PTZ treated mice than in control (p< 0.001), DG and PTZ + DG treated mice (p< 0.01), but did not differ between control, DG and PTZ + DG treated mice. The number of head dips in the EPM also differed between the treatment groups (F(3,36) = 7.745; p< 0.001). PTZ treated mice did more head dips compared to controls (p< 0.05), DG alone (p< 0.01) and PTZ + DG treated mice (p< 0.01). The number of head dips were also lower in the PTZ + DG treated mice than control (p< 0.001). Percent time in the light in the LD test and the frequency of SAP did not dif", "parser_format": "split_from_parent_source", "confidence": "manual_split", "qa_flags": ["needs-split-review"], "note_extra": "Split from T44-split1-split2 at: 'T48)\\tPreliminary findings on the anti-ep'"}
